<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-03 00:20 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Opposition Party Triumphs in Mexico  </HEADLINE>
By JOHN RICE
<TEXT>
<P>
   MEXICO CITY (AP) -- It has been a long, hard wait for Mexico's
largest opposition party.
</P>
<P>
   After seeing its activists ignored, jailed, or derided as
anti-patriotic for generations, the National Action Party on Sunday
earned an electoral triumph behind its presidential candidate,
Vicente Fox.
</P>
<P>
   National Action -- known by its Spanish acronym PAN -- was founded
in 1939 under Manuel Gomez Morin, a leading Mexican intellectual
who opposed the big-government trends of the ruling party at that
era.
</P>
<P>
   From the start, the party appealed to religious, middle-class
Mexicans frustrated by the single-party domination of the
Institutional Revolutionary Party, or PRI, and to what were then
tough restrictions on the clergy.
</P>
<P>
   The ruling PRI of that era allowed other parties -- but not real
opposition. It used fraud and violence to crush foes at the polls.
</P>
<P>
   National Action was long associated in the popular mind with
Catholic lay groups -- stifling its development among other sectors
opposed to the PRI.
</P>
<P>
   Even this year, critics on the left accused it of of
''fascism,'' a reference to the conservative social views held by
many of its leaders and to a minor thread within the party that
dates back to the pro-fascist Sinarquista movement of the 1930s.
</P>
<P>
   But the PAN has always worked peacefully through the ballot box.
</P>
<P>
   And since the 1970s, it has increasingly become a party of
Mexico's growing urban middle classes and business sectors who were
less interested in the church than in a cleaner, smaller
government.
</P>
<P>
   The party's candidate this year, pragmatic businessman Vicente
Fox, has tried to broaden the party's base further, promising to
embrace even some leftist policies in efforts to make the party the
center of efforts to topple the PRI.
</P>
<P>
   Not until the late 1940s did National Action party manage to
elect its first few congressmen, after a legal battle. Not until
1952 did it bother even trying to seek the presidency.
</P>
<P>
   As late as 1961, it only ran for about half of the congressional
seats on offer. By the 1970s, it was winning more than 20 seats.
</P>
<P>
   Luis Alvarez, National Action's presidential candidate in 1958,
recalls seeing his campaign workers -- even himself -- jailed during
the campaign and some physically attacked.
</P>
<P>
   ''Some hotels refused to give us a room,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The party finished third in the crucial 1988 election. Many
thought the PRI stole the election from a leftist coalition headed
by Cuauhtemoc Cardenas.
</P>
<P>
   Seeking legitimacy, then-President Carlos Salinas forged a
tactical alliance with the PAN -- under Alvarez -- which pushed him
into a series of major political reforms that significantly opened
the electoral system.
</P>
<P>
   In 1989, the PAN won its first governorship. On Sunday, it won
its sixth state governorship, in Morelos, and it is part of a
coalition in another. Entering Sunday, the PAN also governed eight
of Mexico's 10 largest cities.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
