<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-03 00:30 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Storied History for Mexican Party  </HEADLINE>
By ISAAC A. LEVI
<TEXT>
<P>
   MEXICO CITY (AP) -- For seven decades the Institutional
Revolutionary Party has ruled Mexico, sometimes with a velvet glove
and at others with an iron fist, omnipresent and almost synonymous
with the government itself.
</P>
<P>
   But with Sunday's loss in the presidential election, the party
known as the PRI lost the chance to surpass the Soviet Communist
Party's record as the longest-ruling party of this century.
</P>
<P>
   The PRI began with many parallels to the Soviet party: tight
links to power, highly centralized leadership, a vast network of
local organizations and a sometimes violent allergy to opposition.
</P>
<P>
   But it has proved vastly more flexible in out co-opting or
neutralizing opponents, leading Peruvian novelist Mario Vargas
Llosa to call it ''the perfect dictatorship.''
</P>
<P>
   Even with its loss of the presidency, the PRI is likely to
remain a large force in Congress, while continuing to hold most
state governorships. But the party's greatest strength -- its
enormous nationwide network of grassroots organizations -- could
wind up squabbling for power if the party is decapitated by the
loss of the presidency.
</P>
<P>
   The PRI was always long on loyalty and short on ideology. It
veered from a home-brewed socialism under President Lazaro Cardenas
in the 1930s to privatizing free-marketeering under its last three
presidents.
</P>
<P>
   President Plutarco Elias Calles created the PRI in 1929 to
discipline the feuding factions who had won the Mexican Revolution
of 1910-1920 and end their often-violent struggles for power.
</P>
<P>
   The party brought stability to Mexico, then a poor, backward,
agrarian country left a shambles by a decade of civil war and
several years of political infighting.
</P>
<P>
   And stability was no small matter to a country that since
gaining independence in 1821 had seen a series of dictators,
invaders and musical-chair governments.
</P>
<P>
   The PRI also did something that few other Latin American nations
have done: keep the army completely out of politics for decades,
after gradually weaning the country away from its revolutionary
military leadership by 1946.
</P>
<P>
   Those benefits long came at the cost of a silenced opposition.
</P>
<P>
   The outgoing president would name a successor, and the party
would get him elected, by fraud when necessary.
</P>
<P>
   The PRI retained its strong base in the rural heart of Mexico.
But as Mexicans increasingly moved to the cities and became more
educated, they often turned to other parties.
</P>
<P>
   Bloody crackdowns on workers in the 1950s and on students in
1968 alienated many Mexicans on the left. And the economic crises
of the 1980s drove many middle class and wealthy Mexicans into
opposition.
</P>
<P>
   Austerity and a turn to free-market ideology started to trim the
party's ability to lavish election-era gifts and jobs.
</P>
<P>
   The party increasingly was forced to open the political system.
In 1989, for the first time, it admitted losing a governorship. By
1997, as its vote percentages declined election after election, it
lost its majority in Congress and the mayorship of most of Mexico's
largest cities.
</P>
<P>
   It responded with even greater, if inconsistent, attempts at
reform. President Ernesto Zedillo pushed the party into Mexico's
first open national presidential primary last November.
</P>
<P>
   But the goodwill it gained was not enough to push Francisco
Labastida to the PRI's traditional easy win over the opposition.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-07-03-00 0030 </TRAILER>
