<DOCNO> APW20000703.0009 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-03 00:31 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Rural Town Sticks With Ruling Party  </HEADLINE>
By JULIE WATSON
<TEXT>
<P>
   SANTA MARIA ACATEPEC, Mexico (AP) -- The people of this mountain
village nestled amid papaya and almond trees may not have
electricity, but they have a new bridge and the promise of cash.
</P>
<P>
   The ruling party has come through again, and this poor Indian
community gave thanks Sunday at the ballot box.
</P>
<P>
   ''They just gave us a bridge, and you have to support the people
who help you,'' said Juan Morales, a 56-year-old corn farmer who
voted at a roadside table while dogs nipped at fleas at his feet.
</P>
<P>
   Nearby, boys winged pebbles at voters. Men in sandals and women
with long braids gathered along the road, some talking in the
staccato Mixteco language. Some walked as long as three hours from
outlying areas to reach the poll.
</P>
<P>
   Despite debates across the country about who will win one of
Mexico's most hotly contested presidential elections, people in
these Oaxacan mountains overlooking the Pacific Ocean say they
already know: the ruling Institutional Revolutionary Party, or PRI,
which has governed Mexico for 71 years.
</P>
<P>
   That was indeed the case, at least in this town: Results
released late Sunday afternoon showed that 87 percent of the 530
residents of Santa Maria Acatepec and surrounding areas who cast a
ballot here voted for the PRI, while only 8 percent voted for the
leftist Democratic Revolution Party, and 3 percent for the
center-right National Action Party, the party of opposition
presidential candidate Vicente Fox.
</P>
<P>
   But on the national scale, Fox beat PRI presidential candidate
Francisco Labastida.
</P>
<P>
   Rarely does a village in this region go against the PRI, which
the party had hoped would make the difference in what has been
touted as Mexico's cleanest election.
</P>
<P>
   ''They say we vote for the PRI because we are poor and
uneducated, but we know what we are doing. It is the only party
that has helped us. We've never seen the other parties around
here,'' said Perfecto Hernandez Lopez, a 44-year-old coffee farmer.
</P>
<P>
   The PRI government's good will was in full force in the days
before the election in this town, which has no indoor plumbing or
street lights. To leave or arrive, residents have had to drive or
wade across a stream, which often swells to a raging river during
the rainy season and blocks the only dirt road to the village of
600 people.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, men carried a woman in labor on a cot across the
raging waters to get her to the clinic on the other side. Families
returning their dead to the village to be buried have had to hoist
coffins on their shoulders across the waist-deep waters.
</P>
<P>
   Two days before the elections, area officials clad in ''Vote for
the PRI'' T-shirts inaugurated a long-requested bridge with a live
brass band and dancers in cowboy hats. The bridge is unfinished,
but was still open for traffic. It is painted in the PRI colors --
the same as Mexico's red, white and green flag.
</P>
<P>
   The day after the bridge inauguration, officials called a
meeting at the town hall, also the polling place. Its walls were
emblazoned with posters of Labastida, but opposition
representatives made city workers take them down 15 minutes after
the polls opened. Labastida looked on from a poster across the
road.
</P>
<P>
   Authorities collected copies of the voter identification cards
after people cast their ballots. In return, each family will
receive about $300 in disaster relief funds for victims of an
earthquake, which destroyed a third of the village's homes nearly a
year ago.
</P>
<P>
   ''We don't know if the money comes from the PRI or from the
government, but we do know it comes from the government, which is
the PRI,'' said Nicolas Flores Lopez.
</P>
<P>
   In April, when polls showed Fox pulling roughly even with
Labastida, officials here distributed cement and other building
materials to the victims.
</P>
<P>
   What was left over is being stored in the yard of Flores Lopez.
PRI campaign posters are the only wall hangings in his home.
</P>
<P>
   ''I know there are opposition supporters among us, but they stay
hidden,'' said the 60-year-old farmer, laughing and showing his
five teeth.
</P>
<P>
   Certainly, there was little evidence of them at the polling
place, where PRI Mayor Ricardo Jinez stood watch over the process
wearing a large gold chain reading ''Rica'' around his neck.
</P>
<P>
   ''What do I do? Do I sign my name?'' a woman asked from behind
the white tarp covering the voting table.
</P>
<P>
   ''No,'' said another man waiting to vote. He pointed at the PRI
logo on the ballot. ''You just put an 'X' here.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
