<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-03 00:59 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Police investigate after boy nearly drowns on ride  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   BRISTOL, Conn. (AP) -Police and safety officials were
investigating after a 5-year-old boy nearly drowned on a water ride
at Lake Compounce amusement park.
</P>
<P>
   Devon M. Alexander, of Hartford, was in critical condition at
Connecticut Children's Medical Center Sunday night, a hospital
spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
   A Lake Compounce official said the boy could not swim and did
not wear one of the life vests provided for water rides. Lifeguards
searched for about 25 minutes before pulling Devon from the water.
</P>
<P>
   The accident occurred Saturday evening on the Lake Plunge, in
which riders take an inner tube down an enclosed slide that empties
into the park's lake, said park spokesman Richard Bisi.
</P>
<P>
   Bisi said the boy fell off his tube when it hit the water. When
he did not surface, the child's stepfather - who planned to follow
Devon down the slide on another tube - alerted park personnel, Bisi
said.
</P>
<P>
   A lifeguard who witnessed the incident jumped in the water and
called for more help, Bisi said. Within a minute, three other
lifeguards joined the search, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Two minutes later, 22 additional lifeguards began searching the
water, Bisi said. The park's emergency medical technicians arrived
within minutes and local and state police dive teams were
contacted, he said.
</P>
<P>
   The boy was recovered in about 25 minutes, more than 100 feet
from where he fell off his tube, Bisi said.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's very fair to say that the lifeguards and supervisors did
everything humanly possible to help and find this young boy,'' Bisi
said.
</P>
<P>
   Some investigators questioned the length of time it took to find
the boy.
</P>
<P>
   ''Lifeguards supposedly immediately went into the water to look
for the child,'' said Southington police Lt. Clifford Saucier. ''I
don't understand why the child wasn't found.''
</P>
<P>
   Devon ascended the ride with Damon Comeaux, identified by police
as his stepfather. The pair passed a sign that warned ''Strong
swimmers only. Deep water. Strong current,'' Bisi said, and the
attendant repeated the warning.
</P>
<P>
   The boy's stepfather assured the attendant that Devon could
handle the ride, Bisi said. The park doesn't require riders to wear
life preservers, but they are optional.
</P>
<P>
   On the dock, Comeaux told lifeguards that Devon couldn't swim,
Bisi said.
</P>
<P>
   Comeaux could not be reached for comment Sunday. A person
answering the phone at a Hartford number under his name declined to
comment. The family kept vigil at the boy's hospital bed throughout
the weekend.
</P>
<P>
   Along with a police investigation, Lake Compounce requested an
independent review by an aquatic safety company. The ride will
remain closed until those investigations are completed.
</P>
<P>
   The last fatal accident at Lake Compounce occurred in August,
when a 16-year-old ride attendant died after falling beneath a
moving ride. The park was cited by the Occupational Safety and
Health Administration in the death of Matthew Henne, of
Southington.
</P>
<P>
   In July 1981, 16-year-old Michele Johnson of Bristol died after
falling from a roller coaster as she stood and reached out the side
of the car.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-07-03-00 0059 </TRAILER>
