<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-03 00:59 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> School districts struggle to fill some teaching positions  </HEADLINE>
By The Associated Press	   While school is out, the hard work lies ahead for
superintendents looking to fill teaching positions.
<TEXT>
<P>
   School officials are busy shoring up their faculties in time for
next school year, advertising across New England at a time when
much of the nation is experiencing a shortage of teachers.
</P>
<P>
   ''It is getting increasingly difficult to find good
candidates,'' said Griswold Superintendent Elizabeth Osga.
</P>
<P>
   Griswold began advertising on the Internet for the first time
this year and finished its advertising for openings three months
earlier than normal. The district also expanded its outreach to job
fairs at universities.
</P>
<P>
   Killingly Superintendent Jules D'Agostino said he is confident
seven openings will be filled, but he expects it will be a struggle
to find a technology teacher and an eighth-grade French teacher.
</P>
<P>
   ''Most superintendents will tell you that has been a problem in
past years and we expect it will be this year,'' D'Agostino said.
</P>
<P>
   The American Federation of Teachers reported shortages in
special education, math, speech therapy and English as a Second
Language in 1999 and some surplus in elementary and social studies
teachers.
</P>
<P>
   A study last year by the National Commission on Teaching and
America's Future said there are plenty of teachers in the job pool,
but the challenge is in recruiting. State education departments and
school districts that do not develop aggressive recruitment
strategies or accept licenses awarded in other states suffer
teacher shortages, the report said.
</P>
<P>
   In Connecticut, shortages were curbed significantly by a 1986
state law that reformed schools by raising teacher standards and
boosting salaries to the highest level in the nation.
</P>
<P>
   School districts that have not had a problem hiring teachers
this year fear the need might become more urgent in the next couple
of years due to substantial retirements.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
