<DOCNO> APW20000703.0017 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-03 01:42 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> School districts claim fewer students now allowed to get top score  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   HUDSON FALLS, N.Y. (AP) - A small, little noted change in the
way the this year's groundbreaking Regents tests are scored will
allow fewer high school students to reach the ''mastery'' level,
some school officials claim.
</P>
<P>
   And because of the change, school districts could appear to be
doing worse compared to past years because fewer students may reach
the top level scores of 85 percent or better for the English
Regents. Students could also suffer by missing out on a chance for
an honors diploma, risk a lower grade average, or perhaps lose a
college acceptance, according to Glens Falls city schools
Superintendent Thomas McGowan. He is seeking the support of local
legislators to find out why the state changed its method.
</P>
<P>
   With the state's new key, a student who got 89 percent on this
year's test would've gotten a 96 last year, McGowan said.
</P>
<P>
   The district may even offer extra classes for those who might
want to retake the exam in August to raise their score.
</P>
<P>
   State Education Department spokesman William Hirschen did not
immediately know why the change had been made or if many other
districts across the state were upset.
</P>
<P>
   According to the state's new chart, a grid in which scores are
calculated by matching a certain number of points given for essays
with points given for multiple-choice answers, students have 12
chances to score 90 or above this year, compared with 36 chances
last year, according to the Glens Falls Post-Star.
</P>
<P>
   School officials said they were blind-sided by the change, which
they learned about only after they'd scored the exam. The exam is
the first of five being phased in over the next few years that
students have to pass in order to graduate.
</P>
<P>
   Robert Judge, Hudson Falls district assistant superintendent for
instruction, said he's spoken with officials in 10 districts
including top-performing schools and found that the percentage of
students scoring in the mastery level was down.
</P>
<P>
   At Hudson Falls, the number of students achieving the mastery
level was about 30 percent last year and 10 percent this year, he
said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-07-03-00 0142 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000703.0018 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-03 01:47 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 16 Killed in Chechen Truck Bombing  </HEADLINE>
By YURI BAGROV
<TEXT>
<P>
   NAZRAN, Russia (AP) -- At least 16 people were killed and 38
wounded early Monday when a truck bomb exploded outside a dormitory
housing Russian troops in eastern Chechnya, the Emergency
Situations Ministry said.
</P>
<P>
   Seven people were missing in the rubble of the shattered
building, the ministry said.
</P>
<P>
   The explosion targeted an Interior Ministory dormitory in the
town of Argun, nine miles east of Grozny. It followed weeks of
hit-and-run attacks by Chechen rebels in Russian-controlled
territory, and a five-day battle in the southeastern region of the
breakaway republic that killed at least 13 soldiers.
</P>
<P>
   On Sunday, a truck bomb exploded in front of a Russian military
headquarters in the Chechen town of Urus-Martan, in what Russian
officials said was a suicide bombing.
</P>
<P>
   The truck driver tried to crash the truck into the headquarters
but was prevented and there were no Russian casualties, said Lt.
Gen. Ivan Babichev, a Russian military spokesman.
</P>
<P>
   However, Ramzan Akhmadov, a Chechen guerrilla commander, said by
telephone Sunday that there were Russian dead. He did not specify a
number.
</P>
<P>
   He also said that rebels would soon send explosive-laden trucks
to Argun, Kurchaloi and Novogrozny and Gudermes, where the
pro-Moscow civilian government of Chechnya has its headquarters.
</P>
<P>
   Russian officials say they have all but won the war to
re-establish control over the rebellious region, but rebels
continue to inflict casualties with mines and ambushes.
</P>
<P>
   In Gudermes, Chechnya's second-largest city, a bomb exploded
Sunday in the attic of a bathhouse where residents and soldiers
were relaxing. Two servicemen and a local woman were wounded, the
ITAR-Tass news agency reported.
</P>
<P>
   Three Russian policemen were killed late Saturday when their car
drove over a homemade land mine at the entrance to a shooting range
in the town of Shelkovskaya, 30 miles northeast of the capital
Grozny, Interior Ministry officials said.
</P>
<P>
   Gunmen also fired for two and a half hours on a military
headquarters in the village of Znamenskoye in the Nadterechny
region, a lowland area the Russians captured last year, police
officials said.
</P>
<P>
   Refugees from elsewhere in Chechnya are living in a large camp
in the town, and a three-member team of human rights observers from
the Council of Europe is headquartered there.
</P>
<P>
   Temporary police stations in Argun and the village of
Nadterechnaya were also fired on Saturday night, the officials
said. No Russian casualties were reported in those attacks.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Russian troops on Sunday were carrying out what
officials called ''special operations'' in the towns of Valerik and
Urus-Martan, southwest of Grozny, ITAR-Tass reported. It said the
towns were sealed off, and that 15 people were arrested for taking
part in rebel operations.
</P>
<P>
   Russian troops were driven out of Chechnya in a 1994-96 war.
They returned after Chechnya-based Islamic militants raided several
villages in the neighboring Russian region of Dagestan, and after
about 300 people died in apartment bombings the government blames
on Chechens.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-07-03-00 0147 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000703.0019 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-03 01:51 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Intolerance Hurts Fijian Indians  </HEADLINE>
By STEVEN GUTKIN
<TEXT>
<P>
   SUVA, Fiji (AP) -- Nilesh Prakash watched in horror as armed
gangs looted and torched his grocery stand on the same day
anti-Indian rebels stormed parliament and took Fiji's Indian-led
government hostage.
</P>
<P>
   ''I looked but I couldn't do anything,'' said the 29-year-old
merchant. ''Some of the men knew us ... but they were all out of
their minds.''
</P>
<P>
   Prakash is one of thousands of ethnic Indians who have been
targeted by a wave of anti-Indian sentiment sweeping this South
Pacific island nation.
</P>
<P>
   The unrest began May 19, when gunmen took the government hostage
in the name of indigenous Fijian rights. They said the ethnic
Indian-led government had too much power and they called for a new
government run by indigenous Fijians.
</P>
<P>
   Indo-Fijians, who make up 44 percent of Fiji's 812,000 people,
are still reeling from attacks on Indian homes and businesses that
took place in the wake of the parliament raid.
</P>
<P>
   Reacting to the coup attempt and the violence, the army took
power 10 days later. On Sunday, the army defied the hostage-takers,
saying it would appoint a temporary government that would include
Indians.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, however, an interim government was installed without
any members of Fiji's Indian minority. Commodore Frank Bainimarama,
the military commander who assumed power, said two members of the
Indian community were asked to join but declined.
</P>
<P>
   The military has conceded to almost all of the hostage-takers'
demands to disenfranchise Fiji's Indian population, leaving
Indo-Fijians with a grave sense of insecurity in a nation they have
always called home.
</P>
<P>
   ''We can't sleep at night. They throw stones at us, rob us,
attack us,'' said Mousam Ali, a 44-year-old vendor. ''We want to
leave because we are fed up. But we have nowhere to go.''
</P>
<P>
   Reminders of the Indians' plight are everywhere in Fiji today:
gutted Indian shops, burnt-out Indian restaurants, Indians locking
themselves indoors to protect their children, a refugee camp in
western Fiji filled with 250 Indians who fled rural violence after
the parliament raid.
</P>
<P>
   Fiji has been struggling to come to terms with its ethnic
diversity ever since English colonialists brought indentured
laborers from India in the 1880s to work in the nation's rich sugar
cane fields.
</P>
<P>
   Anti-Indian sentiment was unleashed a year ago when a trade
union leader named Mahendra Chaudhry became Fiji's first prime
minister of Indian descent. He was elected in balloting that many
Fijians found confusing because, for the first time, they voted for
party lists instead of individuals.
</P>
<P>
   Chaudhry is now among 27 members of the ousted government who
have been held hostage in parliament for 44 days. During his
yearlong tenure as prime minister, he angered many indigenous
Fijians by refusing to allow higher rents to be charged to Indian
sugar cane farmers on land owned communally by indigenous Fijians.
</P>
<P>
   George Speight, the hostage-takers' leader, has capitalized on
this anger in what he calls a battle for the rights of indigenous
Fijians.
</P>
<P>
   Whether Chaudhry actually trampled on indigenous rights is
debatable, but it's clear he trampled on corrupt business practices
that were rampant in the previous, Fijian-led government. Speight
himself was a casualty of the Chaudhry administration, which fired
him as head of a powerful timber commission amid suspicion of
influence peddling.
</P>
<P>
   On Friday, television footage showed a haggard-looking Chaudhry
pacing the grounds where he has been a hostage for more than six
weeks. The deposed prime minister, who walked with his head turned
downward, appeared to have lost weight.
</P>
<P>
   Whether they took Chaudhry's government hostage out of greed or
conviction, Speight and his gunmen have found fertile ground in
deep-seated resentment of Indians. The Indian population here tends
to be more affluent than the indigenous Fijians.
</P>
<P>
   ''You can see that the ethnic rhetoric is a very powerful one.
And scapegoating is actually even more powerful,'' said Vijay
Naidu, who heads the development studies program at the University
of the South Pacific in the Fijian capital, Suva.
</P>
<P>
   Fiji is paying an enormous price for its break with democracy.
With negotiations to free the hostages deadlocked over an 11th-hour
demand by Speight's group to name a new president, the economy has
entered a downward spiral that could take years to reverse.
</P>
<P>
   And many of Fiji's best and brightest are fleeing.
</P>
<P>
   ''The bad news is that the most able, the wealthiest, the
educated, they will find a way to get out. And what will remain
here are the voiceless, the peasants, the taxi drivers, the small
shop keepers,'' said Osman Siddique, the U.S. ambassador to Fiji.
</P>
<P>
   Indo-Fijians are quick to point out that they are not all rich,
and that their roots in Fiji go back more than a century. Their
quest for political equality in the years since has been largely
unsuccessful, with their greatest advance -- the 1997 constitution --
now abolished.
</P>
<P>
   ''Fiji is going in reverse,'' said Prakash, the grocery vendor.
Added his wife, Sumintra: ''We're still very frightened.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
