<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-03 02:00 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> AIDS Threatens S. African Economy  </HEADLINE>
By RAVI NESSMAN
<TEXT>
<P>
   KATLEHONG, South Africa (AP) -- A group of 20 teen-age boys
jostle for the ball during a carefree afternoon soccer game. In the
coming years, half of those exuberant children will die a slow
death from AIDS if statistics hold, triggering a devastating
demographic catastrophe.
</P>
<P>
   The population is projected to stop growing, businesses to be
crushed and the continent's most developed economy to be badly
damaged.
</P>
<P>
   ''This is a disaster,'' said Marothi Ramaube, an official with
the South African Business Council on HIV/AIDS. ''We know it's
massive. How massive we don't know.''
</P>
<P>
   An estimated 4.2 million South Africans, 10 percent of the
population, are currently infected with AIDS or the virus that
causes AIDS.
</P>
<P>
   That number is expected to double by 2006, with many becoming
infected as they enter what should be their most productive years.
</P>
<P>
   If the disease is not reined in, more than half of all the
15-year-old boys in South Africa will die of AIDS in their
lifetime, according to a United Nations study released Tuesday in
advance of the 13th International AIDS Conference, which starts
Sunday in the coastal city of Durban.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike many 15-year-olds playing soccer in the township of
Katlehong east of Johannesburg, Sbusiso Dibitso is fully aware of
the risk. His 27-year-old sister, Tseleng, died of AIDS last July.
</P>
<P>
   Though he did not use a condom the first time he had sex last
year, he has ever since, he said. But many of his classmates have
yet to see someone they care for die of the disease, and they don't
really believe it exists.
</P>
<P>
   ''I'm worried about my friends,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   South Africa's business community is worried as well.
</P>
<P>
   Posters warning of AIDS adorn company bulletin boards, jars of
free condoms sit in front of their nurses' offices and companies
have trained thousands of their workers, and many of the
prostitutes their workers visit, to teach others how to avoid the
disease.
</P>
<P>
   The state-owned power company, Eskom, spends $600,000 a year
educating its 31,000 employees about AIDS, said Liz Thebe, head of
Eskom's AIDS program.
</P>
<P>
   But the company discovered an alarming rate of infection among
the scholarship students -- the future leaders of the company -- it
is paying millions of dollars a year to send to college. So it is
sending them to AIDS-awareness seminars as well.
</P>
<P>
   ''We are worried. Who are you going to employ?'' Thebe said.
</P>
<P>
   Businesses are beginning to face other, more costly, worries,
analysts said.
</P>
<P>
   As workers take more sick days, businesses will have to hire
extra staff.
</P>
<P>
   As they become gravely ill, employers will have to spend more on
medical insurance.
</P>
<P>
   As they die, companies will have to pay to train new employees,
many of whom will also die of the disease.
</P>
<P>
   Customers will die as well.
</P>
<P>
   The effects on the economy, already struggling to overcome
apartheid's legacy of poverty, will be reminiscent of a tragic
natural disaster or an apocalyptic war, said Kristina Quattek,
chief economist at ING-Barings, South Africa.
</P>
<P>
   But those nightmares end.
</P>
<P>
   ''This whole AIDS scenario will only drag on,'' Quattek said.
</P>
<P>
   By 2006, South Africa's Gross Domestic Product is expected to be
3.1 percent lower annually than it would have been without AIDS,
according to a study by ING-Barings. By 2011, it will be 4.7
percent lower.
</P>
<P>
   More than one-quarter of the labor force will be infected by
2006, and the country's population will be less than 50 million in
2015, instead of more than 60 million, because of AIDS, according
to the Actuarial Society of South Africa.
</P>
<P>
   With many families losing their wage-earners, South Africans
will be spending significantly less money -- except when it comes to
health care, according to ING-Barings. The government will be
forced to spend more of its scarce resources on health care, as
well.
</P>
<P>
   In response to the crisis, the government has issued a five-year
plan to combat the disease, stressing prevention, increased
voluntary testing and improved care for those already infected.
</P>
<P>
   Even if that campaign is wildly successful, ''you still can't
stop the whole epidemic in its tracks,'' Quattek said.
</P>
<P>
   Large companies, many of whom are quickly automating to soften
the blow, will likely survive, although they may be far less
profitable.
</P>
<P>
   Small businesses, however, depend more on their individual
employees and may collapse when a key manager, or even the owner,
succumbs to the disease, said Ramaube, of the business council on
HIV/AIDS.
</P>
<P>
   Despite that, many small businesses are completely unprepared
for the AIDS crisis, said Zackie Achmat, chairman of the AIDS
Treatment Action Campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Even big businesses are ignoring the full extent of the problem,
he said.
</P>
<P>
   ''In terms of PR, they're really good. In terms of producing
glossy material saying, 'AIDS kills. Use a condom,' they're really
good,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   They are not doing well when it comes to funding AIDS research --
to help fight the disease itself -- or negotiating medical policies
with insurance companies -- to keep their workers healthy longer.
</P>
<P>
   The business community must quickly develop a better plan for
dealing with AIDS, Achmat said.
</P>
<P>
   ''They cannot avoid it,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-07-03-00 0200 </TRAILER>
