<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-03 02:05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> New Fiji Civilian Government Named  </HEADLINE>
By STEVEN GUTKIN
<TEXT>
<P>
   SUVA, Fiji (AP) -- Fiji's military leader appointed a temporary
civilian government Monday in defiance of hostages takers who had
demanded a role in naming it, but said he would remain head of
state until the hostages are released.
</P>
<P>
   Notably absent from the new government lineup were members of
Fiji's Indian minority, who have been stripped of most political
power since rebels stormed parliament on May 19 and took the
Indian-led government hostage.
</P>
<P>
   ''We approached two well-qualified members of the Indian
community but they declined,'' said Commodore Frank Bainimarama,
the military commander who assumed power in the South Pacific
nation 10 days after the parliament raid.
</P>
<P>
   A banking executive named Laisenia Qarase was named as prime
minister. He has been head of the Merchant Bank Fiji and is a
former general manager of the Fiji Development Bank.
</P>
<P>
   Qarase is known more as a manager than a politician. George
Speight, the former insurance executive who is leading the rebels
holding 27 members of the ousted government hostage, has spoken
positively of Qarase in recent days. However, Qarase was not
Speight's first choice for prime minister.
</P>
<P>
   Bainimarama said the interim government will rule for 18 months
during which time it will draft a new constitution.
</P>
<P>
   After the raid on parliament, the army gave in to most of
Speight's demands to disenfranchise Fiji's ethnic Indians,
including firing Prime Minister Mahendra Chaudhry -- now a hostage --
and throwing out the country's 1997 multiracial constitution.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, Bainimarama said that constitution ''will not be
reinstated.''
</P>
<P>
   During a press conference in the capital of Suva, Bainimarama
said the new constitution should contain provisions to lift Fiji's
poor indigenous majority, but also ''the protection of the rights
of Indians and other communities that are an integral part of our
nation.''
</P>
<P>
   He said he will remain head of state until all the hostages are
safely released, the gunmen's weapons are turned over, and public
order is fully restored. The daily business of government will be
left to the interim government, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ''I remain open to further dialogue with George Speight and his
group,'' Bainimarama said. ''I appeal to them in the name of
almighty God to do the right thing.''
</P>
<P>
   Also Monday, the army announced it will tighten a military
cordon around the parliamentary compound where the hostages are
held.
</P>
<P>
   The tightening will entail a greater military presence in the
area and the restriction of access to and from the compound, army
spokesman Lt. Alipate Mataitini told The Associated Press.
</P>
<P>
   Talks to free the hostages broke down last week over what the
army said was an 11th-hour demand by Speight's group that it be
allowed to name a new president.
</P>
<P>
   Indians were first brought to Fiji over a century ago by English
colonialists seeking indentured laborers in the country's rich
sugar cane fields. They make up about 44 percent of Fiji's
population, while indigenous Fijians account for about 51 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Tensions rose in recent months between Indians and indigenous
Fijians after Chaudhry fought moves by Fijian landowners to raise
rents on land leased to Indians.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
