<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-03 02:12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Co-developer of vaccine to lead UR gene center  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   ROCHESTER, N.Y. (AP) - A developer of a vaccine for childhood
bacterial meningitis has been selected to lead the Center for Human
Genetics and Molecular Pediatric Disease at the University of
Rochester.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Richard A. Insel and a team of 12 scientists will study
diseases that are caused by damaged genes. The team will focus on
diseases that affect children, such as birth defects, asthma,
cystic fibrosis and diabetes.
</P>
<P>
   The research center is part of University's Aab Institute of
Biomedical Sciences.
</P>
<P>
   Insel, a pediatric immunologist, has served as director of the
Strong Children's Research Center since 1993.
</P>
<P>
   In the 1980s, he was one of three University of Rochester
researchers who developed the vaccine against Haemophilus influenza
type b, the disease that is a leading cause of meningitis in young
children.
</P>
<P>
   As the immunologist on the research team, Insel's role was to
study the immune response produced by the vaccine and to help the
researchers refine the vaccine to make it more effective.
</P>
<P>
   The vaccine is known as the Hib vaccine.
</P>
<P>
   According to the Centers for Disease Control and Prevention, the
vaccine caused Hib infections in children under 5 to plummet 99
percent in the United States between 1987 to 1997 - from about
20,000 cases a year to 81.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-07-03-00 0212 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000703.0025 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-03 02:19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> USS Kennedy arrives as Fourth of July buildup continues  </HEADLINE>
By RICHARD PYLE
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK - More ships and boats from Brooklyn to New Jersey and
Verazzano to Manhattan were expected to arrive today in New York
Harbor to join the aircraft carrier USS John F. Kennedy, which
dropped anchor near the Statue of Liberty.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. Coast Guard has estimated as many as 70,000 small craft
might show up for the city's nautical Fourth of July extravaganza.
</P>
<P>
   Some 150 sailing ships from 23 countries and 25 naval ships from
14 nations will take part in the dual event - Operation Sail 2000
and an International Naval Review, the sixth in just over a
century.
</P>
<P>
   Skies over the harbor were abuzz with military helicopters, and
small groups of white-uniformed sailors on shore leave were the
vanguard of an expected throng of some 28,000 seafarers for the
weeklong celebration. Some 3,000 to 4,000 small craft already were
at moorings in the harbor and shore marinas Sunday, Coast Guard
officials said.
</P>
<P>
   ''There's no question that this will be the largest assemblage
ever of tall ships and naval vessels,'' said Greg Perrin, vice
president of OpSail 2000.
</P>
<P>
   While the stately sailing ships are the main attraction, Navy
officials originally had planned for history's largest naval
review, with 61 nations invited to take part. That was scaled back
to a more modest 50 entries, but the event appeared to be falling
well short of any chance to break the record of 25 navies
represented at the 1986 Statue of Liberty centennial.
</P>
<P>
   Although the official list given out to news organizations said
36 ships would take part in the review, a list provided by Berzins
showed only 25 - 10 from the United States, two from Canada and two
from Japan, plus one each from Ireland, Britain, Ukraine, India,
Greece, France, Italy, Brazil, South Africa, Singapore and Turkey.
</P>
<P>
   Navy spokesmen said they couldn't explain the discrepancy.
</P>
<P>
   While many ships will be visiting Gotham for the first time, the
Norfolk, Va.-based Kennedy is no stranger. Commissioned in 1968 as
the Navy's last conventionally powered carrier, it has participated
in the city's annual Fleet Week festivities for a decade. The
Navy's eight newer, nuclear-powered carriers are not allowed in New
York harbor.
</P>
<P>
   The JFK, 80,000 tons and 1,052 feet long, anchored at midday
Sunday just south of the Statue of Liberty, near the amphibious
assault ship USS Nassau, a helicopter carrier that arrived on
Friday.
</P>
<P>
   On July 4, President Clinton will inspect the 11-mile line of
warships in the Hudson River from aboard the missile cruiser USS
Hue City, then transfer by Coast Guard cutter to the JFK, where he
will view the ''parade of sail'' from the flight deck.
</P>
<P>
   The Hue City, one of the Navy's powerful, billion-dollar
Aegis-type cruisers, steamed up the harbor late Sunday, bound for a
Hudson River pier near the Intrepid, a famed World War II carrier
turned military museum. The Hue City is the only U.S. Navy ship
named for a Vietnam War battle.
</P>
<P>
   The all-day harbor activities will be capped at night by what
organizers call the largest fireworks display ever: 60 tons of
explosives launched from barges at five locations, capped by a
grand finale blast near the Statue of Liberty. Organizers say as
many as 4 million people may see some part of the day aboard
watercraft or from vantage points in New York and New Jersey.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-07-03-00 0219 </TRAILER>
