<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-03 02:28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Mexicans Head South To Cast Ballots  </HEADLINE>
By BEN FOX
<TEXT>
<P>
   TIJUANA, Mexico (AP) -- Despite late-opening polling stations and
long lines that barely edged forward in the stifling heat,
thousands of Mexicans living in the United States jammed special
election booths across the border to vote in Mexico's national
elections Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   ''Perhaps we can contribute to a change in our country,'' said
28-year-old economist Eduardo Soriano, who drove from San Francisco
to Tijuana with his parents and two sisters.
</P>
<P>
   Estimates of the number of Mexican citizens who live in the
United States vary from 7 million and 10 million. The Federal
Electoral Institute says 1.5 million have valid voting cards.
</P>
<P>
   But Jorge Santibanez, a Tijuana immigration researcher, said
about 80 percent of those do not have legal residency in the United
States, and were unlikely to risk arrest by crossing the border to
vote.
</P>
<P>
   Even if all eligible voters wanted to cast ballots, they
couldn't: Each of the 64 special booths established in the six
border states was limited to 750 ballots for a total of 48,000, due
to federal regulations intended to prevent multiple or fraudulent
voting.
</P>
<P>
   The election was widely seen as the most competitive ever, with
Vicente Fox of the center-right National Action Party defeated
Francisco Labastida, the candidate of the ruling Institutional
Revolutionary Party, or PRI.
</P>
<P>
   However, immigration researcher Santibanez said that even if
Mexicans living abroad cast all 48,000 special ballots, they
wouldn't have much sway in a race with 58.7 million eligible
voters.
</P>
<P>
   ''I don't think their ballots will carry much weight,''
Santibanez said.
</P>
<P>
   That didn't dull the enthusiasm of voters who walked, drove or
joined political caravans to cast their votes.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's important this time,'' said Rigoberto Mendieta, a
construction worker from Austin, Texas, who leaned against the wall
of a Nuevo Laredo bus station waiting for his turn to vote. ''I
left Mexico because there wasn't any work. We need a change in
government and this time we might get one.''
</P>
<P>
   Tijuana, a sprawling city of more than 1 million people across
the border from San Diego, had just 15 of the polling booths, and a
total of 11,250 ballots.
</P>
<P>
   Lines of 300 people snaked around the makeshift polling booths.
Voters fanned themselves, smoked cigarettes and bounced their
babies during the hours-long wait to vote.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's very poorly organized,'' said Reina Salinas, 50. ''I have
to get back to San Diego to go to Mass.''
</P>
<P>
   Voter frustration was exacerbated when many polling stations
opened up to an hour late due to logistical problems and the
inexperience of polling officials.
</P>
<P>
   At Tijuana's bus station, 400 people waited in line at a polling
booth where only 200 ballots remained. The shortages also affected
booths in post offices, on main avenues and at the airport in
Tijuana.
</P>
<P>
   Ciudad Juarez, across El Paso, Texas, fared even worse, with
just three ballot boxes, or 2,250 ballots.
</P>
<P>
   The limited ballots had to suffice not only for those traveling
from north of the border to vote, but also active duty soldiers,
factory workers and others living in Mexico away from their home
districts.
</P>
<P>
   ''I wanted to be sure I got a ballot,'' said Joel Hernandez, a
vacationing Bible teacher from Guanajuato who stepped into a nearly
deserted Nuevo Laredo plaza just after dawn. ''I was afraid there
would be thousands and thousands of people coming here from the
United States.''
</P>
<P>
   In fact, vacationers and migrant workers far outnumbered U.S.
residents at many of the special voting centers.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-07-03-00 0228 </TRAILER>
