<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-03 02:52 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Obesity Rising in Latin America  </HEADLINE>
By ANA A. LIMA
<TEXT>
<P>
   RIO DE JANEIRO, Brazil (AP) -- The girl from Ipanema is too fat,
and so are many of her Latin American neighbors, health officials
say.
</P>
<P>
   Delegates at the first Latin American Conference on Healthy
Weight in Rio said rising income in some developing nations like
Brazil has led to worse eating habits and an increase in obesity,
especially among poorer people.
</P>
<P>
   About 10 percent of Brazil's 165 million people are obese, said
Walmir Coutinho, president of the Brazilian Association for the
Study of Obesity, which organized the weekend event. Some 6 percent
of Brazilian men and 13.3 percent of women are obese, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Brazil now has the same rate of obesity as France and Italy,
Coutinho said, although the United States remains No. 1, where
about one-quarter of adults are obese. About 15 percent to 20
percent of European adults are obese.
</P>
<P>
   Ironically, prosperous Brazilians generally are leaner than the
less affluent, who turn to fast food when their income rises, said
conference spokeswoman Elizabeth Camarao.
</P>
<P>
   Some 200,000 deaths in Latin America every year are directly
related to obesity, she said.
</P>
<P>
   Obesity is ''the epidemic of the new millennium,'' read a
statement issued at the end of the two-day conference.
</P>
<P>
   A report released in March by the Washington-based research
group Worldwatch Institute stated that, for the first time, the
number of overweight people in the world matched the total of its
underfed, at about 1.1 billion.
</P>
<P>
   Obesity is measured by a person's weight in relation to height.
At 6 feet, a person is considered overweight at 185 pounds and
obese at 220. Someone who is 5-foot-6 would be overweight at 155
pounds and obese at about 185.
</P>
<P>
   About 400 representatives from health ministries of 10 Latin
American countries drafted an ''Act of Rio de Janeiro'' with
recommendations to make people leaner and healthier.
</P>
<P>
   They include training teachers to educate children on diet and
exercise; inspecting school cafeterias to ensure they serve low-fat
foods and healthy snacks; and asking governments to spend more for
recreation centers in poor neighborhoods.
</P>
<P>
   Reducing obesity will eventually save money in treatment of
weight-related illnesses like diabetes, heart disease and
hypertension, Camarao said.
</P>
<P>
   Health officials ''saw the stupid expense they have with
obesity,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   The conference was attended by officials from Brazil, Mexico,
Ecuador, Colombia, Argentina, Chile, Venezuela, Puerto Rico,
Uruguay and Cuba.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-07-03-00 0252 </TRAILER>
