<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Dow, Nasdaq Fall Slightly  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Stocks were narrowly mixed Monday in a quiet,
shortened session ahead of the Independence Day holiday.
</P>
<P>
   In the first hour of trading on Wall Street, the Dow Jones
industrial average was down 19.10 at 10,428.79.
</P>
<P>
   Broader stock indicators were mixed. The Standard &AMP; Poor's 500
index was down 2.78 at 1,451.82, and the Nasdaq composite index was
down 19.54 at 3,946.57.
</P>
<P>
   Trading was extremely light. The stock market was to close at 1
p.m., and many Wall Street professionals had taken the day off,
opting for a four-day weekend. Volume on the New York Stock
Exchange came to 93.91 million shares, compared with 117.68 million
at the same time Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Still, a few catalysts drove trading. The National Association
of Purchasing Management reported a slowdown in manufacturing
activity, raising hopes that six interest-rate increases by the
Federal Reserve in the past year are slowing the economy to a more
sustainable pace.
</P>
<P>
   The purchasing managers' business index for June came in at
51.8, compared with 53.2 in May. While any reading above 50 is
considered a sign of economic growth, the index was lower than
analysts had anticipated.
</P>
<P>
   What's more, the report's ''prices paid'' index fell from 65.8
in May to 61.2 in June. That component is considered an important
gauge of inflationary pressures.
</P>
<P>
   Oracle fell $3.813 to $80.25. Late Friday, the company announced
that chief operating offer and president Ray Lane will leave his
post.
</P>
<P>
   Advancing issues outnumbered decliners by a 5-to-3 margin on the
NYSE.
</P>
<P>
   The Russell 2000 index of smaller companies rose 4.65 to 517.23.
</P>
<P>
   Overseas, Japan's Nikkei stock average rose 1.2 percent. In
afternoon trading, Germany's DAX index was up 0.3 percent,
Britain's FT-SE 100 was up 0.9 percent, and France's CAC-40 was up
0.4 percent.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net:
</P>
<P>
   New York Stock Exchange: http://www.nyse.com
</P>
<P>
   Nasdaq Stock Market: http://www.nasdaq.com
</P>
</TEXT>
