<HEADLINE> Lucky Few Snag Copies of Potter  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   RICHMOND, Va. (AP) -- A lucky few people have their hands on the
eagerly awaited fourth Harry Potter book after two area stores
prematurely sold copies.
</P>
<P>
   ''Harry Potter and the Goblet of Fire,'' the latest installment
in the popular children's series, is to be unveiled Saturday.
Bookstores have been forced to keep nearly 4 million copies under
wraps until then, and many are planning special midnight launch
parties.
</P>
<P>
   But an area Wal-Mart and another unidentified store broke the
embargo last week, giving a handful of kids a scoop on Harry's
adventures, which fill more than 700 pages.
</P>
<P>
   In Chesterfield County south of Richmond, 10-year-old Caitlin
Streett has been reading the book and filling in her friends on the
details.
</P>
<P>
   ''Well, the first 10 pages are pretty boring but then it grabs
you and you can't put it down,'' Caitlin said.
</P>
<P>
   Caitlin and her dad, Gene Streett, found the book at a local
Wal-Mart while they shopped for glue.
</P>
<P>
   ''We were doing papier mache crafts. And we walk in and it was
like, 'Whoa! Harry Potter!' There was a big display with some other
books,'' said Gene Streett, a high school teacher.
</P>
<P>
   He paid $12.97 for the book, which lists for $25.95.
</P>
<P>
   A Wal-Mart spokesman said the store mistakenly put the books on
the store shelves and removed them as soon as they realized they
weren't supposed to be there. About 20 books were sold.
</P>
<P>
   ''This is purely an isolated incident based on a mistake that we
made,'' said Rob Phillips, a spokesman for Bentonville, Ark.-based
Wal-Mart Stores Inc.
</P>
<P>
   While Streett immediately realized the significance of his find,
8-year-old Laura Cantwell had to explain it to her dad, Tim
Cantwell.
</P>
<P>
   He found the book in a second, unidentified northern Virginia
store last week when he was tipped off by a friend.
</P>
<P>
   When he gave the book to his daughter, ''she said, 'Dad, do you
realize how huge this is? ... I said to my wife that night that I
could probably sell this book for a lot of money. She said, 'Under
no circumstances do you sell that book.'''
</P>
<P>
   The Cantwells are not saying where they got the book because
they don't want anyone to get in trouble.
</P>
<P>
   The book's publisher, Scholastic Inc., did not immediately
return a phone call Monday.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
