<HEADLINE> EU Evaluates Yugoslav Companies  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   BRUSSELS, Belgium (AP) -- The European Commission on Monday
released a list of 190 Yugoslav companies to be exempted from
European sanctions because they have proved they are not linked to
President Slobodan Milosevic's government.
</P>
<P>
   The European Union executive body said the preparation of a
''white list'' was part of a drive to focus EU sanctions against
the Milosevic regime without increasing hardships for the Yugoslav
population as a whole.
</P>
<P>
   In a statement, the 15-nation EU said it was considering
applications from over 100 more companies and that 50 of those
would likely be added to the list this month.
</P>
<P>
   Companies on the list including food, pharmaceutical and
electrical companies as well as the local subsidiaries of
international firms including Ericsson, Mercedes-Benz, Siemens, and
Volvo. Companies in sensitive fields such as fuel supply, banking
and production of military equipment were not included.
</P>
<P>
   The EU imposed restrictions on investment and trading with
Yugoslavia during the armed crack down on ethnic Albanians in
Kosovo which led to NATO military intervention in the province last
year.
</P>
</TEXT>
