<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-03 12:11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Smuggler Methods Get Sophisticated  </HEADLINE>
CHRISTOPHER BODEEN
Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   BEIJING (AP) -- Chinese gangs are adopting increasingly varied
and sophisticated methods of smuggling illegal migrants into the
United States, the chief of the U.S. immigration service said
Monday.
</P>
<P>
   All but gone is the crude but common method of packing migrants
into decrepit boats for long sea voyages ending in night-time
landings along the U.S. coastline, said Doris Meissner,
commissioner of the U.S. Immigration and Naturalization Service.
</P>
<P>
   No such vessels have been found this year, she said, though some
immigrants have been found in cargo ships docking at West Coast
ports.
</P>
<P>
   Faced with tighter law enforcement and greater vigilance,
people-smugglers now take migrants out of China overland or by air
to Europe and South and Central America.
</P>
<P>
   Small groups typically enter at major U.S. airports using
doctored passports that are recycled and sold to other hopefuls,
Meissner said.
</P>
<P>
   ''So it has branched out and in some ways it's more difficult
because the groups are small and routes are rather widespread,''
Meissner said.
</P>
<P>
   Chinese migrant smuggling attracted international concern
following the discovery of the bodies of 58 illegal immigrants from
southeastern China in an airtight truck compartment at the English
port of Dover on June 18.
</P>
<P>
   The United States has traditionally been the primary destination
for Chinese migrants, although Meissner said no hard figures on the
numbers of arrivals are available.
</P>
<P>
   Several boats carrying immigrants in soft-top cargo containers
were intercepted earlier this year on the West Coast, including
Seattle, where three people were found dead in a ship intercepted
Jan. 10.
</P>
<P>
   Scores of Chinese stowaways who crossed the Pacific in such
containers have been arrested at West Coast ports in the United
States and Canada this year. Fifteen were apprehended in Los
Angeles in the last U.S. incident reported, in April, and
immigration officials say the smugglers have likely switched to
other methods.
</P>
<P>
   Despite fees of up to $60,000 charged by smuggling ringleaders,
or ''snakeheads,'' large numbers of Chinese, mostly from coastal
Fujian province, attempt the long, dangerous trip for the chance of
working in an American restaurant or factory.
</P>
<P>
   Money sent home pays for flashy new houses, stoking the desire
to work abroad among others.
</P>
<P>
   But to pay back their passage, some migrants are forced into
prostitution. Others risk rape, kidnapping or murder.
</P>
<P>
   According to INS officials, about 200 illegal Chinese immigrants
a week are stopped just at Los Angeles's airport, and 2,700 Chinese
illegals who arrived by air have been repatriated this year.
</P>
<P>
   Many enter the United States using stolen passports from Japan
and Singapore, whose citizens do not need a visa to enter the
United States.
</P>
<P>
   Meissner, who will visit Fujian this week, said her meetings
with Chinese officials focused on finding ways to improve the
sharing of information for prosecuting snakeheads, uncovering
document fraud, and analyzing trends in people smuggling.
</P>
<P>
   While China has helped speed the repatriation of many who
attempted to reach the United States by boat, such cooperation
still occurs chiefly on a case-by-case basis, Meissner said.
</P>
<P>
   ''It is difficult. We would like to see better cooperation, not
only from China but all over,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Ensuring speedy repatriations is especially important, said
Meissner, who called quick returns the strongest message that can
be sent to convince would-be migrants that the risk and large
amounts of money paid are not worth it.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-07-03-00 1211 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000703.0052 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-03 12:16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Dow, Nasdaq Move Slightly Higher  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Stocks were mostly higher Monday in a quiet,
shortened session ahead of the Independence Day holiday. A report
of moderating economic growth helped the market advance.
</P>
<P>
   In midday trading on Wall Street, the Dow Jones industrial
average was up 35.71 at 10,483.60.
</P>
<P>
   The Standard &AMP; Poor's 500 index was up 4.49 at 1,459.09, and the
Nasdaq composite index was up 9.03 at 3,975.14.
</P>
<P>
   Trading was extremely light. The stock market was to close at 1
p.m., and many Wall Street professionals had taken the day off,
opting for a four-day weekend. Volume on the New York Stock
Exchange came to 303.77 million shares, compared with 415.11
million at the same time Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Still, a few catalysts drove trading. The National Association
of Purchasing Management reported a slowdown in manufacturing
activity growth, raising hopes that six interest-rate increases by
the Federal Reserve in the past year are slowing the economy to a
more sustainable pace.
</P>
<P>
   The purchasing managers' business index for June came in at
51.8, compared with 53.2 in May. While any reading above 50 is
considered a sign of economic growth, the index was lower than
analysts had anticipated.
</P>
<P>
   What's more, the report's ''prices paid'' index fell from 65.8
in May to 61.2 in June. That component is considered an important
gauge of inflationary pressures.
</P>
<P>
   ''The market is telling a pretty good story,'' said Alan
Ackerman, senior vice president at Fahnestock &AMP; Co. in New York.
''This was a favorable piece of news that I think will allow some
interest-rate jitters to fade away.''
</P>
<P>
   Rate-sensitive stocks rose. J.P. Morgan gained $4.25 to $114.375
and Bank of America rose $1.563 to $44.813.
</P>
<P>
   Oracle fell $5 to $79.063. Late Friday, the company announced
that chief operating offer and president Ray Lane will leave his
post.
</P>
<P>
   Advancing issues outnumbered decliners by a 2-to-1 margin on the
NYSE, but decliners held a slight edge in Nasdaq trading.
</P>
<P>
   The Russell 2000 index of smaller companies rose 4.74 to 521.97.
</P>
<P>
   Overseas indexes were mostly higher, including Mexico's key IPC
index. Investors were celebrating the presidential victory of
opposition candidate Vicente Fox, whose victory ends the
Institutional Revolutionary Party's 71-year grip on the presidency.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts said the election wasn't a significant factor in U.S.
stock trading, but may stimulate interest in Mexican stocks in the
coming sessions.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
