<DOCNO> APW20000703.0055 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-03 12:35 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Managed Care Balks at Newer Drugs  </HEADLINE>
By PHIL GALEWITZ
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Jane Thompson's arthritis drug was losing its
punch last year just as the federal government was approving two
promising new painkillers.
</P>
<P>
   A doctor gave the retired school teacher a prescription for
Merck &AMP; Co.'s Vioxx, and then Pharmacia Inc.'s Celebrex, both
one-a-day pills that reduce inflammation as well as older medicines
do but that cause fewer side effects such as upset stomach and
ulcers.
</P>
<P>
   But Thompson's insurer, HIP Health Plan, refused to pay for
either new drug. HIP didn't think the new pills were worth the
extra cost -- Celebrex and Vioxx each cost $2.42 a day, eight times
more than common generic arthritis drugs.
</P>
<P>
   HIP's restrictive policy toward the new painkillers reflects how
the managed care industry is playing hardball with this new class
of expensive medicines and high drug prices overall.
</P>
<P>
   Nearly all the large U.S. managed care firms either don't cover
Celebrex and Vioxx, require patients to meet strict medical
criteria to get them, or mandate that their members try and fail
with cheaper medicines first.
</P>
<P>
   ''We're not convinced the new drugs have fewer side effects,''
said United HealthCare spokesman Roger Cruzan.
</P>
<P>
   The managed care industry's approach toward the arthritis drugs
might hurt relations with some customers and doctors, but that's a
price HMOs are willing to pay to control soaring pharmaceutical
costs. New drugs in particular, with their high prices and strong
consumer demand, have been a particular bane for HMOs looking to
improve their profits.
</P>
<P>
   Thompson, 64, of New York, now pays $72 a month for Vioxx and
also relies on free samples from her doctor. ''I'm annoyed about
it,'' she said of her insurer's lack of coverage. ''It's not
fair.''
</P>
<P>
   Some HMOs such as United and Foundation Health Plans, which
provide broad prescription drug coverage, usually require customers
to pay high co-payments to get the two medicines-- often about $25
per prescription compared to $5 for generic drugs and $10 for
preferred brand medicines.
</P>
<P>
   The HMOs' restrictions upsets doctors.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's a shame, because this is an exciting new class of
drugs,'' said Dr. Mark Jarrett, director of rheumatology at Staten
Island University Hospital in New York.
</P>
<P>
   Celebrex and Vioxx are the first in a class of new arthritis
drugs called cox-2 inhibitors, which target an enzyme that causes
inflammation. Unlike earlier drugs, cox-2 inhibitors don't act
against a second enzyme, which protects the stomach lining.
</P>
<P>
   Ulcers, stomach bleeding and other gastrointestinal side effects
are major problems with many painkillers, such as ibuprofen or
aspirin.
</P>
<P>
   While studies show that cox-2 inhibitors may cause fewer ulcers
than other drugs, the Food and Drug Administration still requires
them to carry the same warning about side effects that cheaper
drugs do.
</P>
<P>
   But Jarrett said the new drugs should actually save insurer's
save money over the long term by reducing hospitalizations caused
by side effects from older painkillers. ''We shouldn't be making
everyone jump through hoops to get these drugs,'' he added.
</P>
<P>
   Advocates for arthritis patients say they've heard the
complaints from consumers.
</P>
<P>
   ''The lack of coverage of these drugs is a big issue,'' said Dr.
John Kimpel, medical director of the Arthritis Foundation. But he
acknowledges there is no consensus in the medical community about
which arthritis patients can best be treated with the cox-2
inhibitors.
</P>
<P>
   Generally, most doctors agree that patients who should get the
new painkillers are those who experience side effects from other
painkillers, have a history of gastrointestinal problems or are
over age 50. But there is disagreement over whether the drugs
should be given to arthritis patients who don't have a history of
stomach problems or who are faring well on their current
medication.
</P>
<P>
   Merck and Pharmacia officials say their drug sales have not been
hampered by the HMO restrictions. The companies are spending
millions on additional studies to prove that the drugs are indeed
better than traditional painkillers-- partly in hopes of removing
the warnings on the drugs' labels and partly to win over skeptical
insurers.
</P>
<P>
   Both companies are also spending heavily on consumer
advertising, designed to drive patients into doctors' offices to
ask for the pills.
</P>
<P>
   The promotions are working. Celebrex posted $1.5 billion in
sales last year, its first on the market, and outpaced the
anti-impotence drug Viagra to become the hottest selling new drug
ever.
</P>
<P>
   Rival Vioxx, approved in May 1999, is coming on fast. Vioxx had
$472 million in sales last year and $370 million in sales in just
the first quarter of 2000. In terms of new prescriptions, Vioxx is
running slightly behind Celebrex, according to market data firm IMS
Health.
</P>
<P>
   Joe Pappa, North American president of Pharmacia's Searle's
subsidiary, said HMOs generally are more demanding before allowing
members to have access to new drugs. ''This is typical managed care
activity,'' Pappa said of HMOs not covering the drug.
</P>
<P>
   Citing a company-funded study of 8,000 arthritis patients, Pappa
said Celebrex is an appropriate drug for all patients with
arthritis, regardless of whether they have had problems with older
drugs. But the 13-month study found serious stomach side effects
can occur within the first week of usage, according to a
company-paid study. ''Everyone is at risk'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The company is still trying to convince many managed care firms.
</P>
<P>
   Aetna, the nation's largest health insurer, requires customers
to either first try two different generic painkillers or get
special permission from the plan.
</P>
<P>
   Cigna does not cover either drug, but doctors can appeal for
patients particularly at risk. ''We've concluded there are similar
drugs on the market with the same benefit. There's nothing
substantially new here,'' said spokesman Mark Di Giorgio.
</P>
<P>
   Kaiser Permanente leaves the choice of drugs up to their
doctors, although it works with them to show that only a small
percentage of arthritis patients actually benefit from Vioxx and
Celebrex.
</P>
<P>
   Celebrex and Vioxx make up about 3 percent of anti-inflammatory
prescriptions for Kaiser's 8 million members, but 40 percent of the
costs for this type of drug.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-07-03-00 1235 </TRAILER>
