<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-03 13:56 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Asians Ponder Biotech Foods  </HEADLINE>
By ELAINE KURTENBACH
<TEXT>
<P>
   BAODING, China (AP) -- The dusty, sleepy seed market on the north
China plain seems worlds away from any technological revolution.
But here, when cotton farmers plant, they favor cutting-edge
science to ensure a bountiful harvest.
</P>
<P>
   All but a fraction of the cotton fields in Baoding and
surrounding Hebei province are sown with seeds genetically
implanted with a bacterium that is toxic to boll worms.
</P>
<P>
   ''The farmers really welcome these seeds,'' says seed-seller
Meng Xinghe, standing amid sacks of corn and soybean seed in his
small market stall. ''Without them, they'd be wiped out.''
</P>
<P>
   With memories of famine fresh and dwindling arable land to feed
its 1.26 billion people, China has enthusiastically pursued
genetically modified foods and seen little of the debate that has
raged in Europe and elsewhere over their safety.
</P>
<P>
   But in other Asia-Pacific nations, the controversy over
biotechnology has far exceeded its actual use. In India, Japan, New
Zealand, Thailand and the Philippines, consumer movements are
demanding controls on use of genetically modified crops.
</P>
<P>
   Proponents contend that genetically altering crops to resist
pests, drought or other adverse conditions may be the only way to
ensure food security in the developing world, particularly in
densely populated Asia, home to more than half of humanity.
</P>
<P>
   Such crops, they argue, can drastically reduce the need for
harmful pesticides, restore ravaged ecosystems and promote public
health with foods genetically enhanced with essential nutrients or
vaccines.
</P>
<P>
   But the technique of splicing genes from one organism onto
another has also provoked fears of freak, unforeseen hazards to
health and the environment.
</P>
<P>
   In Southeast Asia, only Singapore has come out strongly in favor
of biotechnology, viewing it as a promising new industry.
</P>
<P>
   ''If it is safe for the Americans, it is safe for us,'' says Lee
Sing Kong, a member of the Singapore government's Genetic
Modification Advisory Committee, brushing aside growing debate in
the United States.
</P>
<P>
   The source of the technology -- mainly the research labs of
governments and corporations in industrialized countries -- raises
political hackles too.
</P>
<P>
   Farmers in southern India torched cotton test fields operated by
St. Louis-based biotech giant Monsanto last year, complaining the
seeds were too expensive.
</P>
<P>
   In the Philippines, seven of 10 farmers are landless, renting
fields from landlords or working for large corporations like Dole
Foods. Leftist groups argue genetically modified crops will give
the companies that sell seeds and farm chemicals even greater
power.
</P>
<P>
   ''Big landlords and transnational corporations will call all the
shots,'' said Wim De Ceukelaire, a consultant for the Peasant
Movement of the Philippines. ''In the case of small farmers, it
means going deeper and deeper into debt.''
</P>
<P>
   The Peasant Movement plans demonstrations against genetically
modified foods later this year, joined by counterparts in Thailand,
India and elsewhere.
</P>
<P>
   Genetic engineering has potentially explosive ramifications for
ethnically divided countries like Malaysia and Indonesia.
</P>
<P>
   ''If people were aware that animal genes might be used in
plants, maybe from cows or pigs, there would be a lot of religious
objections from Hindus and Muslims,'' said Haji Muhammad Haji Abdul
Majid, a professor of biotechnology at the University of Malaya in
Kuala Lumpur.
</P>
<P>
   Such concerns are largely absent in China. Provincial and
central governments have backed research into genetic engineering.
Debate over biotechnology in the state-controlled media has been
muted.
</P>
<P>
   With controls on grain imports set to relax when China enters
the World Trade Organization, pressure is growing to boost farm
productivity and cut costs inflated by heavy use of expensive
pesticides.
</P>
<P>
   ''Production costs are relatively high, so grain prices are
high. Yet, we must bring rural incomes up. We can't push them down
any further. The only way out is to rely on agricultural
technology,'' says Zhu Zhen, deputy director of the Institute of
Genetics at the Chinese Academy of Sciences in Beijing.
</P>
<P>
   ''This is not just a scientific question. This is a political
question of paramount importance,'' he says as he watches
assistants tweeze tiny white boll worms onto transgenic corn
plants.
</P>
<P>
   In Hebei, where cotton crops were devastated in the first half
of the 1990s by boll worms, farmers have overwhelmingly chosen
biotechnology. Genetically modified cotton is also grown
extensively in neighboring Henan province and in Xinjiang, in the
remote northwest.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the genetically modified cotton grown in Hebei is
Monsanto's Bollgard brand, produced by a joint venture set up in
1997. Monsanto plans further joint ventures in several other
provinces, according to company spokesman David Li.
</P>
<P>
   The company is also testing boll worm-resistant corn in two
northeastern provinces. Locally developed transgenic sweet peppers
and tomatoes are also sold, although they have proved less popular.
</P>
<P>
   ''They're the small type, and people don't like their taste,''
said Meng, the seed seller in Baoding, 90 miles southwest of
Beijing.
</P>
<P>
   So far, China has no restrictions on imports of genetically
modified agricultural commodities, such as soybeans, and there are
no labeling requirements for imported processed foods, which may
contain genetically modified products.
</P>
<P>
   Still, not even China has entirely evaded the public backlash
against biotechnology.
</P>
<P>
   Attempts to popularize use of genetically modified tobacco were
abandoned after international corporations like Philip Morris
announced they would buy only unaltered tobacco.
</P>
<P>
   Fears of such troubles have prompted a number of Asian countries
to adopt tight controls on genetic research and farming.
</P>
<P>
   India, the world's third-largest producer of cotton, allows
field testing of genetically altered cotton only under close
government supervision. Commercial cultivation is banned. Likewise
for Thailand, the world's largest rice exporter.
</P>
<P>
   New Zealand has declared a ''voluntary'' moratorium on
dissemination of biotechnology pending an inquiry.
</P>
<P>
   With surveys showing 80 percent of the Japanese public reluctant
to buy genetically altered foods, the government adopted labeling
and safety screening requirements, to take effect in April 2001.
</P>
<P>
   Japanese scientists have been quietly researching genetic
modification of tomatoes, rice, potatoes, melon and corn for years.
Demands for greater accountability followed Tokyo's announcement
last year that beef from cloned cows had been sold unmarked for at
least two years.
</P>
<P>
   Researchers like Zhu of the Chinese Academy of Sciences worry
that public opposition could scuttle work on genetically engineered
grains, such as ''golden rice,'' a variety developed in a Swiss
laboratory that is high in vitamin A. Advocates believe it could
help prevent deaths and blindness among millions of malnourished
children each year.
</P>
<P>
   ''We do not seek to promote biotech. We only want the freedom to
do the research to get the facts,'' says Duncan McIntosh, spokesman
for the International Rice Research Institute in the Philippine
capital, Manila. ''Vitamin A rice: Is it edible? Does it work? Is
it commercially feasible for farmers? Will Asians want to eat
yellow rice in the first place?''
</P>
<P>
   Wary of the brewing controversy, researchers at the rice
institute are searching the 92,000 rice varieties in their gene
bank for those naturally rich in key nutrients.
</P>
<P>
   Tests found that a conventional rice variety unusually high in
iron and zinc was useful in treating anemia -- another severe health
problem in poor countries.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's a very exciting concept to be able to use a staple food
that feeds half the world to solve public health problems. But
biotechnology needs to be kept in perspective,'' McIntosh says.
''The same concept sometimes can work with traditional varieties.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
