<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-03 14:04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Turkish Settlers Having Trouble  </HEADLINE>
By HARMONIE TOROS
<TEXT>
<P>
   FAMAGUSTA, Cyprus (AP) -- Even after 25 years in Cyprus, Fatma
Dagli says she still sticks with her own people -- Turks from
Turkey.
</P>
<P>
   Dagli shares the ethnic background, language and Muslim faith of
Turkish Cypriots, but she married a fellow settler from Turkey and
lives in a neighborhood populated almost entirely by Turks who
moved to the island after the 1974 Turkish invasion.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's easier to find an understanding amongst ourselves,'' says
Dagli, wearing a traditional Anatolian head scarf, which is rarely
worn by secular, Western-oriented Turkish Cypriot women. ''They
resemble us, but they are different.''
</P>
<P>
   Greek Cypriots insist that when a solution to the island's
26-year division is reached, the tens of thousands of Turkish
settlers must leave.
</P>
<P>
   Turks and Turkish Cypriots say the settlers must be allowed to
stay, but their unity masks the deep gaps between native Turkish
Cypriots and Turks from Turkey, many of whom have failed to
integrate into Cypriot society.
</P>
<P>
   The future of the settlers is one of the thorny issues that will
confront Greek and Turkish Cypriot leaders when they meet July 5 in
Geneva for a scheduled third round of talks with U.N. negotiators
as go-betweens.
</P>
<P>
   Many Turkish Cypriots are also concerned that the settlers, who
form a strong electoral bloc, may hinder prospects of uniting the
island out of fear they will be forced to return to Turkey.
</P>
<P>
   Turkish and Turkish Cypriot leaders encouraged Turks to come to
Cyprus to populate land abandoned by Greek Cypriots after the
Turkish invasion, which followed an Athens-backed coup by
supporters of union with Greece. The invasion left 30 percent of
the island's territory in the hands of Turkish Cypriots, who made
up just 18 percent of the population.
</P>
<P>
   Many of the settlers were landless farmers who suddenly found
themselves in one of the most Westernized parts of the Turkish
world.
</P>
<P>
   ''They didn't send people who fit with the Cypriot culture.
People who didn't have a profession, who didn't have education came
here,'' says Kemal Bayram, a Turk who moved to Cyprus in 1974 and
set up a printing shop in Nicosia.
</P>
<P>
   There is no official figure of how many Turks moved to northern
Cyprus after the Turkish invasion. Estimates range from 30,000 to
80,000 settlers, among a total Turkish population on Cyprus of
200,000.
</P>
<P>
   Many Turkish Cypriots can cite ways in which they have grown to
be different from mainland Turks after centuries of living
alongside Greek Cypriots and 80 years under British rule.
</P>
<P>
   ''The main difference between us is culture,'' says Hasan
Kahvecioglu, a political commentator for Cypriot television. The
Turkish settlers ''have crowded families, they have different
attitudes in their business relations, and they carry weapons,
which is not part of Cypriot culture.''
</P>
<P>
   In politics, the Turkish Cypriot leftist opposition has long
argued that Turkey used to urge the settlers to vote for
center-right leader Rauf Denktash, a staunch defender of Turkey's
right to influence Cypriot affairs.
</P>
<P>
   But in recent presidential elections, the settler vote more
closely matched the patterns of Turkish Cypriots -- proof, some
argue, that the settlers are becoming more integrated into Cypriot
society.
</P>
<P>
   Denktash won the last election but faced a serious challenge
from his prime minister.
</P>
<P>
   And most admit that tension between the two Turkish communities
has eased over the years and point at the integration of the
settlers' children, who even speak Turkish with a Cypriot accent.
</P>
<P>
   But in the village of Ulukisla, outside Nicosia, the only
Cypriot inhabitants are the few who married Turkish settlers.
</P>
<P>
   The farmers, who sit sipping strong tea in the village's
traditional Anatolian-style teahouse, are reluctant to speak of
their relations with Turkish Cypriots.
</P>
<P>
   They will, however, voice their conviction that had Turkish
troops not invaded the island, Turkish Cypriots would have been
killed or expelled by Greek Cypriots.
</P>
<P>
   ''We fought for this land,'' Ahmet Cetiner says. ''We are going
nowhere.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
