<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-03 14:15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Cuba Presses Against U.S. Policies  </HEADLINE>
By ANITA SNOW
<TEXT>
<P>
   HAVANA (AP) -- In the wake of Elian Gonzalez's return to Cuba,
Fidel Castro's government pushed ahead Monday with a new propaganda
campaign against decades-old U.S. policies aimed at punishing the
communist island.
</P>
<P>
   It remained unclear, however, if authorities can motivate Cubans
with a campaign that deals with ideas rather than a photogenic
6-year-old child and his distressed father.
</P>
<P>
   Marches, rallies, debates and forums will be held ''every day of
the year'' for an indefinite period, the Communist Party daily
Granma said Monday.
</P>
<P>
   ''There will be no weariness or wavering,'' it said. ''The
battle of ideas ... enters a new and prolonged chapter.''
</P>
<P>
   It encouraged Cubans to collect the special editions state-run
newspapers will be publishing in the coming weeks about U.S.
policies toward Cuba.
</P>
<P>
   The new campaign appears designed to educate Cubans about U.S.
laws and policies the government abhors, such as long-standing
American trade sanctions against the island and the Cuban
Adjustment Act, a law that allows Cubans who reach U.S. soil to
stay and apply for permanent residency.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, the government hopes to transform the
enthusiastic support that Cubans showed for a little boy who had
lost his mother into vocal, visual support for the communist
government's battle against American policies.
</P>
<P>
   Every Saturday, a huge rally will be held in a different
provincial city, just as they have been held every week in recent
months to demand Elian's return to his homeland, Granma said. The
newspaper said that a live televised round-table will be held every
weekday evening, much like the ones that for months updated Cubans
on developments in the Elian case.
</P>
<P>
   Cuba organized more than 100 rallies in the seven months that
Elian was in the United States, calling out hundreds of thousands
of Cubans to show popular support for bringing the boy home.
</P>
<P>
   Elian and his family have remained out of public view since
shortly after their return last Wednesday. They are staying at a
specially prepared boarding school in Havana, where they will live
for two or three weeks along with Elian's classmates and teachers.
</P>
<P>
   Later, they will take a one-week holiday and return to their
hometown of Cardenas, a small port city east of Havana.
</P>
<P>
   Also out of the public eye has been Castro himself, who was not
at the airport when Elian came home and has not been seen with the
family since they returned. It is not known if the Cuban president
has met privately with them.
</P>
<P>
   Cuba blames the Cuban Adjustment Act, in particular, for the
international custody battle over Elian.
</P>
<P>
   The communist government maintains the policy encourages Cubans
to make risky crossings to the United States, despite migration
accords that require the U.S. Coast Guard to repatriate them if
they are intercepted at sea.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
