<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-03 14:47 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Mongolians Turn To Ex-Communists  </HEADLINE>
By JOSEPH COLEMAN
<TEXT>
<P>
   ULAN BATOR, Mongolia (AP) -- Frustrated with painful reform and
disgusted with government corruption, Mongolians have turned to the
political force that represents the stability they long for: the
former communists.
</P>
<P>
   But the overwhelming victory of the Mongolian People's
Revolutionary Party over the reformist government in Sunday's
parliamentary elections won't mean a return to Soviet-style
economics, party leaders said.
</P>
<P>
   ''We cannot afford to go back,'' N. Enkhbayar, the next expected
prime minister, insisted in an interview with The Associated Press
before the vote. ''We cannot survive if we go back.''
</P>
<P>
   An unofficial tally on Monday showed Enkhbayar's party winning a
stunning 72 of the 76 seats in Mongolia's unicameral Parliament.
The government was expected to release official returns on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Despite that victory, most Mongolians don't want to delve too
far into the MPRP's past.
</P>
<P>
   Mongolia became a people's republic under Bolshevik influence in
1921, and the precursor of the MPRP established total control. The
party changed to its current name and declared the world's second
communist country in 1924.
</P>
<P>
   The 1930s brought forced collectivization of land. Buddhist
monks were slaughtered and their land confiscated. Private business
was banned.
</P>
<P>
   Though the regime softened somewhat in the 1950s, Mongolia was
firmly in the Soviet sphere until the Soviet Union started to
falter and a peaceful populist movement brought down hard-line
communism in Mongolia in 1990.
</P>
<P>
   While few voters seemed to yearn for a return to the old days,
the rapid pace of change since the end of communism has been tough
on Mongolia -- making many nostalgic for the stability of years
past.
</P>
<P>
   ''In my childhood I learned under the MPRP, and I was educated
and brought up by the MPRP,'' said S. Chimet, a retired soldier in
Ulan Bator. ''So my whole life has been under the MPRP.''
</P>
<P>
   Though Mongolia has emerged from the fuel shortages and empty
store shelves of the early 1990s, the rapid pace of change has
taken its toll.
</P>
<P>
   Street children spend the winters sleeping next to subterranean
hot-water pipes to keep warm in the capital, and more than
one-third the population lives under the poverty line. Unemployment
can hit 65 percent in some towns.
</P>
<P>
   Much of voter distaste for the reformists also came from the
appearance of dirty politicking and influence-peddling. Three
members of the reformist coalition were jailed in a casino scandal,
and the murder of a popular Cabinet minister and pro-democracy
figure has gone unsolved.
</P>
<P>
   ''The people of Mongolia are hesitating and wondering about
democracy because of the democratic parties' policies,'' said
Gandi, an MPRP lawmaker. Like many Mongolians, she only uses one
name.
</P>
<P>
   Still, given the changes that a decade of democracy and
capitalism have brought to Mongolia, it's hard to imagine things
could ever return to the way they were.
</P>
<P>
   The first floors of dozens of Soviet-style apartment blocks have
been rapidly transformed into privately owned shops. Cellular
phones -- unheard of only a year ago -- have become a rage in the
past few months.
</P>
<P>
   Economic growth hit a respectable 3.3 percent last year. And the
role of the private sector in gross domestic product has risen from
3 percent a decade ago to about 70 percent today.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the lopsided victory in Sunday's election, few
Mongolians really expected a return to state control of the
economy. Too much, they say, has already changed.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's impossible to bring back the old system,'' said
Nyamdulam, a computer engineer in Ulan Bator.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-07-03-00 1447 </TRAILER>
