<HEADLINE> Buffalo homicide rate cause for alarm  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   BUFFALO, N.Y. (AP) - Halfway through 2000, Buffalo homicides
were running 61 percent ahead of last year, leading some to wonder
if the city's five-year trend of decreasing murder rates is about
to end.
</P>
<P>
   The first half of this year ended June 30 with a total of 21
killings, compared to 13 homicides for the same time period a year
ago.
</P>
<P>
   ''We're not sure what to attribute the rise in the numbers to,''
said Homicide Chief Joseph Riga, ''but you have to keep in mind
that we're coming off a substantially low number of homicides for
1999.''
</P>
<P>
   There were 32 city homicides in all of last year.
</P>
<P>
   Deputy Police Commissioner Mark Blankenberg said an overall
slackening of discipline in homes and schools seems to have created
a lack of respect for others among young people.
</P>
<P>
   ''The 'me generation' may have something to do with this,'' he
told The Buffalo News. ''These people don't care what they do, even
if it affects hundreds of other people. They just care about
themselves and don't want anyone to get in their way.''
</P>
<P>
   Elsewhere in the state, Rochester recorded 23 murders in the
first six months of the year, compared with 21 last year. There
were three Albany homicides, compared with 10 during the first half
of last year.
</P>
<P>
   New York City, meanwhile, recorded 333 murders, a 2.4 percent
rise over the same period in 1999.
</P>
<P>
   In Buffalo early Saturday, Darian Clark, 28, and a friend were
standing outside a private social club arguing with two men when
another man walked up and shot Clark between the eyes, police said.
</P>
<P>
   The slaying was the third in four days. A motive remains
unknown.
</P>
<P>
   In other cases, Jericho Stock, 30, was fatally shot in the back
Thursday while talking on a pay phone. On Wednesday, John McCain,
24, was shot several times in front of his home. Police said
McCain's shooter was a friend of a 13-year-old teen-ager whom
McCain had been fighting.
</P>
<P>
   Homicide rates have been decreasing in Buffalo since 1995, when
there were 62 killings, down from a high of 92 in 1994.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
