<HEADLINE> Russian Bribery of Traffic Cops Up  </HEADLINE>
By NICK WADHAMS
<TEXT>
<P>
   MOSCOW (AP) -- They can be seen pacing up and down the dividing
line or standing in wait at tricky corners where motorists will
sometimes bend the rules to save a few minutes on Russia's decrepit
roads.
</P>
<P>
   They are the traffic police, known for their gray uniforms and
the white and black batons that flash out to wave a driver to the
curb. And they are also known for their love of bribes, large and
small.
</P>
<P>
   It is one of the most notable displays of corruption pervading
Russian life, and hundreds of jokes poke fun at the payoff-prone
cop. There were plenty told on Monday, the 64th anniversary of the
State Traffic Control Inspectorate. Officers nationwide -- those who
weren't on duty -- held celebrations to mark the holiday.
</P>
<P>
   Even police acknowledge bribe-taking is a fact of life, but say
traffic cops aren't the only ones to blame.
</P>
<P>
   ''Bribes are accepted because they are offered,'' said traffic
inspectorate spokeswoman Lyudmila Tosheva. ''There's no such case
where you can blame one side or the other.''
</P>
<P>
   Though they lament the corruption, some drivers find relief in
the institution. A bribe is often an easy way to avoid the
bureaucratic hassles of paying for a formally issued ticket.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's an old habit,'' said Sergei Pozhedayev, a sales manager
at a Moscow auto shop. ''If you break the law a little, just give
them 50 rubles ($1.70) and you go on your way.''
</P>
<P>
   Russian law allows police officers to confiscate motorists'
licenses for even minor violations, meaning the driver usually has
to spend half a day paying a fine at the bank and going to the
police with a receipt to get the license back.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's very convenient,'' said a Moscow driver who identified
himself as Sergei. ''Let's say that I haven't gotten my car
inspected and I get stopped, it's a lot easier for me to slip a
little money into his pocket on the spot.''
</P>
<P>
   The lack of discipline has its dangers. Though the country has a
zero-tolerance law for drunk drivers, policemen will look the other
way for a price, though it could cost hundreds of dollars.
</P>
<P>
   The chief of Russia's traffic police, Lt. Gen. Vladimir
Fyodorov, said Monday that 29,000 people died in traffic accidents
in Russia last year. In the United States, the number was more than
41,000, but Russia has far fewer cars on the road because they are
too expensive for most Russians.
</P>
<P>
   Bribes are also a crucial source of income for traffic cops,
whose salaries hover around $60 a month. Some drivers sympathize.
</P>
<P>
   ''We all have to get by somehow,'' said 23-year-old Yuri
Abramov, a truck driver. ''That's how they do it -- by taking from
us.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-07-03-00 1512 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000703.0080 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-03 15:13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Penguins Starving in South Africa  </HEADLINE>
By MIKE COHEN
<TEXT>
<P>
   DASSEN ISLAND, South Africa (AP) -- Penguin chicks began to die
from starvation Monday on an island off South Africa's west coast
after their parents were evacuated to save them from an oil spill.
</P>
<P>
   Dozens of dead chicks lay in their burrows on Dassen Island.
Hundreds of other weakened baby birds' ribs stuck out. Seagulls
attacked unattended chicks.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's very difficult to take adults off nests when we know the
chicks are going to be abandoned ... but all us realize it's the
only option we have at the moment,'' said Anton Wolfhaardt, manager
of the island nature reserve. ''If we are able to save as many
adult birds as we can, those birds can come back and start
breeding.''
</P>
<P>
   Dassen Island's total population of African penguins is more
than 55,000 -- the world's largest colony of the endangered birds,
which are found only off the coast of southern Africa. More than
5,000 birds were captured Monday for evacuation, Wolfhaardt said.
That was in addition to more than 3,000 caught and shipped out
Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   The problem here began last Wednesday, when an oil slick from
the tanker Treasure, which sank June 23 off the coast of Cape Town,
reached Dassen Island, about 37 miles northwest of the city. The
penguins were fenced in Friday to stop them from going into the
polluted sea to fish.
</P>
<P>
   But the fences had to be removed to avoid starving the birds on
the island. Left with no other choice, workers began hauling the
birds from their burrows Sunday and evacuating them.
</P>
<P>
   Conservationists had insufficient resources to relocate the
entire colony. Those birds that were not captured by Monday were to
be allowed to return to the sea to feed and take their chances with
the slick.
</P>
<P>
   The uncontaminated birds captured on Dassen Island, meanwhile,
were shipped to the mainland, trucked about eight hours up the
coast and released to fend for themselves. More than 3,000 of the
penguins were released into the ocean 560 miles up the coast Monday
to begin the long swim home.
</P>
<P>
   They are expected to swim home within about 11 days. Authorities
hope that will give them enough time to clean up the spill.
</P>
<P>
   The birds had dealt very well with the ordeal of being put in
boxes, taken by boat and helicopter off the island and then trucked
to the town of Port Elizabeth, said Aletta van der Merwe, a
spokeswoman for Western Cape Nature Conservation. ''We only had one
mortality and three minor injuries,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, rehabilitation centers in Cape Town battled to feed
an estimated 20,000 oil-coated penguins, most of which were taken
off Robben Island, about four miles off the coast.
</P>
<P>
   Rehabilitating the oil-coated birds will be a mammoth task -- it
takes two people about an hour to clean each bird. Once cleaned,
the birds need to be hand-fed for up to two months before their
coats again become waterproof so that they can swim in the sea.
</P>
<P>
   ''We need more than 1,000 volunteers a day, and got half of this
yesterday,'' said Christina Pretorius, a spokeswoman for the
Southern African National Foundation for the Conservation of
Coastal Birds.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-07-03-00 1513 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000703.0081 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-03 15:17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Cow 'doctor' hired to repair statues from vandals  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   STAMFORD, Conn. (AP) - A cow ''doctor'' has been hired to repair
Fiberglas cows vandalized by people who have tipped, scratched and
ripped off horns from the decorative bovines on display downtown.
</P>
<P>
   About a dozen cow statues have been damaged since being put on
show last month in Stamford. A total of 67 life-size decorated cows
are scattered throughout the city center in a whimsical public art
exhibit.
</P>
<P>
   One cow near the Stamford branch of the University of
Connecticut was tipped over and had a horn ripped off, while a red
nose on a ''hobo cow'' at Veterans Park has been stolen twice. A
golf club was snatched from the mouth of another cow. Still others
have been scratched, or have missing eyelashes and earrings.
</P>
<P>
   Andrew Munce, a Redding artist who has been hired to repair the
statutes, has been dubbed ''The Cow Doctor'' by Sandra Goldstein,
executive director of the Downtown Special Services District, the
agency sponsoring the cow display.
</P>
<P>
   ''I think our biggest problem really relates to the fact that
people have too much love for these cows,'' Goldstein said.
</P>
<P>
   ''There is so much interaction between the cows and hundreds of
children who come and sit on, kiss and hug the cows.''
</P>
<P>
   Whenever a cow is damaged, Munce makes repairs.
</P>
<P>
   ''I've dealt with everything from (damage caused) by banging and
scratching on the paint to things being broken off,'' said Munce, a
metal sculptor.
</P>
<P>
   Similar problems have been reported in other cities with cow
displays.
</P>
<P>
   In New York City last week, a cow on display in the Richmond
Heights section of Queens was stolen. It was later recovered. Some
of the cows have also been covered by graffiti.
</P>
<P>
   In Buffalo, N.Y., statues of bison have been vandalized. One of
the buffaloes was tipped over and had a horn pulled off.
</P>
<P>
   The CowParade in Stamford is funded by a $50,000 state art grant
and corporate and individual sponsors who paid $7,500 for each cow.
</P>
<P>
   A ''cattle auction'' will be held in October with 75 percent of
the proceeds donated to the charity of the buyer's choice.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
