<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-03 15:18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Report: FBI believes municipal judge had role in Passaic County bribery scheme </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   HACKENSACK, N.J. (AP) - The FBI believes a lawyer who serves as
a Municipal Court judge for Totowa was the middleman for a bribery
scheme in which the former Passaic County administrator has been
charged, according to a published report.
</P>
<P>
   The judge, Albert C. Lisbona, has not been charged.
</P>
<P>
   FBI agents in the case against the ex-administrator, Nicola R.
DiDonna, said Lisbona made several telephone calls to advance the
scheme, according to two sworn statements they filed that were
reviewed by The Record of Hackensack.
</P>
<P>
   The documents do not say whether Lisbona profited from his role.
</P>
<P>
   DiDonna, who was Passaic's top appointed official when indicted
in September, faces trial this fall.
</P>
<P>
   The three-year investigation into corruption in Passaic County
has garnered guilty pleas from several officials, including a
former state assemblyman, A. Joseph ''Buddy'' Fortunato.
</P>
<P>
   In 1994, Fortunato was a consultant for Central Medical Services
Inc., of Union, and wanted to speak to Passaic County GOP chairman
Peter Murphy to win a county contract for his client. At the time,
the county freeholders were all Republicans.
</P>
<P>
   Lisbona, a close associate of Murphy, introduced Fortunato to
Murphy, according to one of the affidavits.
</P>
<P>
   Prosecutors said they developed a plan for Fortunato to funnel
bribes to four Murphy associates, and Central Medical got several
contracts for work at the Passaic County Jail.
</P>
<P>
   The ''advisory panel'' did no actual work, federal prosecutors
maintain. The panelists or their attorneys have denied that the
payments were bribes, the newspaper said. Murphy and its members
have not been charged.
</P>
<P>
   In Monday's editions, the newspaper said Lisbona declined
repeated requests for an interview and that his attorney, Anthony
R. Mautone, did not return telephone calls seeking comment.
</P>
<P>
   Lisbona and Mautone did not immediately return messages from The
Associated Press left Monday, when their offices appeared to be
closed for the upcoming Fourth of July holiday.
</P>
<P>
   Lisbona, a municipal judge since January 1978 and a lawyer for
32 years, has no disciplinary action pending against him, David E.
Johnson Jr., director of the state Supreme Court's Office of
Attorney Ethics, said Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Federal officials involved in the DiDonna case did not return
messages Monday seeking comment on Lisbona.
</P>
<P>
   Fortunato met with Murphy and DiDonna at Murphy's restaurant in
Totowa in May 1994. Murphy said Central Medical would get work if
the company made payments to four people, and DiDonna ''stated that
he would give CMSI work in the prison system,'' one affidavit said.
</P>
<P>
   Lisbona later called Fortunato and told him to get the names of
the ''advisory panel'' from Murphy. The four were Undersheriff John
Bonazzi; DiDonna's father, Joseph, who has since died; Totowa Tax
Assessor Curt Masklee, and Totowa Democrat Joseph DiPasquale,
according to court papers.
</P>
<P>
   DiDonna recommended Central Medical to the freeholders, who
awarded the company a contract in July 1994.
</P>
<P>
   The panelists got their first payments in October 1994, and
Lisbona ''intermittently telephoned CMSI's principals to tell them
when it was time to make subsequent payments to the panel,'' an
affidavit said.
</P>
<P>
   At one point, the company was late in making payments.
''According to Fortunato ... Lisbona contacted Fortunato and
indicated that Murphy was angry because the panel had not been
paid,'' it said.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to Fortunato, who cooperated with investigators,
agents who prepared the affidavits relied on conversations secretly
recorded by the company's two founders as early as 1996, the
newspaper said.
</P>
<P>
   Lisbona is a partner in the Fairfield law firm of Dwyer, Connell
&AMP; Lisbona. Over the past decade, it has earned $3.3 million working
for the county and has given at least $41,000 in political
contributions to county Republicans, The Record said.
</P>
<P>
   The indictment against DiDonna charged he worked with an unnamed
''party official to steer lucrative contracts'' totaling $900,000
to an unnamed contractor in exchange for the contractor paying
$70,000 to politically connected people chosen by the party
official.
</P>
<P>
   Murphy is the official, according to unnamed sources cited by
The Record.
</P>
<P>
   Of the payments, $17,000 went to DiDonna's father, who ran a
construction business in Clifton and died in March 1999.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
