<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-03 15:35 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Federal program helps disabled people find jobs, become independent </HEADLINE>
By DEEPTI HAJELA
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) - Samuel Vasquez can measure his freedom.
</P>
<P>
   He does it every day, when he climbs the narrow, double-helix
staircase that winds from the pedestal to the crown of the Statue
of Liberty. Up one set of 146 steps, then down, sweeping them along
the way. Then repeating on the other staircase.
</P>
<P>
   Cleaning those 292 steps once a day, five days a week, is part
of Vasquez's job as part of the custodial team that maintains the
interior of the statue. It's a job that the learning-disabled
36-year-old got through a federal act that provides work
opportunities for disabled Americans.
</P>
<P>
   He doesn't climb up the stairs, he sprints up, a physical sign
of how much he loves his job and appreciates how far he's come from
the days of working whatever construction or seasonal work he could
find.
</P>
<P>
   ''Before, I didn't have that confidence ... At the time, I was
living day-to-day,'' he said. Now, ''I make more than I ever made
in my life.''
</P>
<P>
   The Javits-Wagner-O'Day Act allows the U.S. government to buy
some goods and services from disabled people through contracts with
numerous nonprofit community agencies around the country, such as
Fedcap Rehabilitation Services, the New York-based agency Vasquez
works for. Goods can include anything from military clothing to
office supplies, and services can range from food service to
medical transcription.
</P>
<P>
   For Vasquez, whose dyslexia had him dropping out of high school
after 10th grade, his custodial job has meant employee benefits, a
salary high enough to let him send one of his daughters to Catholic
school, a new car, and he hopes, a business of his own soon.
</P>
<P>
   It's a level of financial freedom and hope for his future that
the Staten Island resident never had before.
</P>
<P>
   ''I would get frustrated, I would give up. ... Every time I
wanted to go fill an application out, I didn't understand what it
said,'' Vasquez said.
</P>
<P>
   He used to rely on government aid. Not anymore.
</P>
<P>
   ''I would never want to go back to letting the government
support me,'' Vasquez said recently, looking out of Lady Liberty's
crown. ''Through this job, I know ... what independence is.''
</P>
<P>
   Under the 1938 Wagner-O'Day Act, agencies that helped blind
people were allowed to sell brooms and mops the blind made to the
government. In 1971, after a push led by Sen. Jacob Javits, it was
amended to include Americans with other disabilities as well.
</P>
<P>
   The program is administered by an independent federal agency
which decides which items and services the government will buy and
at what price.
</P>
<P>
   Then two nonprofit agencies, the National Industries for the
Blind and NISH (formerly the National Institute for the Severely
Handicapped), funnel the contracts to local community organizations
around the country.
</P>
<P>
   More than 30,000 disabled people around the country have gotten
jobs through the program, and the projects generated more than $700
million in sales in fiscal year 1999.
</P>
<P>
   Local agencies train participants in the program for their jobs,
and then pay them after they start working, said Susan Fonfa,
executive director of Fedcap.
</P>
<P>
   Fedcap employs more than 1,400 people at sites throughout the
New York metropolitan area. Vasquez is one of 15 employed through a
contract with the National Parks Service to maintain the statue and
Ellis Island.
</P>
<P>
   ''We work with people who have never worked, or who haven't been
successful,'' Fonfa said. ''They are really learning to be workers.
They are very proud of what they do.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
