<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-03 15:40 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Harry Potter Fans Awaiting Big Day  </HEADLINE>
By BETH GARDINER
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- The countdown is more suspenseful than a
high-stakes game of Quidditch. The anxiety can't even be cured by
one of Professor Severus Snape's magic potions.
</P>
<P>
   Devotees of the Harry Potter books that have captured the
imaginations of millions of readers have only days to wait before
they can lose themselves in the fourth installment of the boy
wizard's magical adventures.
</P>
<P>
   An unprecedented 5.3 million copies of ''Harry Potter and the
Goblet of Fire'' will be released Saturday in the United States and
Britain. For any other children's book, even 500,000 is considered
a large first printing.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's a once-in-a-generation kind of thing,'' said Diane
Roback, children's books editor at Publishers Weekly.
</P>
<P>
   Bookstores around the country are planning Harry Potter parties
and staying open late so they can sell ''Goblet of Fire'' at 12:01
a.m. on publication day. In Britain, author J.K. Rowling will start
a promotional train tour at ''Platform 9&AMP;frac34;'' of London's Kings Cross
Station, where Harry and friends catch the train each fall to
Hogwarts School of Witchcraft and Wizardry.
</P>
<P>
   Advance orders of the book have pushed it to No. 1 on
Amazon.com's best-seller list for 16 of the past 21 weeks, and the
first three volumes occupy three of the fifteen spots on The New
York Times list.
</P>
<P>
   Amazon has already sold more than 265,000 copies of ''Goblet of
Fire.'' That dwarfs Amazon's biggest previous advance sale, 43,000
copies of John Grisham's ''The Brethren.''
</P>
<P>
   A Wal-Mart in Virginia broke the embargo last week when it put
the books on shelves. About 20 copies were sold to lucky youngsters
before the store realized the books weren't supposed to be out and
quickly removed them, a Wal-Mart spokesman said. Another store in
Virginia also jumped the gun.
</P>
<P>
   A wall of secrecy as impenetrable as that surrounding the
devious scheming of Harry's nemesis Voldemort has guarded the
book's plot, heightening fans' anticipation.
</P>
<P>
   ''There is nothing you could compare this to,'' said Linda
Wilkinson, manager of Adventures for Kids, a bookstore in Ventura,
Calif. ''We've been planning for months now, and we're getting
close to the countdown.''
</P>
<P>
   Many booksellers credit the Potter series with boosting sales of
children's literature generally and bringing new popularity to
fantasy stories, which have been overshadowed in recent years by
more reality-based children's books, such as those by Judy Blume.
</P>
<P>
   How has a generation of kids raised on video games and the
Internet become so wrapped up in the twisting, turning, multivolume
tale of an orphaned young wizard?
</P>
<P>
   Most credit Rowling's storytelling skills. The first three books
chronicle Harry's miserable life with his aunt and uncle, Vernon
and Petunia Dursley, his initiation into a world of magic at
Hogwarts, and his plunge into a series of life-and-death adventures
with pals Ron Weasley and Hermione Granger.
</P>
<P>
   The stories are packed with clever bits of fancy -- every-flavor
jelly beans that taste like liver, tripe and sprouts, a vicious
three-headed dog named Fluffy and the Nimbus 2000, a high-velocity
flying broom used for playing Quidditch, wizardry's favorite sport.
</P>
<P>
   Harry ''is a lonely boy who's rescued from a wretched
existence,'' said Publishers Weekly's Roback. ''He goes to this
boarding school where he has these magical powers, and he's treated
like a hero. He goes from rags to riches, and that's really
appealing to kids. He's an every-kid that a lot of kids can relate
to.''
</P>
<P>
   Fantasy books have long been a staple of children's literature --
C.S. Lewis' Narnia series, Madeleine L'Engle's ''A Wrinkle in
Time'' and J.R.R. Tolkien's ''Lord of the Rings'' are all classics.
But in recent years, more popular kids' books have focused on real
life, taking place in schools and dealing with issues like family
trouble and problems with friends.
</P>
<P>
   Booksellers say the runaway success of the Potter series is
helping revive children's interest in fantasy books.
</P>
<P>
   ''Almost nothing in their lives is left up to imagination
anymore, because of television, because of video games that are so
violent,'' said Caron Chapman, executive director of the
Minneapolis-based Association of Booksellers for Children. ''The
balance tipped on the side of overload on facts and reality, and it
now needs to be balanced with a little more daydreaming and a
little more imagination.''
</P>
<P>
   But will grade-schoolers really be willing to crack a 752-page
book (the British edition, with different design and illustrations,
is closer to 600 pages), even if it does star a character they
already know?
</P>
<P>
   Roback said that the length is unusual and that the youngest
readers might find it daunting. Older children, though, are
unlikely to be deterred, particularly if they are already hooked on
Harry, she said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-07-03-00 1540 </TRAILER>
