<DOCNO> APW20000703.0086 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-03 15:41 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 54 Killed in Chechen Truck Bombings  </HEADLINE>
By LYOMA TURPALOV
<TEXT>
<P>
   ARGUN, Russia (AP) -- Federal troops cordoned off Chechen cities
Monday and began a widespread security sweep, hunting for rebels a
day after four towns were hit by suicide truck bombings that killed
at least 54 people.
</P>
<P>
   Sunday's attacks marked the biggest setback for Russian forces
in Chechnya in months.
</P>
<P>
   In one town Monday, emergency workers tugged bodies from a
military dormitory sheared apart by a blast. Meanwhile, police
swept Russian-held cities for rebels. Security agents detained 18
people on suspicion of involvement in the rapid succession of five
bombings, Deputy Interior Minister Ivan Golubev said on Russian
television.
</P>
<P>
   In the attacks, trucks loaded with explosives barreled up to
Russian buildings in four Chechen towns -- Argun, Urus-Martan,
Novogroznensky and Gudermes, Chechnya's second-largest city and
home to the pro-Moscow Chechen government. Russian troops opened
fire on the trucks and caused the explosions in all but one of the
incidents, said the Kremlin's spokesman on Chechnya, Sergei
Yastrzhembsky.
</P>
<P>
   Officials said at least 37 Russian servicemen, 11 civilians and
six rebels were killed. In addition, four Russian servicemen were
missing, the Emergency Situations Ministry reported. More than 100
people were wounded.
</P>
<P>
   ''This was a planned action to carry out terrorist acts in five
towns,'' Chechen rebel commander Ramzan Akhmadov said by telephone
Monday.
</P>
<P>
   It was the rebels' most organized, deadly attack in months, and
it came after weeks of Russian claims that organized resistance had
ended in the breakaway republic. The rebels have unleashed a string
of scattered ambushes that Chechen commanders say are in reply to
those Russian claims of victory.
</P>
<P>
   Russian troops were driven out of Chechnya in a 1994-96 war.
They returned late last summer after Chechnya-based Islamic
militants raided several villages in the neighboring Russian region
of Dagestan, and after about 300 people died in apartment bombings
the government blames on Chechens.
</P>
<P>
   In a videotaped message cited by the Interfax news agency
Monday, Chechen President Aslan Maskhadov said that the rebels'
latest tactics ''leave the Russian troops no chance of establishing
control in Chechnya.''
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, Russian troops barred all nonmilitary traffic in the
capital, Grozny, and the four towns. Military officials sent
reinforcement troops, citing reports of more expected attacks.
</P>
<P>
   ''What happened demands that we should become more vigilant and
use measures that will prevent bandits from fulfilling their
vicious designs,'' said the first deputy of the army's general
staff, Col. Gen. Valery Manilov.
</P>
<P>
   The deadliest bombing targeted an Interior Ministry dormitory on
the outskirts of Argun, nine miles east of Grozny.
</P>
<P>
   The bomb left a deep crater in the asphalt. On one end of the
building, the servicemen's metal bunk beds were still lined up --
but the outside wall was sliced off.
</P>
<P>
   Vasara Vesitaya, a worker in the dormitory cafeteria, left for
home three minutes before the blast.
</P>
<P>
   ''I left the fence and suddenly saw a huge truck coming at high
speed. It crashed through the barrier and then something horrible
began. The glass from windows in surrounding houses shattered, the
earth shook,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   The Emergency Situations Ministry said 26 servicemen and three
civilians were killed in Argun and four were missing.
</P>
<P>
   The other servicemen and civilians were killed in two truck
bombings and an ensuing shootout in Gudermes, one truck blast in
Urus-Martan, south of Grozny, and one truck blast in
Novogroznensky, in eastern Chechnya. All are in territory the
Russians ostensibly control.
</P>
<P>
   One of the Gudermes blasts killed civilians working in their
backyard garden nearby.
</P>
<P>
   ''Innocent people perish in these terrorist acts,'' Mayerbek
Askhadov said at the funeral for his cousin, a slain Chechen
policeman.
</P>
<P>
   Russian officials say some rebels have hidden among civilians
and are using weapons caches hidden in Russian-held territory.
</P>
<P>
   But others blamed a lack of discipline among Russian troops,
including heavy drinking and bribe-taking. Defense Minister Igor
Sergeyev, speaking to journalists in Moscow, urged ''improving
discipline and diligence in the federal forces.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
