<HEADLINE> Giuliani criticizes Con Ed rate hike  </HEADLINE>
By TIMOTHY WILLIAMS
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) - After recent power failures and news of a
possible 30 percent hike in electric bills this summer, Mayor
Rudolph Giuliani escalated his war against Con Edison on Monday,
slamming the utility as ''incompetent.''
</P>
<P>
   ''This is the wrong time to be discussing a rate hike with a
company that does not appear to be serving the public the way the
public wants to be served,'' Giuliani said at a City Hall Park news
conference.
</P>
<P>
   ''We're already paying a lot of money for power, for
electricity, and to say all of a sudden, 'We want 30 percent more,'
when we've already had a blackout in Washington Heights last year
(and) an almost blackout or brownout on the Upper East Side of
Manhattan'' is unacceptable, he said.
</P>
<P>
   The threatened rate hike, Giuliani added, is ''outrageous. The
timing of it is as about as crazy as it could possibly be.'' The
mayor said the utility's performance has been ''incompetent.''
</P>
<P>
   Con Edison responded with a statement, saying that electricity
rates would indeed be higher this summer due to tight oil supply,
the city's booming economy, higher fuel costs and an increase in
customer demand. Con Ed officials declined to discuss figures or
say whether the report of a 30 percent increase was accurate.
</P>
<P>
   ''We deliver power as cheaply as we can,'' read the statement.
''We are all adjusting to new realities and taking steps to meet
the new challenge.''
</P>
<P>
   Last week, the utility warned that due to high oil prices and
high demand it may not be able to supply sufficient power to
prevent brownouts and blackouts this summer.
</P>
<P>
   Con Edison has been under fire since July, 1999, when a blackout
paralyzed Washington Heights for 19 hours during a heat wave and
officials gave conflicting accounts about its cause.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, a brownout reduced power to several buildings on the
Upper East Side of Manhattan during 90-degree heat and 95 percent
humidity.
</P>
<P>
   In both cases, the utility blamed faulty feeder cables. The city
has a lawsuit pending against Con Edison regarding the Washington
Heights blackout; the city said last week that a proposed
settlement had unraveled, but Giuliani said Monday that the talks
were continuing.
</P>
<P>
   The mayor said that for now, Con Edison should hold off on rate
increases.
</P>
<P>
   ''The first thing I would ask them to do is withhold any
decision on any kind of rate hike because obviously it would never
be well received, but it's going to be particularly poorly received
right now,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
