<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-03 16:18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Carper wins on education reform, loses on gun control in last year  </HEADLINE>
By CHRISTOPHER THORNE
<TEXT>
<P>
   DOVER, Del. (AP) - Gov. Tom Carper got his way this year with a
controversial law that holds teachers responsible for how well they
teach in the classroom.
</P>
<P>
   Overall, the two-term Democrat saw many of his legislative goals
adopted by a General Assembly that wrapped up most of its business
early Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   Lawmakers adopted his proposal to allow digital signatures on
electronic legal and business transactions. Legislators also OK'd
most of his $2.18 billion operating budget, which includes millions
of dollars for open space and farmland preservation.
</P>
<P>
   But Carper failed in the last of his eight years as Delaware's
governor to persuade the General Assembly to adopt gun control
legislation to close what he describes as a loophole that could
allow felons to buy handguns. It was a top goal in his final year
as chief executive of this tiny mid-Atlantic state.
</P>
<P>
   The Senate must return in a special session to approve the $543
million capital improvements budget, because it broke up without
considering the bill. This is the second year in a row the Senate
has had to return in a summertime special session to approve the
capital budget.
</P>
<P>
   ''If you look back at the beginning of the 140th General
Assembly, there's a great deal of good that has been done,'' Carper
told reporters in a teleconference Monday. ''Without question the
biggest accomplishment this session, in this General Assembly, has
been our work on the education front.''
</P>
<P>
   The teacher bill didn't come easy. The legislation was left over
from last year when it failed to pass through the General Assembly.
Then the lawmakers embarrassed Carper in October when he called an
ineffective special session, only to see the Senate adjourn before
getting the bill from the House.
</P>
<P>
   This session Carper forged a compromise with legislative leaders
that saw the bill win final approval.
</P>
<P>
   A deal was out of his reach, however, for a law that would have
required background checks in private purchases of firearms,
whether the sale takes place at flea markets and gun shows or in
someone's home.
</P>
<P>
   Licensed firearms dealers currently run instant background
checks to prevent felons from buying guns. But Delaware has no law
requiring similar checks for sales between private individuals.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Harris McDowell, a North Wilmington Democrat, introduced a
bill that would have required background checks before a gun could
be sold privately. But McDowell withdrew the legislation after
testy debate on the Senate floor.
</P>
<P>
   ''There's a loophole that we've sought to plug in this past
legislative session that's already been plugged in New Jersey,
Pennsylvania and Maryland,'' Carper said. ''We simply thought it
should be plugged here. I think eventually it will be.''
</P>
<P>
   Two other bills which would have mandated trigger locks on
handguns never got out of Senate committee.
</P>
<P>
   John Thompson, president of the Delaware State Sportsmen's
Association, an affiliate of the National Rifle Association,
described McDowell's bill as an ''attack'' on law-abiding
gun-owners.
</P>
<P>
   He said Carper's gun-control efforts were a public relations
ploy intended to help him to higher political office.
</P>
<P>
   Carper intends to file papers July 17 to challenge Republican
U.S. Sen. William V. Roth Jr. for his seat, but insisted he
believes the private sales loophole is worth pursuing on its
merits.
</P>
<P>
   ''That's a loophole that has been plugged in all the state's
around us,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-07-03-00 1618 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000703.0095 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-03 16:26 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Coast Guard says harbor is filling up with ships and boats  </HEADLINE>
By RICHARD PYLE
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) - This city's broad, picturesque harbor teemed on
Monday with thousands of vessels, from oceangoing schooners to
destroyers to small recreational craft, in the run-up to the Fourth
of July's nautical spectacular.
</P>
<P>
   As lesser-sized sailing ships came down the East River to join
in Operation Sail 2000, the centerpiece of the event, about two
dozen warships from 13 countries steamed up the Hudson from the
Narrows. The warships anchored in an 11-mile line as participants
in history's sixth International Naval Review.
</P>
<P>
   The main event will be the ''parade of sail,'' about 30 large
wind-powered ships from 19 countries which enter the harbor on
Tuesday and pass up the Hudson before dispersing to assigned
berths. Most, like the Coast Guard's square-rigger Eagle, are
government-owned training vessels for sailors.
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton will review the naval ships, then go aboard
the aircraft carrier USS John F. Kennedy, anchored in mid-harbor,
to watch the sail procession.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, a haze enveloped the harbor, cutting spectators'
visibility but not their enthusiasm.
</P>
<P>
   ''I love it. They're beautiful,'' said Pauline Allen, spending
her lunch hour at the Battery promenade at Manhattan's southern
tip, watching the tall ships and navy vessels. ''I'm waiting for
that warship to come in,'' she said, pointing to a hulking vessel
barely visible in the haze. ''I want to see what's on it.''
</P>
<P>
   Coast Guard Warrant Officer Lionel Bryant estimated some 5,000
craft of all kinds were in the waters between the Verazzano Narrows
bridge and the Battery.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's unbelievable. I've never seen so many boats at once,''
said Bryant. One group of about 100 sailboats, ''probably from the
same yacht club,'' arrived in a group down the East River.
</P>
<P>
   Bryant said the Coast Guard was holding to its prediction of as
many as 70,000 craft of all kinds for the joint holiday
celebration, capped by what organizers say will be the biggest
fireworks orgy ever.
</P>
<P>
   Secretary of the Navy Richard Danzig, who toured the Naval
Review command post on a Hudson River pier, called OpSail 2000 ''a
wonderful opportunity for the city of New York and the Navy to
combine together to display the nature of sea power.''
</P>
<P>
   ''It captures a sense of what extraordinary history this has
through the old ships, the tall ships,'' Danzig said in an
interview. ''At the same time it emphasizes the extraordinary
present-day relevance of naval power. Seventy percent of the globe
is water, and we're able to operate from the sea everywhere. The
Navy really is everywhere for America.''
</P>
<P>
   Among the arrivals on Monday was the 129-foot schooner Amistad,
a replica of the ship made famous when its slave cargo of 53
Africans revolted in 1839. Launched March 25 in Mystic, Conn., it
will be homeported in New Haven, where it will be a floating
history lesson for schoolchildren.
</P>
<P>
   Its captain, William Pinkney, was the first black man to sail
around the world via the southern ocean. ''That's the ne plus ultra
of solo sailing,'' said Pinkney, 64. ''Limited to those who are not
wrapped too tight.''
</P>
<P>
   ''I think it's very exciting,'' said Selma Feldman, peering at
the ships through binoculars at the Battery promenade. ''The Statue
of Liberty looks so impressive, doesn't it?''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-07-03-00 1626 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000703.0096 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-03 16:33 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Probes Consultant for Bribery  </HEADLINE>
By MICHAEL J. SNIFFEN
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- The Justice Department is investigating
whether a financial consultant bribed Kazakstan officials with
money belonging to major oil companies who wanted to work in the
oil-rich nation, a federal law enforcement official said Monday.
</P>
<P>
   The activities of James H. Giffen, chairman of the New
York-based consulting firm Mercator Corp., are being investigated
by the department's Organized Crime and Racketeering Section, this
official said.
</P>
<P>
   The department sent a letter to Swiss officials last month
seeking their cooperation because some of the money may have moved
through Swiss bank accounts, said this official, who requested
anonymity.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. Foreign Corrupt Practices Act makes it a crime to bribe
foreign officials for favorable treatment.
</P>
<P>
   The Wall Street Journal obtained a copy of the department's
18-page June 12 letter to Swiss authorities and quoted an
unidentified law enforcement official as saying the oil companies,
including units of the former Amoco Corp., the former Mobil Oil
Corp. and Phillips Petroleum Co., are not themselves the focus of
the investigation at this point.
</P>
<P>
   Giffen, 59, has been a financial consultant to Kazakstan's
president for most of a decade in negotiations with oil companies
that want to do business in the former Soviet republic.
</P>
<P>
   The letter said the Department ''is investigating James H.
Giffen, a U.S. citizen, and others for violations of U.S. law
involving the alleged use of U.S. banks to funnel funds belonging
to certain oil companies through Swiss bank accounts and shell
companies in Switzerland and the British Virgin Islands for
ultimate transfer to present and former high-ranking officials of
Kazakstan,'' the Journal reported.
</P>
<P>
   The letter said the money belonged to Amoco Kazakstan Petroleum
Co., Amoco Kazakstan (CPC) Inc., Mobil Oil Corp. and Philips
Petroleum Kazakstan Ltd., the paper reported.
</P>
<P>
   Investigators are looking into possible violations of the
Foreign Corrupt Practices Act, as well as statutes on Racketeer
Influenced and Corrupt Organizations, money laundering, stolen
property and extortion, the paper quoted the letter as saying.
</P>
<P>
   The Journal reported the letter also said:
</P>
<P>
   --Investigators have information that shows payments of at least
$115 million were made from the U.S. bank accounts of several
international oil companies to a numbered account, held at Bankers
Trust in New York, belonging to an unidentified Swiss bank. Justice
investigators want information about that numbered account, from
which they believe disbursements were made to Giffen.
</P>
<P>
   --The Justice Department wants Switzerland to freeze Giffen's
assets.
</P>
<P>
   --Giffen is alleged to have passed nearly $60 million from the
numbered account to bank accounts controlled by the Kazak
president, Nursultan Nazarbayev, 60; a former Kazak prime minister,
Akezhan Kazhegeldin, 48; and Nurlan Balgimbayev, 52, another former
prime minister and current head of the Kazak state oil company.
Members of their families also were alleged to be beneficiaries.
</P>
<P>
   An attorney for Kazhegeldin told the Journal his client received
a $6 million payment in 1997 and tried unsuccessfully to return it.
</P>
<P>
   Giffen's lawyer, Mark MacDougall, told the Journal: ''Mercator
has had a long-standing official relationship with the Republic of
Kazakstan and its emerging oil industry. ... When all of the facts
associated with this matter are clearly understood, we are
confident that Mercator will be shown to have acted lawfully.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
