<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Latinos Lament Dearth of TV Roles  </HEADLINE>
By PAUL SHEPARD
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN DIEGO (AP) -- Latino advocates say they are happy that black
men seem to be getting juicier roles in the upcoming fall network
television season, but they want to know how they, American Indians
and Asian-Americans can get in on the action.
</P>
<P>
   ''We don't want the slice of pie African-American men are
getting in Hollywood. We want the entire pie to be much, much
bigger,'' said Alex Nogales of the National Hispanic Media
Coalition that met Monday at the annual convention of the National
Council of La Raza.
</P>
<P>
   The Hispanic coalition was formed last year after minority
advocates criticized the networks for a lack of racial and ethnic
diversity in the fall TV schedule. No minority group members had
featured roles in any new programming slated that season for ABC,
CBS, NBC or FOX.
</P>
<P>
   The group joined forces with the NAACP, the Asian Pacific
American Media Coalition and the American Indians in Film and
Television and negotiated agreements with the major networks to
increase minority participation both on and off screen.
</P>
<P>
   But now it's hard for the Hispanics to tell if they have gained
ground.
</P>
<P>
   While black actors Andre Braugher, David Alan Grier and Mykelti
Williamson have won lead roles in the upcoming season -- giving rise
to hopes that the situation is improving -- no Latinos,
Asian-Americans or American Indians have gotten significant roles
on new shows.
</P>
<P>
   Braugher is slated to star on ABC's ''Gideon's Crossing,'' Grier
on NBC's ''Dag'' and Williamson on CBS' ''The Fugitive.''
</P>
<P>
   CBS has also renewed the hospital drama ''City of Angels,''
which has several black cast members as does a new CBS offering,
''The Street.''
</P>
<P>
   The Latino advocates are especially perturbed by CBS for not
scheduling ''American Family,'' a drama about a middle-class
Hispanic family.
</P>
<P>
   Last month, CBS President Leslie Moonves said ''American
Family'' didn't fit in CBS' schedule. He said he took the unusual
step of letting the show's producers pitch the CBS-developed series
to other networks. No one bought it.
</P>
<P>
   Pressure from the Hispanic coalition led CBS to shop ''American
Family'' to other outlets, said coalition president Esteban Torres,
a former congressman from California.
</P>
<P>
   A ray of light for Latinos comes from cable channel Showtime's
decision to air a Latino-oriented show, ''Resurrection Boulevard.''
</P>
<P>
   One of its actors, Maurico Mendoza, said creation of that show
alone has given work to more than 60 Latino actors and benefited
other minorities.
</P>
<P>
   ''We make sure everyone -- American Indians and Asians and blacks
-- are included in all aspects of the show,'' Mendoza said. ''We
don't want anyone left out.''
</P>
<P>
   Telephone calls to NBC, CBS, ABC, and FOX seeking reaction were
not immediately returned.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-07-03-00 1643 </TRAILER>
