<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Big Movers in the Stock Market  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Stocks that were moving substantially or trading
heavily Monday on the New York Stock Exchange and the Nasdaq Stock
Market.
</P>
<P>
NYSE
</P>
<P>
Telefonos de Mexico SA, up $5.688 to $62.875
</P>
<P>
   Shares of the Mexican telecommunications provider rose after
opposition candidate Vicente Fox won Mexico's presidential
election, ending the Institutional Revolutionary Party's 71-year
grip on the presidency.
</P>
<P>
Sprint Corp., up $1.938 to $54.438
</P>
<P>
   Several newspapers, including the Financial Times, have reported
that Deutsche Telekom and Sprint are in preliminary talks about a
merger. The talks have developed in the wake of U.S. and European
Union objections to Sprint's planned union with WorldCom Inc.
</P>
<P>
IBM Corp., up 25 cents to $109.50
</P>
<P>
   Over the weekend, Barron's magazine reported that the company
would have had ''anemic'' profit growth in the past four years had
it not conducted stock buyback programs. Buybacks can improve
earnings per share by reducing the number of shares outstanding.
</P>
<P>
NASDAQ
</P>
<P>
Oracle Corp., down $3.875 at $80.188
</P>
<P>
   Ray Lane, who is credited with bringing the company back from a
business crisis in the early 1990s, will leave his post as chief
operating offer and president, the company said late Friday. Rumors
of Lane's departure have been circulating through Silicon Valley
for months.
</P>
<P>
David's Bridal Inc., up $8.188 at $19.75
</P>
<P>
   May Department Stores Co. will acquire the bridal retail company
for $436 million, or $20 a share. The companies said David's
Bridal, which generates higher sales in the spring, will complement
May's business, which has higher sales in the fall.
</P>
<P>
Informix Corp., down $2.75 at $4.688
</P>
<P>
   Shares hit a 52-week low after the software maker estimated its
second-quarter earnings will miss analysts' expectations due to a
revenue shortfall. In addition, Informix said its acquisition of
Ardent Software will not add to earnings for 2000, as previously
expected.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
