<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-03 17:21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Clinton Congratulates Vicente Fox  </HEADLINE>
By GEORGE GEDDA
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- In a congratulatory telephone call, President
Clinton told Mexican President-elect Vicente Fox the United States
stands ready to enhance the close bilateral cooperation that he
said already exists between the two countries.
</P>
<P>
   ''Mexico is our neighbor and friend,'' Clinton said in a
statement. ''Mexico's national elections, the freest and fairest in
the nation's history, stand as vivid testimony to the depth of the
democratic commitment of the Mexican people.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton said he also spoke Monday with President Ernesto Zedillo
to praise his ''extraordinary contributions'' to Mexico,
particularly what he has done to deepen democracy.
</P>
<P>
   He said Mexicans should be proud of advances they have made in
the last six years to ''strengthen and consolidate democratic
institutions and set Mexico on a course of economic growth and
prosperity.''
</P>
<P>
   Sunday's election process appeared to have been free and fair, a
welcome development for the Clinton administration, given the
priority it attaches to democratic stability in the hemisphere.
</P>
<P>
   Officials have anguished over flawed elections in Peru and Haiti
in recent weeks, and there also has been disquiet in Washington
about possible weakening of democracy in Venezuela.
</P>
<P>
   One of the few problems voiced about Sunday's historic Mexican
election related to Fox's ability to induce cooperation from a
bureaucracy accustomed to taking orders from a political party in
power for 71 years.
</P>
<P>
   The administration has adopted a wait-and-see attitude toward
some of his promises, including a package of economic changes that
he says will double foreign investment in Mexico and ensure that
jobless Mexicans do not have to flee to the United States to make a
living.
</P>
<P>
   Fox has criticized the Zedillo administration's counternarcotics
record, saying large budgetary outlays have yielded scant results.
</P>
<P>
   Barry McCaffrey, director of the White House drug control
office, said Fox came across as ''enormously determined'' on the
drug issue when McCaffrey and other officials met with him a few
months ago.
</P>
<P>
   ''The guy is extremely smart, dedicated and bold,'' McCaffrey
said in a telephone interview. ''He's determined not to turn Mexico
over to the narcotraffickers.''
</P>
<P>
   One Fox proposal that could cause friction recommends opening
U.S.-Mexican frontier so that Mexicans and Americans can go back
and forth without restriction.
</P>
<P>
   Asked about the idea Monday, a senior U.S. official said he had
seen no formal proposal about it.
</P>
<P>
   The proposal was criticized by David Ray, a spokesman for the
Federation for American Immigration Reform.
</P>
<P>
   ''The immigration issue cannot continue to be ignored by
American politicians when Mexico's newly elected president is
clamoring for even more visas or for the opening of an immigration
safety valve to the U.S.,'' Ray said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-07-03-00 1721 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000703.0104 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-03 17:27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> BC-NY--OpSail-Order of Sail, 1st Ld-Writethru,1700  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   NEW YORK (AP) - Following is the expected order of parade as the
tall ships sail under the Verrazano-Narrows Bridge into New York
harbor starting at about 9:45 a.m. Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   The biggest 26 vessels, led by the Eagle, are to sail in single
column at a distance of 600 yards apart, each with a smaller ship
as a starboard escort. About 100 remaining tall ships will wind up
the marine parade.
</P>
<P>
   1. The Eagle, a U.S. Coast Guard barque.
</P>
<P>
   With the golden eagle as its figurehead, this is America's most
famous tall ship and Operation Sail's host vessel. Built in 1936 in
Germany, the 295-foot schooner was seized from the Nazis in World
War II and made a Coast Guard cadet training in 1946.
</P>
<P>
   Accompanied by: the Zenobe Gramme of Belgium, a 92-foot naval
training ship. Built in 1961, it's named for the Belgian inventor
who perfected the technology of alternating current for motors and
generators.
</P>
<P>
   2. The Danmark, Denmark.
</P>
<P>
   The three-masted, 252-foot tall ship visited the New York
World's Fair in 1939 and was in the United States when Germany
invaded Denmark. Its captain offered his country's services to
President Roosevelt, and the Coast Guard used the ship for
training.
</P>
<P>
   Accompanied by: the Asgard II, of Ireland, a 106-foot brigantine
whose name comes from Norse mythology and means Home of the Gods.
</P>
<P>
   3. The Pogoria, Poland.
</P>
<P>
   A 154-foot barkantine that carries a broad blue stripe the
length of its sides, the Pogoria has foresails adorned with the
symbol of Poland's Iron Shackle Fraternity. Built in 1980, it has
sailed the world with a crew of 50.
</P>
<P>
   Accompanied by: the Amistad, of the United States, a 129-foot
replica of the ''freedom schooner'' that was the scene of an 1839
insurrection by African men who were kidnapped in Sierra Leone to
be sold into slavery.
</P>
<P>
   4. The Niagara, the United States.
</P>
<P>
   Built in Pennsylvania in the War of 1812 to oppose the British
in the Great Lakes, it was restored over many years. The 198-foot
ship was relaunched at Erie in 1988.
</P>
<P>
   Accompanied by: the Californian, of the United States, the
145-foot official tall ship of the state of California that is a
recreation of the 19th century cutter C.W. Lawrence.
</P>
<P>
   5. The Guayas, Ecuador.
</P>
<P>
   Built in Spain, the 258-foot bark sailed all the way around
South America on its maiden voyage in 1978.
</P>
<P>
   Accompanied by: the Soren Larsen, of New Zealand, a 140-foot,
19th century-style brigantine used in a number of films, including
''The French Lieutenant's Woman.''
</P>
<P>
   6. The Rose, the United States.
</P>
<P>
   A replica of a British frigate Rose that was part of the fleet
that attacked New York in 1776. The new, 179-foot Rose, built in
1970, is the world's largest active wooden tall ship and serves as
a training ship.
</P>
<P>
   Accompanied by: the Jens Krogh, of Denmark, a 61-foot ketch
built in 1899 and now owned by a maritime scouts organization.
</P>
<P>
   7. The Sagres, Portugal.
</P>
<P>
   With large red crosses on the sails, the 292-foot bark is a
training ship that has taken part in every Operation Sail. Built in
1937 for the Germany navy, it was taken by the United States and
passed on to Brazil before Portugal acquired it in 1961.
</P>
<P>
   Accompanied by: the Fair Jeanne, of Canada, a 120-foot
brigantine that serves as a floating classroom and sail training
vessel.
</P>
<P>
   8. The Oosterschelde, Holland.
</P>
<P>
   An early 20th century schooner that transported cargo around the
Mediterranean and Africa, the 164-foot tall ship became a motor
vessel in 1930 and remained so until 1980.
</P>
<P>
   Accompanied by: the Pride of Baltimore II, of the United States,
a 157-foot replica of a 1812-era schooner that serves as an
educational goodwill ambassador for Baltimore.
</P>
<P>
   9. The Kalmar Nyckel, the United States.
</P>
<P>
   This 3-year-old pinnace is a replica of the vessel that brought
the first Swedish settlers to the Delaware Bay in 1638. The
original later served in Sweden's navy and was lost at sea.
</P>
<P>
   Accompanied by: the Providence, of the United States, a 110-foot
replica of an 18th century yellow-and-black sloop that once fought
British warships.
</P>
<P>
   10. The Europa, Holland.
</P>
<P>
   Built in Germany in 1911, this 184-foot bark is now a sail
training vessel that was restored in Amsterdam.
</P>
<P>
   Accompanied by: the A. J. Meerwald, of the United States, the
official tall ship of New Jersey. A bald-headed (without topmasts)
schooner, it was launched in 1928 as a Delaware Bay oyster dredge.
</P>
<P>
   11. The Gazela, United States.
</P>
<P>
   Built in Portugal in 1883 from trees said to have been planted
in the 15th century, this 177-foot barkentine was a fishing vessel
that harvested cod off the Newfoundland coast. It is now owned by
the Port of History Museum in Philadelphia.
</P>
<P>
   Accompanied by: the Kathryn B, a 105-foot luxury charter
schooner that sails the Atlantic and Caribbean.
</P>
<P>
   12. The Kaiwo Maru, Japan.
</P>
<P>
   With a name meaning King of the Sea, the 361-foot bark was
constructed in 1989 to replace an earlier vessel by the same name
that trained Japan's merchant marine cadets for more than 50 years.
</P>
<P>
   Accompanied by: the Spirit of Massachusetts, of the United
States, a 125-foot replica of the 19th century Gloucester fishing
schooner Fredonia.
</P>
<P>
   13. The Cisne Branco, Brazil.
</P>
<P>
   The hull color matches its name, meaning White Swan. The
249-foot Dutch-made ship was delivered to the Brazilian navy last
year.
</P>
<P>
   Accompanied by: Ernestina, of the United States, the 156-foot
official vessel of Massachusetts, a 19th century fishing schooner
that later operated as a trade ship from Cape Verde.
</P>
<P>
   14. The Capitan Miranda, Uruguay.
</P>
<P>
   A research vessel for the Uruguayan navy in the 1960s, the
198-foot schooner was built in 1930 as a cargo ship. In 1978, it
was refitted with a rig developed for racing yachts.
</P>
<P>
   Accompanied by: the Half Moon, of the United States, 100-foot
copy of the ship Henry Hudson sailed while exploring the Hudson
River in the early 1600s.
</P>
<P>
   15. The Esmeralda, Chile.
</P>
<P>
   A training vessel for the Chilean navy, this barkantine was
built in Spain in 1952. The figurehead is an Andean condor.
</P>
<P>
   Accompanied by: the Corwith Cramer, of the United States, a
135-foot sailing school vessel operating out of Woods Hole, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   16. The Simon Bolivar, Venezuela.
</P>
<P>
   Launched in 1980, the 270-foot bark is named for the hero of the
revolutions that won six Latin American countries independence from
Spain. The figurehead symbolizes liberty - a woman holding a sword.
A navy training vessel, its false gun ports are painted black on a
white hull.
</P>
<P>
   Accompanied by: the Harvey Gamage, of the United States, a
131-foot sail training schooner that specializes in curricula for
youth-at-risk.
</P>
<P>
   17. The Dar Mlodziezy, Poland.
</P>
<P>
   Meaning Gift of Youth, the 357-foot ship built in 1982 is
Poland's main sail training vessel.
</P>
<P>
   Accompanied by: the Bat'kivschyna, of Ukraine, an 80-foot
schooner whose name means Motherland.
</P>
<P>
   18. The Libertad, Argentina.
</P>
<P>
   This 340-foot Argentine navy tall ship is one of the world's
largest and fastest sailing-school vessels. It was built in 1962.
</P>
<P>
   Accompanied by: the Clearwater, of the United States, a 106-foot
replica of a Hudson River merchant sloop. Now serves as an
environmental education vessel.
</P>
<P>
   19. The Dewaruchi, Indonesia.
</P>
<P>
   Named for a Hindu sea god, the 191-foot Indonesian navy training
ship represents a nation that still maintains a fleet of sailing
cargo schooners.
</P>
<P>
   Accompanied by: the Lycia, of Italy, a 60-foot privately owned
wooden sloop that navigates the Mediterranean.
</P>
<P>
   20. The Amerigo Vespucci, Italy.
</P>
<P>
   One of the parade's most elegant tall ships, the 331-foot vessel
is patterned after an 18th century frigate and serves as a naval
training ship. Built in 1931, it has quarters for more than 500
people and is among the largest vessels in Operation Sail.
</P>
<P>
   Accompanied by: the Bel Espoir, of France, a 113-foot schooner
crafted in 1944 and used by a French Catholic group to retrain
troubled youths; its name means ''Beautiful Hope.''
</P>
<P>
   21. The Gorch Fock, Germany.
</P>
<P>
   The 293-foot steel bark, named for a German poet killed as a
seaman in World War I, is a school ship for the German navy. It was
built in 1958.
</P>
<P>
   Accompanied by: the Mist of Avalon, of Canada, a 100-foot cod
fishing boat from the 1960s, reborn in the 1990s as a fully rigged
vessel.
</P>
<P>
   22. The Juan Sebastian de Elcano, Spain.
</P>
<P>
   The 370-foot schooner is named for the commander of the only
galleon that returned from Ferdinand Magellan's 1522 attempted
voyage around the world. Magellan was killed by Philippine natives,
but his flagship completed the trip.
</P>
<P>
   Accompanied by: the Lettie G. Howard, of the United States, a
129-foot marine education vessel that is part of Manhattan's South
Street Seaport Museum. The 105-year-old schooner once fished out of
Gloucester, Mass., and is a National Historic Landmark.
</P>
<P>
   23. The Gloria, Colombia.
</P>
<P>
   A winged figurehead represents the 249-foot bark that is the
training ship of the Colombian navy, built in Spain in 1968.
</P>
<P>
   Accompanied by: the Whitehawk, of the United States, a 105-foot
racing yacht.
</P>
<P>
   24. The Eendracht, Holland.
</P>
<P>
   A fast, 194-foot ship with a crew of 56, it was built in 1989
and is operated by the Sailing School Foundation in the Hague.
</P>
<P>
   Accompanied by: the Rona II, of Great Britain, a 68-foot ketch.
</P>
<P>
   25. The Bluenose II, Canada.
</P>
<P>
   A 161-foot schooner built in 1963, it was modeled after a Nova
Scotia fishing schooner and racer in the 1920s and 1930s. It serves
as a goodwill ambassador for the Canadian province.
</P>
<P>
   Accompanied by: the Mystic Whaler, of the United States, a
110-foot New England-style schooner from Mystic, Conn., that
operates as a sailing school.
</P>
<P>
   26. The Picton Castle, New Zealand.
</P>
<P>
   This 176-foot barque represents a deep-sea sailing era when
ships battled fierce storms around Cape Horn. Built in England in
1928, the Picton Castle traded from the Arctic Circle to southern
Europe.
</P>
<P>
   Accompanied by: the Eye of Wind, of Great Britain, a 132-foot
topsail schooner built in 1911 for the South American hide trade.
</P>
</TEXT>
