<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-03 17:27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> State suspends license of Buffalo-area doctor  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   BUFFALO, N.Y. (AP) - An obstetrician-gynecologist has been
temporarily barred from practicing medicine for allegedly
mistreating nine patients, including two who died, state health
officials said Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Monica Applewhite, who maintains offices in Williamsville and
Lockport, faces 23 charges of misconduct, including gross
negligence, gross incompetence, moral unfitness to practice
medicine, and fraud.
</P>
<P>
   The charges relate to eight pregnant patients and one who sought
a tubal ligation, a procedure that prevents pregnancy, Department
of Health documents show.
</P>
<P>
   Applewhite is accused of improperly performing the tubal
ligation, elective surgery, when the patient had an infection. She
died June 3.
</P>
<P>
   A second patient died Feb. 5 of pregnancy-related complications.
In that case, Applewhite is accused of failing to order adequate
tests and to follow up on the patient's worsening condition before
and after delivery, state officials said. The doctor then allegedly
altered her notes.
</P>
<P>
   Applewhite, who was licensed to practice medicine in New York in
October 1986, could not be reached for comment Monday. Her
answering service said the office was closed until Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   A hearing was scheduled for July 10.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
