<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Ethiopia, Eritrea Talking in U.S.  </HEADLINE>
By GEORGE GEDDA
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Delegations from Ethiopia and Eritrea opened
indirect talks Monday at the State Department on issues remaining
after they agreed to stop fighting last month, department spokesman
said.
</P>
<P>
   As the talks began, with U.S. officials shuttling back and forth
between the two delegations in separate rooms, U.N.
Secretary-General Kofi Annan dispatched a team to Ethiopia and
Eritrea to lay groundwork for a possible U.N. peacekeeping mission
along the bitterly disputed border.
</P>
<P>
   The two sides were discussing in Washington demarcation of the
disputed 620-mile border, compensation for deportees and the
origins of their two-year war. Eritrea was part of Ethiopia until
it gained independence in 1993, with a poorly defined border.
</P>
<P>
   The two-year war between the Horn of Africa neighbors claimed
tens of thousands of lives. The cessation of hostilities was agreed
June 18 in Algiers through mediation by the Organization of African
Unity.
</P>
<P>
   At the United Nations, Annan said in a report to the Security
Council that he was sending a mission Monday to speed up
implementation of the cease-fire agreement.
</P>
<P>
   The team is headed by Maj. Gen. Timothy Ford of Australia, a
former chief of staff in U.N. peacekeeping operations in the Middle
East. It includes military and humanitarian experts.
</P>
<P>
   Annan also is sending liaison officers to Addis Ababa and
Asmara, the capitals of Ethiopia and Eritrea, to help plan the
peacekeeping operation. Pending approval by the Security Council
and both countries, the officers would be followed by military
observer groups in each capital.
</P>
<P>
   The council was expected to discuss the Horn of Africa situation
this week.
</P>
<P>
   The June 18 cease-fire would deploy international peacekeepers
during negotiations to delineate the border.
</P>
<P>
   Some diplomats have suggested a force of about 2,000 troops, but
others have said nearly double that many may be needed.
</P>
<P>
   Ethiopia insists it will not withdraw troops from Eritrean
territory until U.N. peacekeepers are deployed in a buffer zone
along the border.
</P>
<P>
   Annan urged governments for generous responses to the U.N.
humanitarian appeal for the Horn of Africa, which has been hit by a
severe drought.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   EDITOR'S NOTE -- Associated Press writer Harmonie Toros
contributed to this report.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
