<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-03 17:59 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Teacher overruled, students who failed graduate at ceremony  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   QUEENSBURY, N.Y. (AP) - Two high school seniors who flunked a
course despite repeated opportunities to make up the work have
graduated with their class after their parents pressured
administrators.
</P>
<P>
   Officials in other school districts said they've regularly faced
similar cases in which parents have demanded that students with
spotty academic records be allowed to graduate, according to the
Glens Falls Post-Star.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's just not right,'' said the teacher, Sonja Martinson, who
has taught for 28 years at the Queensbury Central School District
46 miles north of Albany. She said she's outraged that in this day
of raising academic standards statewide that she feels
administrators lowered standards after bowing to repeated parental
complaints in the last week of school.
</P>
<P>
   Martinson said the students didn't get good enough grades in her
elective class in mythology despite opportunities to do extra work
to make up for poor test scores.
</P>
<P>
   At first, she told the Glens Falls Post-Star, administrators
told her the students would be allowed to take part in graduation
ceremonies but would simply be given a fake diploma and would have
to make up the class. Later, she said she learned the students had
received their diplomas.
</P>
<P>
   Acting Superintendent Linda Noon denied that parents' complaints
triggered the decision to allow the two students to graduate. But
she acknowledged that the parents' protests prompted a review of
the students' grades. She said the review showed the students met
the requirements for passing.
</P>
<P>
   ''You can't bend under pressure, but you need to look at every
case individually,'' Noon said. ''We try to be extremely fair to
all our students.''
</P>
<P>
   The Queensbury students' names weren't released.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
