<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Clinton Speaks With Barak, Arafat  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- President Clinton talked on the phone Monday
to Palestinian leader Yasser Arafat and Israeli Prime Minister Ehud
Barak, but no decision has been reached for a Camp David-style
Mideast summit.
</P>
<P>
   After a recent round of shuttle diplomacy by Secretary of State
Madeleine Albright, Palestinians and Israelis were reported as
remaining far apart on crucial issues, including whether Israel
would withdraw from all territory it took in the 1967 Six-Day War.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton spoke on the phone for about 15 minutes with Barak and
30 minutes with Arafat from Camp David, the presidential retreat in
Maryland's Catoctin Mountains where Egypt and Israel held a summit
with President Carter in 1978. Clinton is trying to assess whether
the parties are close enough to bring the leaders together, or
whether further lower-level negotiations are needed, White House
spokesman P.J. Crowley said.
</P>
<P>
   ''He (Clinton) recognizes that at some point we'll need to get
the leaders together to work through the most difficult issues that
they still face, but the president has made no decision on what the
next step is -- whether it is to resume negotiations, or go to a
leadership meeting,'' Crowley said.
</P>
<P>
   ''I think we recognize there's a danger to bringing the leaders
together prematurely if we don't think they're close enough to
where that kind of meeting could bridge those differences.''
</P>
<P>
   The Palestinians and Israelis are far behind their schedule for
a final status agreement by Sept. 13. Arafat has said he will
declare a Palestinian state on that date if the negotiations have
not been conclusive, which would be almost sure to increase tension
in the area.
</P>
<P>
   Asked about Arafat's pending declaration, Crowley said: ''Our
position has not changed. Unilateral steps outside of final status
negotiations are not helpful.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
