<HEADLINE> Mexico's New President Details Plans  </HEADLINE>
By NIKO PRICE
<TEXT>
<P>
   MEXICO CITY (AP) -- Vicente Fox woke up Monday and realized the
magnitude of what he had just done -- come from political obscurity
a decade ago to bring down the world's longest-ruling party.
</P>
<P>
   ''I felt responsibility,'' Mexico's next president said in an
interview with The Associated Press. ''People have told me, 'You're
our last hope,' 'Don't fail us, Vicente.' So I can't fail.''
</P>
<P>
   Fox, a businessman from northern Mexico known as much for his
cowboy boots as for his political philosophy, stunned the world
with his decisive victory in Sunday's elections over the party that
has ruled Mexico uninterrupted since the Depression began.
</P>
<P>
   In an interview in English and Spanish at a Mexico City hotel
Monday afternoon, Fox described his vision of the transformations
ahead for Mexico.
</P>
<P>
   He said he would spend the next two months recruiting and hiring
Cabinet secretaries and aides to form ''a very transparent,
accountable government. We will have moral authority and democratic
legitimacy,'' he added.
</P>
<P>
   He said he would have teams search for qualified candidates from
any party -- or from outside all parties -- and then interview the
top three candidates for each post himself.
</P>
<P>
   ''I'm not showing up to govern with friends or relatives or
buddies,'' he said. ''I'm showing up to govern with the most
professional team there is in this country.''
</P>
<P>
   Fox said his first priorities would be to tackle the commitments
he made during his campaign: creating jobs, improving education and
eliminating corruption and crime.
</P>
<P>
   He said he would reform electoral laws to let Mexican migrants
vote in the United States, and that he would work with the United
States to open the borders to workers over the next decade.
</P>
<P>
   In the long term, he said, he would pressure to expand the North
American Free Trade Agreement into a common market -- similar to the
European Union -- of the United States, Canada and Mexico.
</P>
<P>
   He said that would eliminate the migration problem and bring
Mexican salaries up to where they are in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   ''The United States has always tried to resolve migration, drug
trafficking or trading problems on a day-to-day basis, and we will
never solve it in that way,'' he said. ''We need to think
long-term, 20-30 years from now, where we want to be.
</P>
<P>
   ''Mexico wants to be an equal partner with the United States and
Canada ... and if we have wisdom and we have a long-term view, we
should be able to meet that long-term objective.''
</P>
<P>
   Fox said President Clinton had called to congratulate him, and
that the two planned to meet before he takes office on Dec. 1, even
though Clinton will be gone shortly after Fox's term begins.
</P>
<P>
   ''He said congratulations to me and to all Mexicans for this
historic day,'' Fox said. ''He committed himself to be always near
and always accessible for any Mexican problems that might present
themselves.''
</P>
<P>
   Fox also sought to reassure investors in Mexico to prevent the
kind of economic crisis that has plagued Mexico in each of the last
four presidential handovers -- even though those were among members
of the same parties.
</P>
<P>
   ''That won't happen this time,'' Fox said, then turned to
address an imaginary group of investors: ''You are the ones who
know business. You are the ones who create jobs. My obligation is
to serve you, to support you, to create confidence inside you.''
</P>
<P>
   Fox said he's considering doing away with jackets and ties once
he begins his term. And the cowboy boots? They aren't coming off.
</P>
<P>
   ''Not even in the grave,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-07-03-00 1813 </TRAILER>
