<HEADLINE> Three killed in crash on Route 42  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   WASHINGTON TOWNSHIP , N.J. (AP) - Three people were killed and
three members of a Pennsylvania family were injured in a
three-vehicle crash on Route 42 that closed the southbound lanes of
the road for about two hours Monday.
</P>
<P>
   The identities of the those killed had not been released late
Monday afternoon because State Police were trying to notify their
families.
</P>
<P>
   The incident began at 11:44 a.m. when the driver of a 1989 Ford
Probe traveling westbound on the Atlantic City Expressway lost
control of the car, State Police said.
</P>
<P>
   The car crossed the median and went into the southbound lanes of
Route 42 where it struck a 1999 Dodge Durango head-on, according to
the State Police. The Durango was driven by Thomas Jacob, 49, of
Devon, Pa. and his wife, Marie Jacob, 48, was a passenger, police
said.
</P>
<P>
   The Durango spun around and rolled over after crashing into a
1995 Jeep Cherokee being driven by Michael Foy, 26, of West
Chester, Pa., State Police said. A passenger in the Cherokee was
Deidre Jacob, 19, of Devon, Pa., the daughter of the couple in the
Durango, according to police. Foy and Deidre Jacob were following
the Durango, police said.
</P>
<P>
   The driver of the Probe was airlifted to Cooper
Hospital-University Medical Center in Camden where he was
pronounced dead, police said. The two passengers in the Probe were
pronounced dead at the scene of the crash.
</P>
<P>
   Marie Jacob was in critical condition at Cooper, a hospital
spokeswoman said Monday. Thomas and Deidre were treated and
released, the spokeswoman said. Police had no report of injuries to
Foy.
</P>
<P>
   Route 42 was reopened about 1:30 p.m., but the investigation
caused traffic delays until 4 p.m. The crash is still under
investigation.
</P>
</TEXT>
