<HEADLINE> Erie Canal reopens after work on damaged Lock 12 near Fort Hunter  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   FORT HUNTER, N.Y. (AP) - The Erie Canal is reopened after work
was done on a lock 32 miles northwest of Albany that was damaged
since June 7.
</P>
<P>
   With the work done on Lock 12, the entire system is open for the
boating season that ends Nov. 1, said state Canal Corp. Executive
Director John Platt.
</P>
<P>
   The lock on the canal popular with pleasure boats was shut down
after part of the dam and bridge was severely damaged by
floodwaters on June 6. The lock reopened Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   A temporary dam was built as part of a $1.6 million contract
awarded to Chemung Contracting Corp. The dam and bridge also
supports county Route 27 which closed June 7. Further tests are
needed to determine when the highway might reopen.
</P>
<P>
   The bridge connects Tribes Hill with Fort Hunter in rural
Montgomery County. Without the bridge, the detour to get between
the tiny villages within sight of each other is 12 miles.
</P>
</TEXT>
