<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-03 18:37 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> New toll plaza will have glass walkways, real flowers  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   CARNEY'S POINT, N.J. (AP) - Twenty-three lanes of limestone,
glass walkways and real flowers.
</P>
<P>
   New Jersey Turnpike officials say the planned $44 million new
toll plaza will end legendary traffic tie-ups at Interchange 1 and
make New Jerseyans proud.
</P>
<P>
   ''It doesn't look like a typical interchange,'' said New Jersey
Turnpike Authority Executive Director Edward Gross. ''Just about
everyone I've shown the design to says it's very attractive. That
was the intent.''
</P>
<P>
   Construction begins next year on the new plaza, a few miles from
the Delaware Memorial Bridge and 1.2 miles north of the existing,
50-year-old plaza. Its opening is scheduled for June 2003.
</P>
<P>
   The plaza, which will include administrative offices, will have
23 lanes, eight more than the old one, to alleviate holiday and
summer weekend traffic.
</P>
<P>
   Backups of six to 20 miles are not unusual on holiday weekends,
when some 80,000 motorists pass through the plaza. The turnpike
authority has occasionally let drivers cruise through the plaza for
free rather than have backups all the way to Delaware.
</P>
<P>
   The plaza, with a limestone and whitewashed facade, will include
glass walkways for toll collectors and outside faucets so that
motorists can pass by real flowers instead of fake ones that sit at
other toll plazas.
</P>
<P>
   Motorists said the plaza will give a good impression of New
Jersey to drivers entering the state for the first time.
</P>
<P>
   ''It looks pretty,'' said Peter Light, 43, of Staten Island.
</P>
<P>
   But Ed and Deena Moss of Cheltenham, Pa., wondered about the $44
million cost.
</P>
<P>
   ''You have to go through, give them your money and drive away,''
Deena Moss said. ''That seems like more than you need for that
scenario.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
