<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-03 18:44 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Jurors questioned witnesses in pilot program  </HEADLINE>
By J.J. THOMPSON
<TEXT>
<P>
   TRENTON, N.J. (AP) - Camden County Superior Court Judge John T.
McNeill III noticed a welcome change in the jury box during the
last six months.
</P>
<P>
   Jurors generally seemed interested and more enthusiastic while
performing their civic duty - something he attributes to a pilot
program that allows them to question witnesses during civil trials.
</P>
<P>
   ''They really felt more involved,'' he said. ''I think it cuts
down on the number of people there (who try) to get out of
serving.''
</P>
<P>
   During the experiment, which began Jan. 1 and ended Friday,
jurors in selected courtrooms throughout the state were allowed to
take notes and submit written questions to witnesses during civil
trials.
</P>
<P>
   Judges and attorneys then looked over the questions - outside of
the presence of witnesses and jurors - to ensure there were no
objections. If there weren't any problems, the questions were posed
to witnesses.
</P>
<P>
   Attorneys then had the chance to present follow-up questions.
</P>
<P>
   McNeill said he informally spoke to jurors about the opportunity
while they filled out questionnaires after trials.
</P>
<P>
   ''I got a lot of positive comments,'' he said. ''I wouldn't be
surprised at all to see it became part of our court rules.''
</P>
<P>
   The pilot program went smoothly, said Gloucester County Superior
Court Judge Donald A. Smith, and he didn't mind allowing jurors to
question witnesses.
</P>
<P>
   ''I think it keeps the jurors interested because they know they
will have an opportunity to fill in the blanks,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   A New Jersey Supreme Court advisory committee suggested the
experiment after the court ruled in 1993 that jurors couldn't ask
questions until guidelines were established.
</P>
<P>
   While the program was popular with some judges, several
attorneys weren't as enthusiastic.
</P>
<P>
   McNeill said lawyers worried jurors would ask questions about
issues they hoped to avoid, which he discounts as a weak argument.
</P>
<P>
   ''If you look at it from the perspective that a trial is
supposed to be the search for truth, I'd say a complaint like that
doesn't hold much water,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Overall, he said attorneys objected to 10 to 15 percent of the
questions posed by jurors. And the questions did extend the length
of some trials.
</P>
<P>
   Gregory P. Joseph, former chairman of the American Bar
Association's section on litigation, helped the bar association
adopt guidelines in 1998 for the practice. He said the procedure
can enhance juror comprehension when implemented properly.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's a very forward-looking experiment,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Many federal judges already allow it, said Joseph, now partner
of a Wall Street law firm. Arizona has adopted its own rules for
allowing jurors to question witnesses. Courts in Wisconsin,
Connecticut, Iowa and Montana have ruled that the practice is
acceptable under certain circumstances.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-07-03-00 1844 </TRAILER>
