<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Poll: Majority of state residents satisfied with new inspection system </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   NEWARK, N.J. (AP) - Most New Jerseyans are satisfied with the
state's new car inspection system despite criticism by state
officials, according to a new poll.
</P>
<P>
   More than 70 percent of respondents in a Star-Ledger/Eagleton
telephone poll said they were satisfied with the inspection
process. Seven out of 10 residents said they waited no longer than
30 minutes in line, while 46 percent said they waited 15 minutes to
get their cars inspected.
</P>
<P>
   More than eight out of 10 of those polled said that people
running the test were courteous and said they believed the test was
fair.
</P>
<P>
   The poll of 802 people was conducted by telephone June 8-13. The
results were published Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Only 206 people surveyed took their cars in for a test since
December and 118 of those people believed they had taken the
tougher emissions test.
</P>
<P>
   The enhanced auto emissions test has been plagued by breakdowns
and other problems, causing long waits at its debut in September.
An investigatory panel recently blamed state officials for ignoring
or squelching warnings that a contractor was unable to deliver the
test on time and as promised. The new test was designed to more
accurately measure tailpipe pollution to bring New Jersey in line
with federal clean air rules.
</P>
<P>
   The margin of error for the poll was plus or minus 3.5
percentage points for the entire sample, and plus or minus 7
percentage points for the 206 people who said they had their cars
tested since December.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-07-03-00 1850 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000703.0122 </DOCNO>
