<HEADLINE> Man dies, several injured in Passaic apartment fire  </HEADLINE>
By J.J. THOMPSON
<TEXT>
<P>
   PASSAIC, N.J. (AP) - Investigators are looking into the cause of
a fire that killed a man and forced members of his family and other
residents to flee early Monday morning.
</P>
<P>
   Firefighters were called to the 2&AMP;frac12; story building at 371
Highland Ave. just after 5 a.m., said fire Capt. Al Hastick.
</P>
<P>
   The second-floor apartment - where the fire began - was occupied
by a grandmother, a couple, their 1-year-old daughter and two other
children from the mother's previous marriage, Hastick said.
</P>
<P>
   The grandmother, Joyce Mosley, age unknown, and two girls, ages
12 and 10, made it safely outside, but the couple and their infant
were trapped, Hastick said.
</P>
<P>
   One-year-old Deajia Anderson was dropped out of the first-floor
window and caught by an unknown bystander, according to Hastick.
The mother, Monique Anderson, 40, jumped out the window and was
severely injured, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Husband Donald Anderson, age unknown, died on the second floor,
Hastick said.
</P>
<P>
   On the third floor, Kemp Mosley, age unknown, escaped without
injuries, Hastick said. Thirty-year-old Adrienne Stegall jumped
from the third-floor fire escape, injuring her right leg, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Residents on the first floor made it safely outside,
firefighters said.
</P>
<P>
   Hastick said a chained fire escape ladder and an air conditioner
blocking a third-floor window hampered efforts to evacuate the
building.
</P>
<P>
   Monique Anderson was taken to Saint Barnabas Medical Center burn
unit in Livingston and was in critical condition Monday afternoon,
according to hospital officials.
</P>
<P>
   Deajia Anderson and Stegall were transported to Saint Joseph's
Hospital &AMP; Medical Center in Paterson, where they were treated and
released, a spokeswoman said.
</P>
</TEXT>
