<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-03 19:18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Report: Mayor Giuliani's father served time at Sing Sing  </HEADLINE>
By BETH GARDINER
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) - Mayor Rudolph Giuliani's late father Harold
served a year-and-a-half in Sing Sing prison for holding up a
milkman at gunpoint in the 1930s, a decade before his law-and-order
son was born, The Village Voice reported Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Harold Giuliani pleaded guilty to third-degree armed robbery in
May 1934, a month after milkman Harold Hall was robbed in the
stairwell of an Upper East Side apartment building, the Voice
reported in an excerpt from reporter Wayne Barrett's upcoming book
about the mayor.
</P>
<P>
   Giuliani and an accomplice stopped Hall as he entered the
building to collect customer payments, pointed a gun at him and
took $128.82 from his pocket, the Voice said.
</P>
<P>
   The report comes in the midst of a difficult year for Rudolph
Giuliani, who recent dropped out of the U.S. Senate race after
revealing he had prostate cancer, was separating from his wife and
had formed a close friendship with another woman.
</P>
<P>
   The mayor, a former federal prosecutor, has built his career on
a reputation as a crime-fighter, gaining national prominence as New
York's crime rates dropped dramatically under his administration.
Until recently, he rarely spoke about his personal life.
</P>
<P>
   Sunny Mindel, a spokeswoman for the mayor, declined to comment
on the story about Harold Giuliani.
</P>
<P>
   ''We haven't read it,'' she said. ''Don't read The Village
Voice.''
</P>
<P>
   A call to the state Department of Correctional Services seeking
confirmation of the report was not immediately returned.
</P>
<P>
   After a police officer interrupted the aborted robbery, an
indictment identified Harold Giuliani, then 26, as the man who
pressed a gun into Hall's abdomen, the Voice reported. But the
milkman later changed his statement, saying Giuliani's accomplice
wielded the pistol, according to the paper.
</P>
<P>
   Prosecutors said in court that Hall had been told to change his
story, according to the Voice.
</P>
<P>
   ''This milkman tried to change his statement after he was
visited at about four o'clock that morning by several people who
threatened him,'' assistant district attorney Louis Capozzoli
reportedly said at a court hearing. ''Then he said he thought this
fellow (Giuliani) ought to get a break.''
</P>
<P>
   Harold Giuliani, who told a judge his name was Joseph Starrett,
was initially charged with four felonies, and pleaded innocent, the
Voice reported. After Hall changed his statement, Giuliani was
allowed to plead guilty to just one felony, according to the paper.
He was sentenced to two to five years and released on parole after
a year and a half.
</P>
<P>
   The Voice report says Harold Giuliani's criminal record is filed
under the name Joseph Starrett.
</P>
<P>
   The mayor recalled his father's influence on him while speaking
to reporters about his cancer diagnosis in April. Harold Giuliani
died of prostate cancer in 1981 at age 73.
</P>
<P>
   ''It brings up very painful memories,'' the mayor said of the
diagnosis. ''And, you know, I miss my father every day of my life.
And he's a very, very important reason for why I'm standing here as
the mayor of New York City.''
</P>
<P>
   The Village Voice story, headlined ''Thug Life,'' describes
Harold Giuliani as a hot-tempered man who was quick to throw a
punch and rarely held a legitimate job.
</P>
<P>
   In the late 1940s, it says, he began working as a bartender at a
tavern owned by his brother-in-law Leo D'Avanzo, the brother of
Rudolph Giuliani's mother Helen.
</P>
<P>
   The Voice says D'Avanzo ran a loan-sharking and gambling
operation out of the bar, Vincent's Restaurant. Harold Giuliani
wielded a baseball bat to collect debts owed to his brother-in-law,
according to the paper, which quoted an unidentified witness as
saying he saw Harold Giuliani smack a man in the face with a bat
after the man asked for an extra week to repay a loan.
</P>
<P>
   Another unidentified source told the Voice that the elder
Giuliani came to his house to collect a loan and threatened to
break bones. That dispute was resolved without violence, the paper
said.
</P>
<P>
   Giuliani moved his family from Brooklyn to Long Island in 1951,
and left his bartending job in the late 1950s to become a school
custodian. He was eventually fired for failing to show up to work,
the Voice said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
