<HEADLINE> Judge tells Ocean County man to prove he has cancer  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   TOMS RIVER, N.J. (AP) - An Ocean County man accused of trying to
have the man who allegedly sexually assaulted his daughter killed
has asked a judge to release him from jail so he can receive
medical treatment for prostate cancer.
</P>
<P>
   Superior Court Judge Edward J. Turnbach Friday told him to prove
it.
</P>
<P>
   Turnbach said he hasn't seen any medical records for William J.
Fisher, of Stafford, but directed jail officials to notify
prosecutors if his condition gets worse.
</P>
<P>
   Fisher, 40, was charged in February with conspiracy to commit
murder for hire after he met twice with an investigator from the
Ocean County Prosecutor's Office who posed as a hit man or someone
who could get one.
</P>
<P>
   Fisher's family told the Asbury Park Press of Neptune that
Kenneth Guenther, of Barnegat, was the target because he had
repeatedly abused Fisher's daughter.
</P>
<P>
   Guenther has been indicted on two charges of aggravated sexual
assault. He told the newspaper the charges are unfounded, and that
Fisher manipulated the girl to destroy Guenther's relationship with
Fisher's ex-wife.
</P>
<P>
   Fisher was released in March after posting $50,000 bail. He was
arrested last week on a new charge: He tried to fraudulently obtain
a controlled substance.
</P>
<P>
   Authorities said Fisher, using a cell phone, pretended he was a
physician so he could get a prescription drug from the ShopRite
pharmacy in Stafford.
</P>
<P>
   L. Gilbert Farr, Fisher's attorney, said his client is innocent
of the recent charge.
</P>
<P>
   Fisher remains in Ocean County Jail in lieu of $50,000 bail for
the conspiracy count and $10,000 for the drug charge.
</P>
<P>
   ''My client is in bad health,'' Farr said. ''He's under a
doctor's care at the jail. He is supposed to begin chemotherapy
next week.''
</P>
