<HEADLINE> Nephew charged with 1997 murder of Camden schoolteacher  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   CAMDEN, N.J. (AP) - The nephew of a Camden schoolteacher was
arraigned Monday on charges that he murdered his aunt by stabbing
her to death in her home in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   Marvin Q. Smith argued with his aunt, Paula Macklin, on Nov. 17,
1997, in her Camden home, prosecutors said. The fight escalated,
and Smith beat his aunt and stabbed her with a kitchen knife,
according to prosecutors.
</P>
<P>
   Smith then robbed Macklin's house and fled in her 1997 Jeep
Cherokee, said Greg Reinert, spokesman for the Camden County
Prosecutor's Office.
</P>
<P>
   Macklin's body was found later that evening by her son, Michael
Smith, 28, and his girlfriend. The blade was still in Macklin's
chest.
</P>
<P>
   ''This is hurting two mothers. It's hurting my mother and
hurting my nephew's parents,'' Macklin's sister, Melinda Rijos,
told The Courier-Post of Cherry Hill for Monday's edition. ''It
hurts all the way around.''
</P>
<P>
   Smith, 22, was arrested and charged Sunday for his aunt's murder
after being arrested by Glassboro police on an unrelated charge.
</P>
<P>
   He is being held in Camden County Jail in lieu of $300,000 cash
bail.
</P>
<P>
   Macklin, 44, was a kindergarten teacher at McGraw School in
Camden.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's hard. Everybody's really numb right now,'' said Rijos, of
Cherry Hill. ''It's somebody she really trusted.''
</P>
</TEXT>
