<HEADLINE> Royals Move Suppan To Bullpen  </HEADLINE>
By DOUG TUCKER
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. (AP) -- Jeff Suppan, who has given up 23 of the
major league-high 132 homers of Kansas City's pitching staff, was
demoted to the bullpen Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Taking his spot in the rotation will likely be Blake Stein, who
has been out since spring training with a fractured bone in his
right forearm.
</P>
<P>
   ''Each game, I'm not moving forward,'' said Suppan, who was
10-12 with a 4.53 ERA last year, tying Jose Rosado for most wins on
the Royals. ''It's best for me to get a few innings out of the
bullpen. I wish I would have figured it out already. But I haven't,
so this is a good time to figure it out. I've tried to do
everything except be aggressive.'''
</P>
<P>
   Manager Tony Muser said he hoped the bullpen assignment would
not be permanent for Suppan, 2-6 with a 5.57 ERA in 18 starts.
</P>
<P>
   ''I think he's a little confused right now, a little bit
frustrated. He's given up quite a few home runs and he's lost his
aggressiveness,'' Muser said.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's not a physical thing. It's a mental thing. He needs a
break. It's just like every-day position players need a couple of
days off sometimes when they get confused and things aren't going
well.''
</P>
<P>
   Stein, a right-hander who came to the Royals last year from
Oakland in the Kevin Appier trade, was being counted on as a major
part of the rotation. In his last rehab start for Triple-A Omaha,
he beat Nashville 6-1, allowed four hits in seven scoreless innings
with nine strikeouts and no walks.
</P>
<P>
   Stein was expected to arrive in Kansas City on Monday and might
take Suppan's start Friday at Houston.
</P>
<P>
   ''I'm happy to see Stein. But at the same time I don't want to
get overly excited because he's been in rehab a long time,'' Muser
said. ''He's missed half the season because of that broken bone. I
hope he helps us. But I'm not expecting Nolan Ryan.''
</P>
</TEXT>
