<HEADLINE> Missing steer shows up at barbecue  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   COHOES, N.Y. (AP) - A family enjoying a backyard barbecue
unexpectedly had a steer for dinner Sunday while had steer for
dinner.
</P>
<P>
   The young, cream-colored animal missing for a week from a nearby
farm then bolted into a heavily wooded ravine before police
arrived.
</P>
<P>
   Despite several sightings, Cohoes police searching for the beast
about 5 miles north of Albany find themselves still asking,
''Where's the Beef?''
</P>
<P>
   One homeowner who came face-to-face with the steer said the
animal, which looks like an undersized bull, stood at the back of
his lawn for a few minutes as they sized up each other before the
steer raced away.
</P>
<P>
   The neighborhood lines a deep valley to the south where at least
a few farms still stand amid many new homes.
</P>
<P>
   ''I don't know why he'd want to be out there alone,'' said
Clayton Waterbury, who owns the missing steer that bolted June 23
from his Cherry Hill Farm. ''They're just as scared of you as you
are of them,'' he told the Albany Times Union.
</P>
