<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-03 19:42 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Arafat: We'll Pledge Statehood  </HEADLINE>
By LAURA KING
<TEXT>
<P>
   GAZA CITY, Gaza Strip (AP) -- Yasser Arafat's government told
Palestinians Monday to prepare for statehood by Sept. 13, even as
Israel insisted anew that independence must come only as part of a
peace accord.
</P>
<P>
   The Palestinians' chief policymaking body, the PLO's Central
Council, was wrapping up two days of closed-door talks in the Gaza
Strip about the timing of a statehood declaration.
</P>
<P>
   The chief policymaking body told Palestinians to get ready for
statehood by Sept. 13.
</P>
<P>
   The PLO Central Council declared its ''determination'' to
declare independence by that time, and called on the world
community to recognize statehood when it is declared, ''noting the
natural and historical right of our nation to establish a state.''
</P>
<P>
   The published statement, issued by the official Wafa news agency
30 minutes after the meeting concluded, went beyond a statement
read out by PCC chairman Salim Zanoun immediately after the
meeting, in which he noted the Sept. 13 date, but did not declare
it as a deadline.
</P>
<P>
   The PCC called on Arafat's government to launch the procedures
toward statehood, although it omitted his earlier threats to
declare statehood unilaterally, which Israeli Prime Minister Ehud
Barak has said would lead to unilateral Israeli decisions. Such
brinkmanship would likely lead to violence.
</P>
<P>
   Palestinians have said repeatedly they have the right in
principle to declare statehood any time after Sept. 13, when a
deadline for reaching a peace accord with Israel expires, with or
without a peace pact.
</P>
<P>
   Before the gathering's conclusion, Arafat aides said action by
year's end was inevitable.
</P>
<P>
   ''A Palestinian state will be declared in the year 2000,'' said
Nabil Shaath, the Palestinian planning minister.
</P>
<P>
   Palestinian officials suggested privately, however, that real
decision-making about a precise date for independence still lay
ahead, and that nothing would be finalized without taking into
account factors like Palestinian public opinion.
</P>
<P>
   Council sources, speaking on condition of anonymity, said Arafat
had quietly asked some council members to study whether the
Palestinian people would be willing to accept delays beyond Sept.
13
</P>
<P>
   Israeli officials have said that a Palestinian declaration of
independence without a peace treaty would prompt Israel to annex
chunks of the West Bank -- a step that would very likely trigger a
violent confrontation.
</P>
<P>
   Barak told the parliamentary Defense and Foreign Affairs
Committee on Monday that in case of a unilateral statehood
declaration, Israel would annex Jewish settlement blocs, and would
militarize parts of the Jordan Valley. That would effectively
rescind Barak's recent offer to hand over the strategic lowlands as
part of a final peace package.
</P>
<P>
   ''We made it clear to the Palestinians quite some time ago that
we do not accept unilateral steps as a mode of action, and if they
take unilateral action we will take immediate unilateral steps of
our own,'' Barak told the committee, according to a partial
transcript released by the parliament's spokesman.
</P>
<P>
   All this could be avoided if the sides reach an agreement by
Sept. 13 -- but that seems out of reach now, with both sides digging
in their heels on the most sensitive negotiation topics: Jerusalem,
borders and refugees.
</P>
<P>
   PCC chairman Zanoun's statement emphasized the tough line
Palestinian negotiators have taken in recent talks with Israel: a
right of return for Palestinian refugees of Israel's 1948
independence and the dismantling of all Jewish settlements in
disputed lands. Israel has adamantly rejected both positions.
</P>
<P>
   The PCC called on the international community to salvage the
peace talks by pressing Israel into compromises. It said a
Palestinian state would ''be a cornerstone for real peace in the
region.''
</P>
<P>
   Both sides say there has been a worrisome increase in tensions
on the ground, particularly in the crowded, impoverished Gaza
Strip.
</P>
<P>
   Israeli commanders have said publicly in recent weeks that the
army will use whatever force is necessary to put down any clashes
in the West Bank and Gaza. That has drawn angry protests from the
Palestinians.
</P>
<P>
   Amid the statehood debate, some Palestinian officials pointed
out that there was much more to statehood than simply declaring it.
</P>
<P>
   ''I call upon my colleagues to work to organize the Palestinian
community, to build a Palestinian economy and to solve social
problems as well as building institutions that are needed in our
state,'' said Nabil Amr, the parliamentary affairs minister.
</P>
<P>
   Arafat has developed a reputation as an authoritarian leader,
and the PCC urged his government to ''respect democracy, the
independence of the judiciary, and freedom of speech.''
</P>
<P>
   The leadership meeting was boycotted by the radical Islamic
group Hamas, which bitterly opposes peace with Israel and has
repeatedly staged suicide bombings in the past to try to stave off
a peace accord.
</P>
<P>
   ''Without an armed struggle, we are wasting time,'' Hamas
spokesman Mahmoud Zahar said in Gaza. ''We believe negotiations
will bring nothing.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
