<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Protestants Vow To Defy Parade Ban  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   BELFAST, Northern Ireland (AP) -- Protesters and police clashed
for a second day Monday, after Northern Ireland's Parades
Commission banned a bitterly divisive Protestant march through a
Catholic neighborhood for the third year running.
</P>
<P>
   The decision to ban the march set for Sunday down the Garvaghy
Road was met with defiance by the Orange Order, the province's
major Protestant group.
</P>
<P>
   ''This is a complete non-runner. Everything goes ahead as
planned,'' said Orange Order spokesman David Jones.
</P>
<P>
   Sporadic protests erupted Monday evening near the Drumcree
Anglican Church, where British security forces for the past two
years have prevented Orangemen from parading past a nearby Catholic
neighborhood.
</P>
<P>
   A group of about 50 people behind the banner of the Ulster
Freedom Fighters -- an outlawed pro-British paramilitary group --
briefly marched to the church, 50 yards from a line of police and
armored British army vehicles blocking the way to Garvaghy Road.
</P>
<P>
   A crowd of several hundred threw rocks and other missiles at the
security forces before police moved in to clear away the
demonstrators.
</P>
<P>
   Later, masked gunmen standing in front of an Ulster Freedom
Fighters banner fired a volley of shots in a Protestant area of
nearby Portadown.
</P>
<P>
   Though banning Sunday's parade, the commission said it might
permit a march on the Garvaghy Road later if members of the Orange
Order stopped protesting and agreed to consult with Catholics in
the divided town of Portadown.
</P>
<P>
   The announcement came a day after Protestants clashed with
police near the Drumcree church, where another Orange march was
stopped from going down the Garvaghy Road. Seven police officers
suffered minor injuries.
</P>
<P>
   ''The decision is fundamentally flawed and allows Garvaghy Road
residents to sit on their hands and do nothing,'' Orange Order
spokesman Jones said.
</P>
<P>
   He said the decision created a void that could be ''easily
filled in this country by people becoming violent -- although we
will do our best to prevent and discourage that -- but our
credibility has been reduced by this decision.''
</P>
<P>
   ''The onus is fairly and squarely on the Orange Order and the
events which the Orange Order carry out on the streets of Portadown
and elsewhere in the province this week,'' said Breandan Mac
Cionnaith, who has led protests by Garvaghy Road residents.
</P>
<P>
   The Portadown march, which commemorates the Battle of the Somme
in World War I, has caused violence whether or not police have
permitted the Orangemen to parade. Police forced Catholic
protesters off the road in 1996 and 1997, provoking riots in many
Catholic areas, but have banned the parade route since 1998,
triggering Protestant disturbances.
</P>
<P>
   The Parades Commission said the march could be allowed in three
to eight months if the Orange Order complied with the decision,
stopped protests at Drumcree and opened talks with Catholic
residents.
</P>
<P>
   The commission would then look to Garvaghy Road residents to
show ''that they were genuine in seeking a long-term resolution of
the intercommunal tensions in Portadown by taking steps to
facilitate the proposed parades.''
</P>
<P>
   The Orange Order, a hard-line fraternal group founded near
Portadown in the 1790s, remains influential today, particularly
over its opposition to Northern Ireland's 2-year-old peace accord.
Tens of thousands of Orangemen march each July, often to celebrate
17th-century military victories over Catholics.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
