<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Multi-tribe powow celebrates peace, all warriors  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   AURIESVILLE, N.Y. (AP) - At least nine tribes including the
Mohawks, Onondaga, Sioux, Incas and Aztecs celebrated culture,
peace and warriors in an annual powow.
</P>
<P>
   Hundreds gathered at the fifth annual powwow in honor of Kateri
Tekakwitha over the weekend at the Auriesville Shrine 35 miles
northwest of Albany to see tribal dances, Indian crafts and taste
native American cuisine.
</P>
<P>
   Known as ''Lily of the Mohawks,'' Tekakwitha was born near
Auriesville in 1656 and established many Native American ministries
in Catholic churches throughout the United States and Canada, said
Bob Ross, powwow coordinator. The Catholic church is in the process
of canonizing Tekakwitha.
</P>
<P>
   Participants representing at least nine tribes performed
ceremonial dances in a roped off area known as ''The Circle.''
Before the dancers could go into The Circle they had to be smudged
with the smoke of burning sage to cleanse and rid them of any
negative energy.
</P>
<P>
   One of the dances performed was in honor of veterans, not only
Indians, but veterans of all wars, including World War I, World War
II, The Korean War, Vietnam, and Desert Storm.
</P>
<P>
   ''We are the only people who sing and dance to honor our
warriors,'' Ross told The Daily Gazette of Schenectady.
</P>
<P>
   Cathy Hauh Ha Chaun (One Who Weeps), an Apache from Yardley,
Pa., wore an intricate bead necklace that was once her
mother-in-law's, a turtle shell necklace, and a hair clip fastened
by the quill of a porcupine. She also carried a fan made from red
tail hawk feathers.
</P>
<P>
   ''We do this to keep our heritage alive and so people remember
us,'' Hauh Ha Chaun said.
</P>
<P>
   She said powwows are held all over the country during the summer
months. She and her husband Bart Standing Elk, a Delaware Indian,
travel around from powwow to powwow dancing and enjoying the
festivities. ''It helps us to see people,'' she said. ''It's like
family.''
</P>
<P>
   The powwows ''allow us to share our culture and music,'' said
Jassier Cabrera, a member of the Inca tribe from Otabalo, Ecuador.
''It's educational.''
</P>
<P>
   ''I respect their culture and I like the music,'' said Carolyn
LaVare of Schenectady, of Irish descent. LaVare brought her
grandchildren to the festival so ''they learn to enjoy and respect
other cultures.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-07-03-00 2013 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000703.0142 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-03 20:19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Reds 3, Diamondbacks 2  </HEADLINE>
By MEL REISNER
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX (AP) -- Brian Anderson lost at home for the first time in
1&AMP;frac12; years, and Alex Ochoa homered Monday as the Cincinnati Reds won
consecutive games for the first time in nearly a month, beating the
Arizona Diamondbacks 3-2.
</P>
<P>
   Steve Parris (4-11) won on the road for the first time since
April 16, striking out a season-high six in 6 2-3 innings. Parris,
who allowed one run and seven hits, had been 0-5 in seven road
starts since beating Los Angeles on April 16 at Dodger Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   Parris' 11 losses already are the most by a Reds' right-hander
since Jay Tibbs went 10-16 in 1985. Danny Graves, Cincinnati's
third pitcher, got three outs for his 13th save in 14 chances.
</P>
<P>
   Cincinnati had not won consecutive games since a three-game
sweep of Minnesota on June 2-4. The Reds are 9-1 at Arizona and
16-6 over the Diamondbacks overall.
</P>
<P>
   Anderson (8-3) lost at home for the first time in 20 starts
since Sept. 18, 1998, stopping a 12-game winning streak. He gave up
three runs and eight hits in 6 1-3 innings.
</P>
<P>
   Dante Bichette drove in Cincinnati's first run with a
first-inning sacrifice fly, and Benito Santiago had an RBI single
in the seventh, stopping an 0-for-9 skid.
</P>
<P>
   Ochoa, who had three hits and three RBIs Sunday in his first
start since May 26, hit a line drive into the left-field stands
with one out in the fifth, his fourth homer of the season.
</P>
<P>
   Arizona got its run on RBI singles by Tony Womack in the
seventh, which chased Parris, and Greg Colbrunn in the ninth off
Danny Graves.
</P>
<P>
Notes: Arizona manager Buck Showalter is budgeting extra time in
the rotation , anticipating an All-star appearance for Randy
Johnson, scheduled for starts Tuesday and Sunday. ... The Reds
haven't had a complete game in 82 games this season. The previous
team record for consecutive games at the season's start without one
was set in 1997, when Dave Burba got one in their 81st game.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-07-03-00 2019 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000703.0143 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-03 20:24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Gore Touts 'Real' Prescription Plan  </HEADLINE>
By MIKE GLOVER
<TEXT>
<P>
   ST. LOUIS (AP) -- Vice President Al Gore courted senior citizens
and Hispanics Monday, touting his plan for a ''real,
comprehensive'' prescription drug benefit as a stark contrast to
the proposals of rival George W. Bush.
</P>
<P>
   ''We'll put the power of medical science back in the medicine
cabinets of our mothers and fathers,'' Gore said of his Medicare
benefits plan. ''It's the right thing to do.''
</P>
<P>
   Gore, speaking in the suburb of Clayton at a town hall-style
meeting with senior citizens, also took on the big drug companies,
accusing them of ''price gouging.'' And he criticized the
Republicans' drug bill now pending in Congress, saying it was put
together by the drug companies and ''its only purpose is to serve
as an illusion or camouflage.''
</P>
<P>
   Accompanying the vice president was House Democratic leader Dick
Gephardt of St. Louis, who said the cost of drugs could be a
decisive matter in both the presidential election and the fight for
control of Congress.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's a huge, huge issue to senior citizens,'' said Gephardt.
</P>
<P>
   The Republicans have received more than $3 million from drug
manufacturers, while the Democrats have gotten just over $700,000,
Gore aides said campaign finance records showed.
</P>
<P>
   The proposal Gore has offered would provide a prescription drug
benefit under the Medicare program, with the government paying half
of the annual costs up to $5,000. Aides said it would extend
coverage to 40 million people at a cost of $255 billion over 10
years. Gore had explained details of the proposal earlier, but was
hammering hard at his plan in the battleground state of Missouri.
</P>
<P>
   He said many senior citizens have to choose between buying drugs
or going without other necessities. ''We just should not be putting
our seniors in that position,'' he said. ''It's just not right.''
</P>
<P>
   Later, Gore flew to San Diego to pitch the proposal to the
National Council of La Raza, an important Hispanic group. Gore said
Hispanics would benefit under the plan.
</P>
<P>
   In remarks prepared for delivery, Gore said 2 million Hispanics
would gain because the number eligible for Medicare was expected to
triple over the next 25 years. Further, Hispanics are more than
twice as likely to lack supplemental coverage for prescription
drugs, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ''I'm committed to a real prescription drug benefit for all
Hispanics who rely on Medicare,'' Gore said. ''Not one that tells
them to go beg the HMOs and the insurance companies for help.''
</P>
<P>
   Aides said the vice president would focus on the prescription
drug proposal and health care throughout the week, including in
separate appearances before two big teachers' unions.
</P>
<P>
   Bush was addressing the National Council of La Raza on
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier in the day, Sen. Bob Graham, a Florida Democrat, made a
Gore-arranged conference call to reporters to criticize Bush for
offering minimal details about what he would provide in financing
for prescription drug aid to senior citizens.
</P>
<P>
   ''I think the American people deserve to have a clear statement
by Governor Bush as to what he would propose to do,'' said Graham,
sometimes mentioned as a vice presidential possibility for Gore.
</P>
<P>
   Bush campaign spokesman Dan Bartlett said Bush has been
consistent in proposing to allocate $5 trillion over five years to
both save and strengthen Social Security and Medicare, also
providing prescription drug benefits.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans also said Gore, as vice president, should have
spoken up much earlier if he thought the issue was so important.
</P>
<P>
   ''After eight years of failing to propose a solution, the vice
president is calling for reform,'' said Missouri Rep. James Talent.
</P>
<P>
   Gore said his plan would cover far more people than a more
modest bill backed in Congress by Republicans. He also said his
plan is best because it includes coverage under Medicare, while
Republicans rely on insurance companies to provide the coverage.
</P>
<P>
   At the Missouri campaign stop, 72-year-old Jacqueline Steele
Johnson said she spends $423 of her monthly $870 income on
prescription drugs. She said she eats macaroni and cheese every
day.
</P>
<P>
   Gore also used his appearance for spirited criticism of big drug
makers, the second straight week he has taken on a large and
unpopular industry. Gore spent much of last week bashing big oil
companies over the soaring price of gasoline.
</P>
<P>
   ''They are price gouging and you are paying the bill,'' Gore
said of the drug makers. ''There's no other industry in America
that has profits nearly as high.''
</P>
<P>
   There was something of a vice presidential buzz surrounding
Gore's swing with Gephardt.
</P>
<P>
   ''We haven't talked about that,'' Gephardt said when questioned.
''As Harry Truman once said, I don't answer iffy questions.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
