<HEADLINE> Former Comedian Sentenced for Rape  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   OMAHA, Neb. (AP) -- A former ''Star Search'' comedian accused in
a string of sexual assaults on college campuses in the Midwest was
sentenced Monday to 25 to 30 years in prison for one of the rapes.
</P>
<P>
   Vincent Horace Champ had pleaded no contest to the 1997 rape of
a University of Nebraska at Omaha faculty member.
</P>
<P>
   The sentence will be served after Champ, 38, completes a 40-year
term given to him last month for the rape of a student at Union
College, in Lincoln, in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   Champ, a former comedian on the college circuit, still faces two
potential life sentences in Iowa on rape charges, and an attempted
assault charge stemming from an attack at Pasadena City College in
California.
</P>
<P>
   Similar attacks were reported at Knox College in Galesburg,
Ill.; Carthage College in Kenosha, Wis.; and Augustana College in
Rock Island, Ill. No charges have been brought in those cases.
</P>
<P>
   Champ used to open for entertainers such as Diana Ross, Sinbad
and Arsenio Hall. He also appeared on the syndicated TV talent show
''Star Search.''
</P>
</TEXT>
