<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 6 More Anti-Navy Activists Detained  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN JUAN, Puerto Rico (AP) -- U.S. marshals detained six more
anti-Navy activists Monday, bringing to 56 the number of Puerto
Rican protesters jailed for failing to post bail on trespassing
charges.
</P>
<P>
   The arrests included two mayoral candidates in November
elections, Hector Diaz of northern Arecibo and Charles Escobares of
the mountain town of Adjuntas, protest organizers said.
</P>
<P>
   Officials from the U.S. Marshals Service and the U.S. Attorney's
office did not return calls for comment Monday.
</P>
<P>
   The 56 are among 183 people arrested in recent days while trying
to enter a U.S. Navy bombing range on the island of Vieques in an
attempt to stop military exercises. They were released and given
until Friday to post $1,000 bail, but 122 have refused to pay.
</P>
<P>
   Since Friday, U.S. marshals have been arresting them at their
homes across the U.S. Caribbean territory.
</P>
<P>
   Resentment over the Navy's presence in Vieques flared in April
1999, when a U.S. Marine Corps jet dropped a bomb off target and
killed a civilian security guard in the bombing range.
</P>
<P>
   Protesters occupied the range for nearly a year, preventing
further exercises until authorities forcibly removed them on May 4.
In all, about 600 protesters have been detained on the island.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
