<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Jewish Memorial Defaced in Latvia  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   RIGA, Latvia (AP) -- Vandals painted swastikas and other
anti-Semitic graffiti Monday on the remains of a Riga synagogue
that had been burned down by the Nazis during World War II.
</P>
<P>
   Police confirmed that the graffiti was discovered Monday, a day
before Latvia holds its nationwide Holocaust commemoration.
</P>
<P>
   On July 4, 1941, the Nazi army torched Riga's central synagogue,
burning to death dozens of Jews trapped inside. The stone remains
of the building, now overgrown with grass and weeds, were left
standing as a memorial.
</P>
<P>
   Police have no suspects.
</P>
<P>
   Latvia and its Baltic Sea neighbors, Estonia and Lithuania, were
overrun by the Soviet Union, then Nazi Germany during World War II,
and suffered mightily at the hands of both.
</P>
<P>
   After annexing the country in 1940, the Soviets deported
thousands of Latvians to Siberia, where many were shot. The Nazis
occupied Latvia from 1941 to 1944 and murdered nearly 80,000 Jews,
with Latvians as well as Germans taking part in the killings.
</P>
<P>
   The Red Army returned in 1945, deporting thousands more and
staying until the Baltic states won independence in 1991.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-07-03-00 2051 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000703.0149 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-03 20:57 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Pakistan Ruler Discusses Democracy  </HEADLINE>
By AMIR ZIA
<TEXT>
<P>
   ISLAMABAD, Pakistan (AP) -- For the first time since seizing
power nine months ago, Pakistan's army ruler met the country's
disgraced politicians Monday to discuss a return to democracy.
</P>
<P>
   Gen. Pervez Musharraf met members of deposed prime minister
Nawaz Sharif's Pakistan Muslim League, as well as a dissident
faction.
</P>
<P>
   He also met Fazle-ur Rehman, who leads the ultraorthodox Jamiat
Ulema-e-Islam, a big supporter of the hardline Islamic Taliban
rulers in neighboring Afghanistan.
</P>
<P>
   There also were reports of a meeting between Musharraf and
members of ousted prime minister Benazir Bhutto's party.
</P>
<P>
   Raja Zafar-ul Haq, acting head of Sharif's party, said that
Musharraf -- the man who overthrew Sharif's elected government last
October -- has a plan to return the country to democracy.
</P>
<P>
   Haq, however, refused to give details of the plan, saying he
will take Musharraf's proposals to his party leadership to decide
whether they will participate.
</P>
<P>
   There was no immediate comment from Musharraf or other members
of his regime.
</P>
<P>
   Previously Musharraf said he would return Pakistan to democratic
rule in three years, in keeping with a ruling by the Supreme Court.
But before general elections are held, Musharraf said he wants to
revive the economy, implement electoral reform and root out
corruption.
</P>
<P>
   Musharraf has set up an anti-corruption commission, ordered a
survey to document the country's economy and made inroads against
smuggling, a multibillion dollar business in Pakistan.
</P>
<P>
   The Supreme Court also gave Musharraf the authority to amend the
constitution. Musharraf is expected to revise the constitution to
institutionalize the military's involvement in running the country
allowing civilian rule.
</P>
<P>
   Musharraf has accused many of Pakistan's former rulers of
corruption and has said many will not be allowed to return to
politics.
</P>
<P>
   Sharif is currently in jail convicted of hijacking and terrorism
and sentenced to concurrent life terms. He is appealing his
conviction.
</P>
<P>
   Sharif and several of his family members and close associates
also face charges of corruption and abuse of power.
</P>
<P>
   Haq said he complained to Musharraf that Sharif has been badly
treated in prison, often kept in handcuffs and denied basic
amenities.
</P>
<P>
   Sheikh Rashid, a former minister in Sharif's cabinet, called
Musharraf's meetings with the politicians an ''icebreaker.''
</P>
<P>
   ''We hope the process will continue and pave the way for the
return of democracy,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-07-03-00 2057 </TRAILER>
