<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China 2, Canada 1  </HEADLINE>
By JOSEPH WHITE
<TEXT>
<P>
   FOXBORO, Mass. (AP) -- Qiu Haiyan, taking advantage of a moment
of confusion in front of the goal, scored in the 73rd minute Monday
night to give China a 2-1 victory over Canada in the third-place
game of the women's Gold Cup.
</P>
<P>
   Qiu got the fortuitous bounce after Pan Lina chipped a long ball
into the box. Canadian goalkeeper Nicole Wright was late coming off
the line, and the ball caromed among Wright and teammates Amy Wash
and Breanna Boyd before landing at Qiu's foot for the easy shot and
her second goal of the tournament.
</P>
<P>
   Jin Yan scored in the 42nd minute for China. Charmaine Hooper
tied it with a penalty kick in the 59th minute as Canada gave the
World Cup runner-up a surprisingly stiff challenge for the third
time this year.
</P>
<P>
   The match effectively ended Canada's major tournament play for
the year, although the team showed impressive progress under new
coach Even Pellerud. Canada defeated China on penalty kicks after a
2-2 tie in the Pacific Cup in Australia last month and lost 3-2 to
China in Gold Cup group play last week.
</P>
<P>
   The Canadians didn't qualify for the Olympic Games, but they
will give the United States one of its final Sydney tuneups on Aug.
20 in Kansas City.
</P>
<P>
   The third-place finish for China reflects another disappointment
in its buildup to the Olympics. The Chinese finished third in the
Algarve Cup in Portugal in March and second in the Pacific Cup.
</P>
<P>
   Shui Qingxia, filling the playmaker's role in place of injured
midfielder Sun Wen, set up China's first goal with a nice feed to
Jin on the left side. Wright was unable to cut off the angle, and
Jin outraced a defender and left-footed the ball into the net for
her fourth goal of the tournament.
</P>
<P>
   Hooper tied the game after she was tripped in the box by Bae
Jie. Hooper then converted the spot kick, her sixth goal of the
tournament.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-07-03-00 2104 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000703.0152 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-03 21:04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Lazio starts his second 'Mainstream Express' bus tour  </HEADLINE>
By FRANK ELTMAN
<TEXT>
<P>
   YONKERS, N.Y. (AP) - On the road, again.
</P>
<P>
   Republican Senate candidate Rick Lazio fired up his second
''Mainstream Express'' statewide bus tour on Monday, visiting a
health care facility on Long Island before heading to rallies in
Yonkers and Schenectady.
</P>
<P>
   The congressman wasted no time in launching into an attack on
rival Hillary Rodham Clinton, referring to himself as a ''leader in
the House'' on cancer legislation while calling his opponent's
''one foray into policy on health care ... an unmitigated
disaster.''
</P>
<P>
   When asked if he was trying to steal one of Clinton's favorite
issues - health care - Lazio said he has a record of
accomplishments, while his opponent's record is dismal. ''I mean
you can say anything you want on the campaign trail,'' Lazio said.
''You've got to look at what people have done.''
</P>
<P>
   He added: ''Compare what Mrs. Clinton did when she had the
opportunity, which was to create a monstrosity that would have
limited choices, and would have undermined our ability to deliver
quality health care, and what I have been doing.''
</P>
<P>
   The Clinton campaign fired back: ''Carefully staged photo ops
won't change the fact that Rick Lazio has committed legislative
malpractice,'' said spokesman Howard Wolfson.
</P>
<P>
   He said Lazio ''voted against a real patient's bill of rights,
against a prescription drug plan that will cover all seniors, and
voted to cut Medicare by $270 billion.''
</P>
<P>
   Before departing from his home turf on Long Island, Lazio, the
chairman of the House's ''Cancer Awareness Working Group,'' called
for a ''comprehensive strategy on all cancers, including breast
cancer.''
</P>
<P>
   He called on President Clinton to sign the ''Breast and Cervical
Cancer Treatment Act,'' which would provide treatment to low-income
patients.
</P>
<P>
   Lazio stayed on the health care theme later Monday, visiting
Good Samaritan Hospital in Suffern.
</P>
<P>
   The tour, featuring a pair of luxury buses with out-of-state
license plates, is Lazio's second since receiving the state
Republican party nomination for the Senate in late May. Lazio
entered the race on May 20 after New York Mayor Rudolph Giuliani
dropped out as the GOP candidate, citing his battle with prostate
cancer.
</P>
<P>
   The five-day tour winds through the Adirondacks, then south to
Syracuse and west to Buffalo before ending Friday afternoon in
Rochester. The Long Island congressman, who is seeking to raise his
visibility in upstate New York, was traveling with his wife, Pat,
and two young daughters, Molly and Kelsey.
</P>
<P>
   At a rally attended by about 100 people in a Yonkers park, Lazio
repeated one of the mantras of his six-week-old campaign: Clinton
is the outsider and he's the ''real New Yorker.''
</P>
<P>
   ''I didn't need an exploratory committee to find ... (your city
here; in this case Yonkers),'' he said moments before a disc jockey
fired up Ray Charles' version of ''What'd I Say?'' including the
line:
</P>
<P>
   ''Tell your momma, tell your pa, gonna ship you back to
Arkansas.''
</P>
<P>
   A small turnout also greeted Lazio for a rally in a Schenectady
park early Monday night. Lazio repeated the exploratory committee
line for the benefit of the locals and pressed his criticism of
Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   ''If this race is based on character, honesty and integrity, I
think we win this race handily,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Lazio plans to spend Tuesday marching in three July Fourth
parades in the northern New York towns of Argyle in Washington
County, and Ticonderoga and Lake Placid, both in Essex County. He
also will participate in a ''Salute to Korean War Veterans''
breakfast in Saratoga Springs.
</P>
</TEXT>
