<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Amateur historians say Thomas Jefferson kin buried in Orange County </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   TUXEDO, N.Y. (AP) - A town will hire another historian to
research whether the child of Thomas Jefferson and his slave
mistress rests in a local cemetery.
</P>
<P>
   The new historian is needed after a bizarre news conference over
the weekend in which the hired researcher apparently disappeared in
the middle of the event billed to release evidence of the
relationship.
</P>
<P>
   Roger A. King, of Monroe was hired to study the cemetery for the
town last summer. King has said that the cemetery in Southfields
contains the grave of a son of founding father Jefferson and Sally
Hemings, his slave mistress.
</P>
<P>
   But when a group of reporters and officials gathered at the
cemetery Saturday so King could reveal the missing half of a
tombstone said to link Jefferson and Hemings, King was nowhere to
be found.
</P>
<P>
   ''I'm very concerned that this whole thing is a fake,'' said
Christian Sonne, the town's historian, who was only informed of the
find last Thursday by a reporter.
</P>
<P>
   ''I have no physical evidence. I'm going to do everything to get
an independent expert on this case,'' he told the Middletown Times
Herald-Record.
</P>
<P>
   Town Supervisor Kenneth Magar said that additional research
needs to be done on the cemetery, which contains the ancestors of
many local families, to satisfy the community.
</P>
<P>
   ''The town needs a second opinion, a view from a different
angle,'' said Magar. ''Before the town gets too involved, we need
to make sure the information is completely accurate.''
</P>
<P>
   King was outraged over reports that he left Saturday's press
conference before presenting crucial evidence: a tombstone that
reads, ''Thomas Jefferson ... son of Thomas Jefferson and Sally
Heming.'' (sic)
</P>
<P>
   ''I did not disappear,'' said King. ''I am very, very upset
about what was put in the paper.''
</P>
<P>
   After briefing a crowd of some 30 residents, local officials and
members of the press, for about 45 minutes, King was nowhere to be
found.
</P>
<P>
   According to King, he was being interviewed by a reporter for an
hour and a half, and then headed over to the nearby cemetery, which
he says was empty. King says he spent the remainder of the day
swimming.
</P>
<P>
   The reporter King referred to was unidentified.
</P>
<P>
   No one at the restaurant remembers seeing King after his speech,
nor do they remember seeing a reporter.
</P>
<P>
   However, one restaurant employee said King left shortly after
the crowd headed to the nearby cemetery, where the tombstone is
said to lie. Some returned to the restaurant in search of King, but
none recall seeing him. The press and local officials were left
waiting at the cemetery until well after 3 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   King's absence triggered speculation among some that he may have
the stone in his possession. But King said, ''No stone has been
taken away from the cemetery, and there is nothing that has been
tampered with.''
</P>
<P>
   Yesterday, he could not be reached for comment on his criminal
record.
</P>
<P>
   In November, a DNA study concluded that a ''Jefferson male'' -
not necessarily Thomas - was the father of Eston Hemings, the
slave's youngest son. In January, the Thomas Jefferson Memorial
Foundation acknowledged that Jefferson is the likely father of one,
if not all six, of Hemings' children.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-07-03-00 2107 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
