<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Guatemala Civil War Victims Found  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   GUATEMALA CITY (AP) -- Investigators uncovered the bodies of 12
Indian peasants killed during Guatemala's 36-year civil war, in the
seventh excavation this year of clandestine cemeteries in the
highlands of western Guatemala.
</P>
<P>
   Monday's find brought to 65 the number of victims pulled from
hidden graves this year in the mountainous Guatemalan state of
Quiche.
</P>
<P>
   The cemetery, in the village of Carrigal about 100 miles
northwest of Guatemala City, contained the remains of nine men and
three woman, said Jose Suasnauar, a spokesman for the Forensic
Anthropological Foundation of Guatemala, which conducted the
excavation.
</P>
<P>
   The foundation received witness accounts telling them where to
dig from the Guatemala City-based human rights group Coordination
of Guatemalan Widows.
</P>
<P>
   ''We have so much information about the area that we can't use
it all, even now when we are doing an excavation a month,''
Suasnauar said.
</P>
<P>
   Suasnauar said the bodies belonged to adults between 20 and 55.
They were shot dead between 1980 and 1984 with the kinds of weapons
carried by Guatemalan soldiers, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Guatemala's civil war, which pitted leftist Indian guerrillas
against hard-line state forces, began in 1960 and ended with
December 1996 peace accords -- but not before some 200,000 people --
mostly Indian peasants -- had been killed.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-07-03-00 2113 </TRAILER>
