<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-03 21:24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Iowa Gov. Offers Gas Price Plan  </HEADLINE>
By KEN THOMAS
<TEXT>
<P>
   DES MOINES, Iowa (AP) -- Besieged with howls of protest over
sky-high gas prices, Gov. Tom Vilsack on Monday suggested
reimbursing Iowa drivers $10 each for their purchases of
ethanol-blended gasoline.
</P>
<P>
   Vilsack proposed reimbursing drivers for the 19-cents-a-gallon
tax on 53 gallons of ethanol-blended fuel, also known as gasohol.
It would cost the state an estimated $14 million.
</P>
<P>
   ''This is a way of tailoring and targeting the relief to Iowans
and at the same time promoting Iowa's product -- ethanol -- and
renewable fuels, which we think, in the long-run, is the way we
avoid being held hostage by high gas prices in the future,''
Vilsack said.
</P>
<P>
   If approved by state lawmakers, $10 reimbursement coupons could
be sent to consumers this summer.
</P>
<P>
   Parts of the Midwest, including Iowa, have battled soaring
gasoline prices in recent months. On Monday, the average cost of a
gallon of regular unleaded was $1.73, up from $1.54 a month ago and
$1.07 a year ago, according to the American Automobile Association.
</P>
<P>
   Illinois legislators voted last week to suspend the sales tax on
gas for six months. Indiana Gov. Frank O'Bannon suspended his
state's gas tax for 60 days and asked station owners to pass the
savings on to customers.
</P>
<P>
   Vilsack, a Democrat, met with lawmakers last week to try to
forge a plan to help Iowa consumers. Both sides agreed that
something must be done, but said they needed more time to develop a
solution.
</P>
<P>
   In seeking a plan for Iowa, some have suggested a two-month
suspension of the gas tax, a move that would pare $65 million to
$100 million from the state's road-use fund.
</P>
<P>
   However, leaders of the Republican-controlled Legislature worry
about the possible harm to the state's highway maintenance efforts.
They have countered with a plan to suspend the tax on
ethanol-blended fuels, about 40 percent of the market.
</P>
<P>
   The GOP plan would call for the state to make up for the lost
gas taxes by using the state's budget surplus.
</P>
<P>
   The governor's plan would be funded with $14 million from the
state's road-use tax fund. Vilsack said he plans to discuss the
proposal with legislative leaders on Wednesday.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-07-03-00 2124 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000703.0159 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-03 21:25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Truce Proposals in Colombia  </HEADLINE>
By CESAR GARCIA
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN VICENTE DEL CAGUAN, Colombia (AP) -- Colombia's largest rebel
group denounced a government ''defamation'' campaign Monday even as
the two sides exchanged proposals for a truce in a 36-year
conflict.
</P>
<P>
   The leftist Revolutionary Armed Forces of Colombia said it was
tired of officials labeling the group as ''bandits'' and
''terrorists'' while the government pledges sincerity about peace.
</P>
<P>
   ''The persistent defamation campaign by officials against the
FARC must end if we are to achieve positive results at the
negotiating table,'' said an angry statement read by FARC
negotiator Raul Reyes in the village of Los Pozos.
</P>
<P>
   Reyes claimed the government tried to discredit the group at a
rebel-hosted conference in Los Pozos last week -- in part by urging
delegates from 21 countries to criticize Revolutionary Armed Forces
kidnappings and ties to the drug trade.
</P>
<P>
   He lashed out in particular at top military officials and
presidential peace envoy Camilo Gomez, saying Gomez was acting like
a ''troublemaker.''
</P>
<P>
   The rebel group's statement, and the meager results of Monday's
cease-fire exchange, did little to raise hopes of peace in the
strife-torn South American nation. Negotiations begun 18 months ago
are moving slowly.
</P>
<P>
   Emerging from a six-hour meeting in Los Pozos, the sides pledged
only to carefully study the truce offers -- contained in sealed
envelopes and kept secret from the public.
</P>
<P>
   Acts of peace will occur only ''when the negotiations advance,''
said a joint rebel-government statement.
</P>
<P>
   Tensions have been on the rise since U.S. lawmakers approved
$1.3 billion in aid last week, mostly to train and supply Colombian
troops who are set to confront rebels protecting wide swathes of
drug-producing regions.
</P>
<P>
   They apparently flared further at last week's conference on
illegal drug crops, at which the rebel group took unexpected
criticism from its mostly European guests.
</P>
<P>
   Rebel and government negotiators said Monday they would keep the
cease-fire proposals under wraps for now. But some of the likely
differences have surfaced.
</P>
<P>
   FARC commander Alfonso Cano said the rebel proposal would impose
short-term cease-fires in well-defined regions and no international
monitors. ''This is an internal affair,'' Cano said.
</P>
<P>
   A Colombian lawmaker disagreed.
</P>
<P>
   ''A cease-fire needs a mechanism of verification and hopefully
this would be linked to the international community,'' Nancy
Patricia Gutierrez, president of the House of Representatives, told
RCN radio.
</P>
<P>
   Gomez, the presidential envoy, said the government proposal
called for a cease-fire and an end to rebel kidnappings and attacks
against civilians.
</P>
<P>
   FARC leaders have said they would consider halting kidnappings
as a means of raising funds only if the government financed the
rebel group. They also doubt the government would be able to
control right-wing paramilitary squads that could scuttle any peace
agreement.
</P>
<P>
   Foreign governments -- who are being asked to fund development
projects to support the peace process -- are demanding both sides
cut back on atrocities.
</P>
<P>
   ''The most important thing now is to stop the senseless killing
of civilians, to stop the massacres and stop the kidnappings and
then go toward a more wide-ranging cease-fire agreement,'' U.N.
peace envoy for Colombia, Jan Egeland of Norway, told The
Associated Press last week.
</P>
<P>
   Roughly 3,000 people are killed annually in the 36-year
conflict, the majority villagers accused by rebels or rival
paramilitary groups of supporting the opposing side.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-07-03-00 2125 </TRAILER>
