<HEADLINE> URGENT  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   UTICA, N.Y. (AP) - The mayor of Utica who has been fighting
allegations of sexual harassment by two former and two current male
city employees announced his resignation late Monday.
</P>
<P>
   ''I am not quitting,'' longtime Mayor Edward A. Hanna said in a
written statement. ''But I am forced because of my serious heart
condition along with my age, the execution of and stress in the
regular routine as mayor, regretfully it is strictly a health
decision to bring my work as mayor to a close, effective midnight,
July 3.''
</P>
<P>
   Hanna, 78, a Republican self-made millionaire who funds his own
campaigns, has never minced words in his often-stormy political
career. Two years ago he referred to his own city council as a
''childish collection of mindless babblers who act without any
coherent or cogent vision for this city.''
</P>
<P>
   ''As some already know, I have had chest pains which have
occurred more frequently during the past months,'' Hanna said.
</P>
<P>
   The sexual harassment allegations were contained in sworn
notices of claim served in June against Hanna and the city of
Utica.
</P>
<P>
   In the notices of claim, the four claimants allege their
employment was tied to their responses to the mayor's advances.
</P>
<P>
   ''I would hope to be remembered as a mayor who had eyes that
could see what needed to be done and a heart that cared,'' Hanna
said.
</P>
<P>
   Timothy Julian, common council president, will assume mayoral
duties.
</P>
</TEXT>
