<DOCNO> APW20000703.0170 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-03 22:32 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chavez Raises Minimum Wage 20 Perc.  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   CARACAS, Venezuela (AP) -- President Hugo Chavez increased the
minimum wage for Venezuelan workers in the private sector by 20
percent to $210 a week.
</P>
<P>
   The increase, approved by presidential decree on Monday, equals
the minimum pay approved for state workers in May.
</P>
<P>
   The increase is expected to benefit nearly 40 percent of workers
in Venezuela, where more than 7 million workers work for private
businesses, according to the country's largest workers group, the
Confederation of Venezuelan Workers.
</P>
<P>
   The decree, signed weeks ahead of July 30 presidential
elections, also calls for a 60-day firing freeze, effective
immediately.
</P>
<P>
   The decision came after weeks of negotiations between
government, union, and business leaders, who reached an initial
agreement on Thursday, but failed to resolve the nagging issue of a
firing freeze.
</P>
<P>
   Although Venezuela is the third-largest oil exporter in the
world, more than half the country lives in poverty. The official
unemployment rate is 15 percent, though private economists put the
rate at closer to 20 percent.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-07-03-00 2232 </TRAILER>
