<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-03 22:43 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Denmark Guard Decries Concert Deaths  </HEADLINE>
By JAN M. OLSEN
<TEXT>
<P>
   COPENHAGEN, Denmark (AP) -- A security guard Monday criticized
the handling of a deadly crush of fans at a Pearl Jam concert,
saying the music should have been stopped earlier to prevent the
deaths of eight people.
</P>
<P>
   Per Johansen, who was one of 60 security personnel stationed
near the stage barrier to control the crowds, said too many people
had to approve the decision, and a full 15 minutes elapsed between
the time people started falling and the music stopped.
</P>
<P>
   ''If the music doesn't stop, they'll die,'' Johansen recalled
shouting to the leader of the security group, which was in a pit
between the festival's main stage and the crowd.
</P>
<P>
   Johansen told the Ekstra Bladet newspaper that he then shouted
that those who had fallen in the mud ''are dying now.''
</P>
<P>
   Eight people suffocated Friday night when they were caught up in
a crush of fans pressing closer to the stage just before midnight
as Pearl Jam was playing on the main stage at the popular Roskilde
festival.
</P>
<P>
   Twenty-five people were injured and a 22-year-old Australian man
remained hospitalized in serious condition, but his injuries were
not life-threatening, police said.
</P>
<P>
   The grounds at the annual festival near Roskilde, for which
74,000 tickets were sold, were muddy from an all-day rain when the
tragedy occurred.
</P>
<P>
   Johansen told Danish public radio that he asked the security
chief in the pit three times to stop the music. Finally, that
person, whom Johansen didn't identify, put the request to the stage
security person, who then contacted the office and finally got hold
of the U.S. band's manager, who interrupted the concert.
</P>
<P>
   Security guards began pulling concert goers over a barrier and
into a corridor set up for photographers and to evacuate people in
emergencies. Some 50,000 people had attended the concert in
Roskilde, 25 miles west of the capital, Copenhagen.
</P>
<P>
   Festival organizers have defended security arrangements but said
they would look into the allegations.
</P>
<P>
   Spokesman Leif Skov said each security guard could not be
expected to have a full overview.
</P>
<P>
   ''Therefore chains of command are necessary,'' he said. ''It's
important that this is investigated.''
</P>
<P>
   Police spokesman Bengt Rungstroem said investigators were
looking into security arrangements, but he had no immediate comment
on the reports.
</P>
<P>
   British bands Oasis and the Pet Shop Boys pulled out of their
Saturday night appearances, but other groups played as scheduled.
The festival ended Sunday when popular Danish band D-A-D lit eight
torches -- one for each victim -- and let them circulate in the crowd
before the Orange Stage.
</P>
<P>
   It was the first major accident at the four-day festival, which
was first held in 1971 and was inspired by the 1969 Woodstock
Festival in upstate New York.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
