<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-03 23:00 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Bruins Sign Sweeney to 3-Year Deal  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON (AP) -- Boston defenseman Don Sweeney, a 12-year veteran
and the team's longest-tenured player, signed a three-year contract
with the Bruins on Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Sweeney, 33, was an unrestricted free agent as of July 1, and
could have signed with any team. Terms were not disclosed.
</P>
<P>
   ''This was not an easy deal to make because there were a lot of
teams that wanted to sign Don,'' Bruins president and general
manager Harry Sinden said. ''He reminds us of what is needed to
have a winning team and we did not want to lose him.''
</P>
<P>
   Sweeney has 44 goals and 180 assists for 224 career points in
832 regular season games.
</P>
<P>
   The Bruins struggled through an injury-marred 1999-2000 season,
missed the playoffs and traded defenseman Ray Bourque, one of the
team's greatest players.
</P>
<P>
   ''I'm looking forward to moving ahead, putting last year behind
us and getting back to where we want to be,'' Sweeney said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-07-03-00 2300 </TRAILER>
