<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-03 23:46 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Embattled Utica mayor resigns, cites heart condition  </HEADLINE>
AP Photo
<TEXT>
<P>
   UTICA, N.Y. (AP) - The mayor of Utica, fighting allegations of
sexual harassment by two former and two current male city
employees, announced his resignation effective Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   ''I am not quitting,'' longtime Mayor Edward A. Hanna said in a
written statement. ''But I am forced because of my serious heart
condition along with my age ... and stress in the regular routine
as mayor (to) bring my work as mayor to a close, effective
midnight, July 3.''
</P>
<P>
   Hanna, 78, a Republican self-made millionaire who funded his own
campaigns, has never minced words in his often-stormy political
career. Two years ago he referred to the city council as a
''childish collection of mindless babblers who act without any
coherent or cogent vision for this city.''
</P>
<P>
   ''As some already know, I have had chest pains which have
occurred more frequently during the past months,'' Hanna stated
Monday night.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier Monday, Hanna announced that he and his wife would take
an unplanned 10-day vacation following a doctor's visit. He
referred to city hall as a ''pressure cooker'' and noted several
medications he now takes daily.
</P>
<P>
   He also released a letter from a physician from 1992 that stated
he had blocked arteries. He noted that he'd taken just five
business days off each year since working as mayor. Hanna served
two mayoral terms in the mid-1970s and was elected comptroller in
the early 1990s then relected mayor in 1995 and again in 1999.
</P>
<P>
   The sexual harassment allegations were contained in sworn
notices of claim served in June against Hanna and the city of
Utica.
</P>
<P>
   In the notices of claim, the four claimants allege their
employment was tied to their responses to the mayor's advances.
</P>
<P>
   At the time, Hanna denied the allegations, calling them part of
a ''cleverly orchestrated conspiracy to extort money, including
political rewards and control.''
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, he spoke of the city's future and his legacy.
</P>
<P>
   ''I would hope to be remembered as a mayor who had eyes that
could see what needed to be done and a heart that cared,'' Hanna
said.
</P>
<P>
   Timothy Julian, common council president, will assume mayoral
duties.
</P>
<P>
   Hanna's colorful career often made headlines statewide and
sometimes nationwide since the son of Lebanese immigrants was first
elected mayor in 1973. In The New York Times Magazine in 1976 he
said: ''The phonies and the fakers and the blue bloods have been
draining this lousy town for too long. It's time for them to wake
up and see this is a new day.'' He made the statement when he was
sworn into office.
</P>
<P>
   He was arrested in the 1970s for breaking into his police
chief's office amid a feud in which he said the police turned Utica
into a ''banana republic.''
</P>
<P>
   A former city hall employee, Ed Byrne, was quoted in The Wall
Street Journal in 1976 as saying: ''Utica is the only city in the
United States where the village idiot got elected mayor.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet Hanna had his supporters, those who swept him to office
twice.
</P>
<P>
   To encourage citizens to feel better about city hall he once
filled the lobby with cocktail tables and chairs with potted trees
nearby. In some of the trees he put mechanical tweeting canaries.
He took the door off the mayor's office and put a sign over his
couch saying ''The Town's Living Room.''
</P>
<P>
   The old manufacturing city of 59,300 people 46 miles east of
Syracuse had a population of about 90,000 in the 1970s, but Rust
Belt pressures led to a long depressed economy. Several initiatives
have sought to revive the economic base and to renovate low-income
sections of the city, initiatives that continue today.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-07-03-00 2346 </TRAILER>
