<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-03 23:48 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Judge Paul G. Hatfield Dies  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   GREAT FALLS, Mont. (AP) -- Senior U.S. District Judge Paul G.
Hatfield, a former senator who in 1979 cast a deciding vote for the
treaties that gave the Panama Canal back to the Central American
country, died Monday. He was 72.
</P>
<P>
   Hatfield apparently suffered a heart attack at his home, the
coroner said.
</P>
<P>
   Appointed to the Senate in 1978 after the death of Sen. Lee
Metcalf, a fellow Montana Democrat, Hatfield served for only a
year. Hatfield was among the last of the undecideds on the Panama
Canal issue, and he did not make up his mind to vote for
ratification until the last moment.
</P>
<P>
   The treaties, which were passionately opposed by many Montanans,
were ratified by a single vote.
</P>
<P>
   Mike Mansfield, the former Senate majority leader from Montana
who at the time was U.S. ambassador to Japan, wrote Hatfield
congratulating him for ''an act of statesmanship and courage on the
part of a new senator under very heavy pressure.'' But Hatfield
paid a heavy price.
</P>
<P>
   Mary McGrory, a national political columnist, described in a
column after the vote how Hatfield, a Korean War veteran, returned
to Montana to speak to his hometown Veterans of Foreign Wars post
in Great Falls a day later -- and was met by boos.
</P>
<P>
   He was dubbed ''Panama Paul.'' A recall petition circulated,
though it was quickly declared invalid by the attorney general. In
the four-way Democratic primary two months after the vote, Hatfield
got only 19 percent of the vote to 65 percent for Max Baucus, now
in his fourth term in the Senate.
</P>
<P>
   The following year, he was appointed to the federal bench by
President Carter. He served as U.S. district judge for 17 years
before taking senior status -- the equivalent of retirement for
federal judges, a status that left him with a limited caseload.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-07-03-00 2348 </TRAILER>
